<HEADLINE>
FT  13 MAY 91 / Survey of Cardiff (1): Hard times at bay - The recession has
crept into the service sector, as well as manufacturing. And while the city
waits for an improvement in the economy, a programme to redevelop its
decaying docklands has recently suffered a setback in parliament.
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ANTHONY MORETON
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
SINCE THE middle of last week, the centre of Cardiff has been bedecked with
bunting and flags - the blue flag of the European Community, with its 12
yellow stars, vying for place of honour with the red, white and green Welsh
dragon.
It is Europe Week in the Welsh capital, a festival launched to place the
city firmly in the heart of the EC.
Behind the festival, though, lie a number of fears. Cardiff is suffering its
worst economic setback since the early 1980s. Unemployment has been rising,
and the economy has slowed down.
'There was a fundamental shift in business confidence between last August
and the end of the year,' says Nigel Guy, director in Cardiff for 3i, the
venture capital group. 'Cardiff, like South Wales generally, entered the
recession later than the rest of Britain, but then the wheels fell off. This
came as a great surprise to a business community that had experienced five
good years, and didn't quite know how to handle a downturn.'
Mr Guy's opinion is backed by others. Hugh Thomas, senior partner of Price
Waterhouse, says that business has been 'very quiet' since the end of the
year, with many concerns 'fighting to stay alive'. And David Phillips,
director of the Cardiff Chamber of Commerce, who says that after having
ridden the storm better and longer than the rest of the UK, the situation in
the city is now exactly the same as elsewhere in the UK.
'Most worrying, future investment plans are down yet again in both the
manufacturing and service sectors,' observes Dr Phillips. 'I have never seen
such a depressing picture.'
There are tentative signs, according to Mr Guy, that the bottom may have
been reached: 'I don't think it will fall further. But when the upturn will
come is another matter.'
Dr Phillips foresees an upturn 'well within the next 12 months. Confidence
among companies about increased turnover and profitability is evident.'
However, the manner in which the recession has crept into the service
sector, as well as manufacturing, is disturbingly ominous. Cardiff draws
much of its wealth from its offices, shops and administrative services.
Its great strength in recent years has been as a centre of government. A
major government department, with a secretary of state who has a seat in the
cabinet, overlooks Cathays Park in the civic centre. Only Edinburgh, and to
a lesser extent Belfast, outside London enjoy this privilege.
Nearby Bristol, for instance, a regional centre of government and a city
about a third larger than Cardiff, has one under-secretary as its senior
civil servant. Cardiff has not only a secretary of state, a minister of
state and a parliamentary secretary of state, but also a permanent
secretary, two deputy secretaries and 11 under-secretaries, as well as a
raft of assistant secretaries. This is an enormous weight of administrative
fire-power.
Recent years have seen this strength supplemented by the growth of an
important financial-services industry. Since Sir Julian Hodge, in the 1960s,
formed what has now become the Bank of Wales - 75 per cent owned by the Bank
of Scotland, which is bidding for the remaining 25 per cent - there has been
a steady infusion of financial companies into the Welsh capital, and the
workforce in the sector has grown strongly to 18,000.
Though manufacturing industry has declined severely since the mid-1970s, two
highly important new arrivals have been Bosch, making alternators for the
auto industry; and British Airways, which is to service its fleet of Boeing
747s, the jumbo, next to the airport.
BA chose the site in preference to Liverpool and Singapore, and work starts
soon on a building that will be one of the largest in Europe, employing at
least another 1,200 people - the same number as Bosch expects to employ
fairly soon.
The momentum generated by the inflow of investment is being backed
internally by a programme to redevelop 2,700 acres of Cardiff's decaying
docklands. This redevelopment, the estimated cost of which is more than
Pounds 2bn, is the largest urban regeneration programme in Europe after
London's docklands.
The scheme would bolt on to the city a 21st-century addition, and bring work
for over 30,000 jobs in the next 10 to 15 years, according to Geoffrey
Inkin, chairman of Cardiff Bay Development Corporation.
Some Pounds 250m of investment has already been carried out by Tarmac
Beazer, Westbury, Crest Nicholson and Barratt. The proposed centrepiece for
the whole development, though, is an opera house, a home for the Welsh
National Opera Company, costing perhaps Pounds 40m, on the water's edge
within a development being undertaken by Grosvenor Waterside, Associated
British Port's property arm in Cardiff.
'We are virtually ready to go on the Pounds 150m scheme,' says Mr Freddie
Watson, Grosvenor Waterside's director in charge of the project: 'It is now
simply a matter of getting sufficient commitment to ensure a start will be
made soon.'
But the strategy behind the redevelopment of the docklands suffered a
setback last month. A locally-sponsored private parliamentary bill, to allow
a barrage to be built across Cardiff Bay, creating a non-tidal 500-acre
freshwater lake, collapsed on its last stages of a three-year passage. At an
all-night sitting, a group of Labour MPs made long speeches and raised
persistent objections. They oppose the scheme on environmental grounds,
though a number of them would also prefer to see any government money spent
elsewhere in Wales.
The inability of the government to shepherd the private bill through
parliament was a nasty political blow for the Welsh secretary, David Hunt,
and for Mr Inkin, who had failed to neutralise the opposition to it.
Yet the chances of the Pounds 125m barrage (the largest civil-engineering
project in Europe, after the channel tunnel) coming into being may possibly
have been strengthened by its failure as a private bill. The government has
promised to introduce a bill of its own, and get it through quickly.
But can this be achieved in the present session of parliament, or before a
general election? If it cannot, the measure would have to be brought in
again - though another government might not have the same commitment to the
whole scheme.
Meanwhile, the institutional investors who are necessary to fund the huge
projects, having burnt their fingers on the present recession, are sitting
on their hands. They will need rather more certainty about the barrage
project before they commit themselves to positive decisions.
The bay scheme, the developments announced by NFC, Grosvenor Waterside,
Tarmac, Laing, Carla Properties and Charnwood Holdings, the imminent arrival
of other financial institutions, the likelihood of more hotels being built -
all these augur well for Cardiff. First, though, the city must climb out of
the recession. Until that happens, perhaps in nine months to a year's time,
much of the next phase of economic advance will remain on hold.
</TEXT>
<PUB>The Financial Times
</PUB>
<PAGE>
