<HEADLINE>
FT  11 MAY 91 / The empire crumbles but the suffering goes on: A look at
what is happening to the people now that socialism has broken down even in
the proletarian heartlands of the Soviet Union
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JOHN LLOYD
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THE BREAKDOWN of socialist society in the Soviet Union, an irreversible and
ugly process, is now evident in the proletarian heartlands. Novokuznetsk,
once called Stalinsk, the mining and metallurgical centre of Western
Siberia, is one example.
Like moneylenders in the temple, the new signs of market behaviour and
individual enrichment display themselves among the icons of a collapsing
power. The slogans of the 1970s, and earlier, (dis)grace every large
building: 'The service of the state is the interest of all' and 'Raising the
people higher is the aim of the Communist Party of the Soviet Union' and
even, interwoven into a socialist realist mural on the side of an apartment
building: 'Land to the peasants]"
The miners' strike, which ended reluctantly three days ago , had its
militant core here in the Kuzbass coalfield. According to Alexander
Aslanidi, the man who emerged with Gregory Malykhin as the most articulate
exponent of their views, one source of their bitterness is that they feel
they cannot trust the government. 'We think it plays political tricks. Even
now, the agreement between Yeltsin and Gorbachev is to benefit them, not
us.'
There is more to it than that, though. The distrust is fuelled by the sheer
oppressiveness of the ideology which surrounds lives oppressed already by
harsh working conditions, poor, cramped apartments and slop food which is,in
any case, available only with coupons.
Vast factories like the Kuznets Metal Combine, the ZapSib (West Siberia)
steel works and the two aluminium plants disgorge sulphurous smoke into the
valley which contains the city. The food in the canteens is greasy:
rissoles, rice or mashed potatoes, tepid soup and dry, crumbling bread. The
flats - a mixture of Stalin-era gothic and slabs from the 1960s and 1970s,
with some fantasy added outside - are typically two or three small rooms,
kitchen and bathroom. The old wooden houses, some mere shacks, mostly have
outside lavatories. At night, you can hear screaming, desperate rows coming
from the stinking stairwells and you walk among stumbling, incoherent drunks
on the streets. 'You see, there is something to strike about,' said
Alexander Romankov, a young mine manager (who was nevertheless against it).
There is, however, another reason for the unrest, which could be the most
powerful. Among the Stalinist ikons, the new motto is the old one - 'enrich
yourself'. Kuzbass is not like the Ukrainian Donbass field - or, for that
matter, South Wales or the Pas de Calais. Many of the mines have rich, thick
seams of high quality coal for which there is international demand. They
have a market future.
But several things have happened simultaneously.
First, the centralised control of the Union coal ministry has, like all
other such controls, been weakening for some time: indeed, the transfer of
control of the Russian mines from Union to Russian Government in the past
week was more of a logical, if large, step in an already evident direction
than a sudden turnabout. This has meant, for example, that the dozen pits
belonging to the Kuznetsugol Combine in Novokuznetsk have been able to trade
coal abroad, under license, for some years.
Second, decentralisation has impoverished central government. Its foreign
debts have ballooned and its exports, especially of oil, have gone down. It
is starved of hard currency and takes whatever is earned by the fledgling
enterprises.
Kuznetsugol, and other combines, have sought to circumvent this by barter -
coal for Japanese goods. The Sonys now appearing in the cramped living rooms
are nominally available at a subsidised price of Rs2000 (and can be bought
on the black market for Rs12,000). The shining new Nissan Patrols and Urvans
and Sunnys which litter the Kuznetsugol car park are even more obvious signs
of the new affluence. The combine ships them in through Vladivostok, hauls
them across Siberia on the railways and sells them to the mines and the
miners at highly subsidised prices (after which, of course, the black market
takes over).
Matters have not stopped here. Some pits have been leased to their workers,
who must fulfil the state's output target but can then sell the excess on
the market. One pit, Polosuxinskaya, 30 kms from Novokuznetsk, is the first
Soviet mine to hand over majority control to a foreign capitalist. It is
relatively new and very rich in coal.
Two years ago, Igor Gladun, now 43, took over as its director. A short,
powerful man of great energy, he saw how the wind was blowing and got rid of
its (full time) Communist Party secretary (most enterprises in the town now
have, according to Romankov, who has worked in several.) Last year, Gladun
sold 55,000 tonnes of his high quality coking coal abroad at Dollars 46 a
tonne: this year he hopes to sell 90,000 tonnes at Dollars 50-55.
Gladun knew he needed access to Western capital and equipment if he was to
make his pit spin real money. At the same time, Morris Cartwright, a British
coal trader in his early 50s, was sniffing about in Moscow looking for a new
challenge. They were brought together by Valentin Aksilenko, a former Soviet
diplomat in Cuba who had set up his own consultancy called Uni-Eko.
Last month, an agreement was signed giving Cartwright's company, Britseco,
and a Swiss partner, Traiko AG, a majority share of the output of
Polosuxinskaya. The deal sets up a new company, valued at Dollars 15m, also
includes Gladun, Aksilenko, Kuznetsugol, the local railway concern and the
regional soviet (council) at Kemerovo.
This company could become very rich. The pit must produce 2.3m tonnes a year
for the state but it can sell everything above that - and Gladun reckons he
can produce 2.5m tonnes this year. And although only two days were lost to
strikes during the wave just ended, he has told his miners they must work
hard now they are under capitalist ownership.
By chance, Cartwright has now played the role of strikebreaker in two
continents: in the British miners' strike of 1984/85, he helped ship coal
into the little ports which were still open on the south coast, beating
Welsh pickets and getting the coal to power stations. Gladun has marked out
a vast area of reserves - 100m tonnes, called Antonov 2  - which is
Britseco's to exploit. The core of the deal is that Cartwright will, over
the following months, invest heavily in (mainly Western) equipment to drive
the roads and set up the faces on Antonov 2.
This machinery will then sheer away the thick seams of coking coal, load it
onto the railways and wait for the profits to roll in. As simple as that?
The infrastructure is bad; and the collective farm beneath whose fields
Antonov 2 waits for exploitation is cutting up rough. Gladun says he needs
Dollars 4.5m worth of investment right away, but that he cannot get it until
Cartwright sees some coal.
If Polosuxinskaya does not fail badly, pits like it will receive the same
attention and investment. Their workers will be much better off than those
around them - who may well become worse off soon, since much of Novokuznetsk
has a technological death sentence hanging over it, with cuts looming in
work forces and production. Most of Aslanidi's pit delegates know of this.
Some may hope to gain others fear to lose.
Finally, although the strikes were a product of political collapse. Not only
have the Gladuns of Novokuznetsk kicked out their Communist Party
secretaries but the party itself, although still in command of the town, is
isolated and disliked, especially by the young. A vast statue of Lenin,
which should have been completed a decade ago, remains barely started and is
hardly likely to swell the mass ranks of its fellows now.
An amateur video shot by some local enthusiasts on their (Japanese) video
shows snatched, jumpy interviews with citizens who responded to questions
about what they thought of the current state of politics. The supporters of
the status quo (or the past) were usually on sticks: the young and middle
aged were dismissive or contemptuous.
On the edge of town, you will find the Preobrazhenie Sobor, or
Transfiguration Cathedral. Here worshipped Dostoyevsky. After the revolution
it was, in turn, a bakery and a warehouse and was to have been made into a
dance hall. The loosening of political control and the rapid rise in the
power of the church has meant that its partly burnt structure is now being
repaired. Services are taking place although the roof is still being
constructed.
On Tuesday, about 12 old women, one old man and a young man with long wild
hair and beard made up the congregation. A small choir of elderly women
chanted the Orthodox service. A youngish priest paraded about with a censer.
The heavy, mystical atmosphere - the opposite of, and the antidote to, the
triumph of will and reason outside - was evident even in the handful of
ageing bodies genuflecting among the sawdust.
The Orthodox Church has not come out of its decades of trial as a liberal
institution: it has also lost generations of potential faithful and might
never recapture future ones in the atomised, urban society. But it, and the
Nissan Patrols and Aslanidi's followers and Cartwright's mine, are the
elements out of which Novokuznetsk is seeking to restore itself.
</TEXT>
<PUB>The Financial Times
</PUB>
<PAGE>
London Page VIII Photograph Miners in southern Kuzbass vote for a 24-hour
strike (Omitted).
</PAGE>
