<PROFILE>_AN-BELAGAFNFT</PROFILE>
<DATE>910511
</DATE>
<HEADLINE>
FT  11 MAY 91 / Lift off with sweat and tears: The painful birth of the jet
engine 50 years ago
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By WILFRED HARPER
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
ON A cloudy wartime evening 50 years ago Britain's first jet-propelled
aeroplane made its maiden flight from RAF Cranwell in Lincolnshire. It was a
pretty little thing and it swooped around smoothly for 17 minutes before
making a perfect landing.
This event, of such vast significance to the the world, was witnessed by
only a handful of people and filmed by a hand-held camera in monochrome.
This was entirely in keeping with the story of how jet propulsion came into
the world.
It was the fruit of 13 years theoretical and experimental work by Sir Frank
Whittle, on a pitifully small budget and in the face of much official
scepticism and wrangling. The wonder is that Whittle did not chuck his hand
in or that the strain, increased by the stress of war, did not cripple him.
Perhaps it did in some ways. A small fraction of the recognition which he
eventually gained would have done him a lot of good in the discouraging
1930s and 1940s.
On Wednesday, 50 years to the day, he is due to stand, if his health permits
upon that same airfield while an array of aircraft from the vast progeny of
his invention will thunder past in salute.
It is, however, a sad irony that the anniversary falls at a time when
Rolls-Royce is in serious difficulties. The aero-engine maker, which used
the original Whittle engine to develop its Wellend, Derwent, Nene and Dart
power plants, announced only last Thursday a sweeping new round of job cuts
because of the recession in the airline and defence markets.
Wednesday's fly past will be followed by a ceremony at Cranwell College
where, as an RAF flight cadet 64 years ago, Whittle wrote the thesis which
fixed his destiny, Future Developments in Aircraft Design.
He was born in Coventry in 1907, less than four years after the Wright
brothers' first powered flight. His father was an inventive mechanic with a
small engineering business who encouraged his son's mechanical abilities.
Aviation was the novelty of the time and the young Frank read everything he
could on the subject.
When he was 15, he applied to join the RAF as an apprentice. Initially
rejected because of his size - he was only five feet tall. After growing
three inches in six months he was accepted as a Cranwell apprentice in 1923,
graduating as a Pilot Officer from Cranwell College five years later.
Whittle's thoughts on aviation's future grew from his conviction that high
speeds and long range necessitated high-altitude flight in the less dense
and therefore less resistant air. RAF fighters in those days had a top speed
of about 150 mph. Whittle was thinking of 500 mph.
The essential requirement was a propulsion system capable of operating in
thin air. The speeds of propellers and reciprocating engines are limited by
tip speeds and air intake.
Whittle considered various possibilities including the newly developed gas
turbine driving a fan. Then it occurred to him that a gas turbine could be
developed to provide an exhaust jet which alone would be sufficient to
propel an aircraft.
He was encouraged by one of his flying instructors to place his ideas before
the Air Ministry. The Ministry considered them impractical. It was biased
against any form of gas turbine because materials which would withstand the
stress and temperatures in an aircraft application did not then exist.
That was in 1929. Although depressed by rejection, Whittle filed a
provisional specification with the Post Office on January 16, 1930. The Air
Ministry said it had no official interest in the patent. This gloomy year
was brightened, however, by marriage to his Coventry fiancee.
Despite rejection by officials and industrialists, the idea of jet
propulsion increased its grip on Whittle. He continued his theoretical
explorations using any relevant data he could find, such as supercharger
performance in the Schneider Trophy aircraft. Meanwhile Whittle's RAF career
prospered. In 1934 he was sent to Peterhouse, Cambridge, to read Mechanical
Sciences.
In 1935 his jet patent fell due for renewal. Astonishingly, neither he nor
the Air Ministry felt it was worth the Pounds 5 fee, so the patent lapsed.
Soon afterwards, tentative support began to gather behind Whittle's idea. A
new company called Power Jets was formed in 1936 with authorised capital of
Pounds 10,000.
Whittle, still an undergraduate, was allowed by the Air Council to act as
Honorary Chief Engineer provided that such work did not interfere with his
RAF duties and that in any case it should not exceed six hours a week. The
engine work and his studies combined to affect his health but nevertheless
he graduated with a first in 1936 and continued as a post-graduate.
Power Jets had neither workshop nor test premises. The engine of its design
was sub-contracted to British Thompson-Houston, the industrial steam turbine
maker, of Rugby. By April 1937 the first crude engine was ready for test.
Good engineering practice required that novel components should be developed
independently. However, money was so short that the engine had to be tested
as a whole.
Whittle himself was at the test controls for the first run. The engine,
mounted on a truck in the turbine factory, was spun up. The flame in the
combustion chamber was ignited and Whittle gradually opened the control
valve. 'For a second or two the engine speed increased slowly,' he recalled.
'Then, with a rising shriek, like an air raid siren, the speed began to rise
rapidly and large patches of red heat became visible on the combustion
chamber casing. The engine was obviously out of control.'
Everyone around ran for their lives. Whittle, badly frightened, immediately
shut down. Speed control was to remain a problem for a long time. British
Thompson-Houston asked Power Jets to take its project elsewhere, eventually
offering part of a dilapidated and disused foundry a few miles away. For
nearly four years that engine, altered as repairs and experimental work went
along, was the only test piece. It was set up in ramshackle premises, the
project was inadequately staffed and funded, and war was looming.
Whittle was listed for special duties with Power Jets, a curious position in
which from time to time he had to choose between the advancement of his more
orthodox career as an RAF officer and his invention. Conflicts of all kinds
arose between Power Jets, BTH and later, Rover, as well as with the Air
Ministry. The Lutterworth outfit became known as 'the Cherry Orchard', after
the play by Chekov in which preoccupied characters wander in and out, making
seemingly irrelevant utterances. Whittle's habit of breaking off to take pot
shots at rabbits with his .22 rifle doubtless helped foster the allusion.
In 1938 the Air Ministry at last ordered an engine to power an aircraft. A
year later, on the brink of war, it ordered a fast, single seat aircraft,
the G28/39 Pioneer, in which to fit the engine from the Gloster Aircraft
Company. Then designs for a twin jet fighter were put in hand. A second
experimental engine was tested at Lutterworth, much to the pleasure of the
cows in the adjacent field, which gathered in the warm jet stream.
In keeping with many of the bizarre aspects of the project the first jet
aeroplane, with its 29 foot wing span was assembled in a former 19th century
horse emporium in the middle of fashionable Cheltenham, a location chosen
because of the risk of an air raid on the main factory.
The completed aircraft was taken to Brockworth and on April 7, 1941 it made
200-yard six-feet hops over the grass airfield, Whittle piloting some of the
runs. Then it was fitted with the latest engine and taken to Cranwell which
has a long runway, for light tests.
Gloster's chief test pilot, Flight Lieutenant Gerry Sayer, made the first
flights and was charmed by the aircraft's smoothness and by the lack of
noise and vibration associated with propellers. It was about as fast as
current Spitfires but it was very thirsty. 'It's the first time I've flown
an aeroplane where you can actually see a fuel gauge moving,' said one
pilot. Another took his eye off the gauge for too long and ran the aeroplane
dry, then having to make a risky landing on a dead engine.
The aeroplane was used to gather test data for the proposed twin-engined
fighter. It was retired in 1944 and now hangs in the Science Museum.
The Gloster Meteor fighter entered squadron service in 1944, the first jet
aeroplane in the world to do so. Shortly afterwards a German equivalent also
entered squadron service - the Germans had been working along similar lines
and actually had a jet plane, the Heinkel 178, in the air 21 months before
the Pioneer. Fortunately for Britain they failed to take full advantage of
their lead.
</TEXT>
<PUB>The Financial Times
</PUB>
<PAGE>
London Page VIII Photograph Sir Frank Whittle (Omitted).
