<DATE>910511
</DATE>
<HEADLINE>
FT  11 MAY 91 / Arts: Faces over the last hundred years - The Royal Society
of Portrait Painters' exhibition at the Mall Gallery
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By PATRICIA MORISON
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
QUITE POSSIBLY Louise, Duchess of Connaught, was simply a stout middle-aged
lady with a double-chin. Then she sat to Sir John Singer Sargent and was
transformed in a three-quarters length portrait. The haughty duchess was
immortalised with her excess inches skillfully vanished away, swelling
upwards but not outwards from black satin and puffs of white chiffon.
Sargent and dozens of other celebrated Edwardian portraitists can be seen at
the Mall Gallery where the Royal Society of Portrait Painters holds its
centenary exhibition (until May 31).
The exhibition honours many past members of the Society, starting with the
bravura and opulent vision of the 1880s and 1890s generation of Lavery,
Orchardson, Guthrie, Shannon, Solomon, and the Victorian old-timer, GF
Watts. Strange that no portrait appears by Archibald Wortley, who therefore
remains just a name although it was he was responsible for calling into
being a society dedicated to giving portraiture higher status and an
exhibition base broader than that offered by the Royal Academy.
The second generation around 1910 brought in the very different approaches
of painters such as Rothenstein, Strang, Orpen and Nicholson. The Strang
portrait is particularly fine, a beautifully poised study of a gentleman
which is strongly influenced by Degas. Quite one of the most remarkable
portraits, however, is Harold Speed's powerful image of a surgeon operating
for cataract. A difficult subject, one might think, brilliantly handled by a
composition which focusses the viewer's gaze not on Dr Little's down-tilted
face, but on his hands as he inserts scalpels into the horridly shining eye
of his patient. This painting normally hangs in the Manchester Royal Eye
Hospital, so this is a rare chance to see it.
Sir Gerald Kelly's famous and exuberant portrait of Vaughan Williams and
Brockhust's bewitching 'Clytie' should stop you in your tracks. So, no
doubt, will 'Juanita Forbes', a preposterous Annigoni temptress who cradles
an hour-glass in a surrealist landscape. There is a fine clutch of inter-war
society ladies of the boneless, chiffon-wrapped variety. One of them by
Cowan Dobson is actually called 'Chiffon'. Lipstick had become now quite the
done thing for ladies but even so, this lady's lips are not for the
squeamish.
And so it continues, a crammed miscellany of portraits familiar and mostly
unfamiliar. At the end is a small but interesting selection of work by
present-day members. This is a large exhibition but it is not, alas, a
generous one. The public pays for admission, which in the circumstances is
perfectly reasonable. But what should an entry-fee buy you?
This exhibition has no labels so some 90 per cent of the exhibits are
anonymous. You have to buy the catalogue to find out even who the artists
and sitters are. Now that smacks of sharp practice, the more so as the
catalogue entries are quite remarkably uninformative - just a few lines from
each artist's curriculum vitae and nothing about the paintings. As half the
pleasure of portraits is as documents to social history, this is a fairly
disastrous omission. These may be lean times for the Society, but even so I
am surprised that in its centenary year it chose to go before its public in
quite such a threadbare dress.
My colleague William Packer has already written about the important
exhibition of Canadian landscape-painting, The True North now at the
Barbican Art Gallery. Our Home and Native Land is a pendant exhibition which
has now moved to Canada House, Trafalgar Square from a previous, rather
larger showing at Sheffield's Mappin Art Gallery.
Arthur Lismer and Frederick Varley, two of the most famous and influential
figures in the history of Canadian art, emigrated from Sheffield. So did a
number of other artists, most notably Stanley Royle and Elizabeth Nutt,
although Royle eventually returned to England. The exhibition explores the
early influences on this generation of artists who, in an artistic
environment subtly permeated by Ruskin's values, trained at the Sheffield
School of Art for jobs in the commercial art world. Interestingly, these
young artists' commitment to landscape-painting is placed within the context
of the political movement to win greater access to the countryside for the
urban proletariat.
It is fascinating to see how that exceptionally gifted pair, Lismer and
Varley, responded to the raw colours, the vastness, of the Canadian
landscape. Equally, it is almost uncanny to find their late work turning
back to close-focus Ruskinian studies of their youth. This is an exhibition
Sheffield can be proud of. It shows the energy and passion for research
which, funds permitting, flourishes in our provincial public collections.
</TEXT>
<PUB>The Financial Times
</PUB>
<PAGE>
London Page XIX Picture Lips not for the squeamish belonging to an inter-war
society lady, detail from Chiffon, a portrait by Cowan Dobson (Omitted).
