<HEADLINE>
FT  11 MAY 91 / Arts: Mehta in concert
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By RICHARD FAIRMAN
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
WHILE ZUBIN Mehta is in London conducting Carmen at Covent Garden he has
found time to take on a few concerts as well, giving us an opportunity to
judge his form on the platform when he is not in the company of a visiting
international orchestra on a prestige tour.
To date the conductor's most notable successes here have been at the
opera-house. He led a splendid, wide-screen sound production of Puccini's La
fanciulla del West, for which he reportedly re-seated the orchestra. There
was a Tristan und Isolde, too, no less luscious sonically, though doubts
began to creep in there; and it was unfortunately the Wagner opera that
rather came to mind at his concert on Thursday with the London Philharmonic
at the Royal Festival Hall.
The evening made an unexciting start with Mozart's Symphony No 41, the
'Jupiter'. This was a typically euphonious performance, well played, keen
not to offend, though it found a more positive attitude in the finale. As
the 18th-century repertoire brings forth a new breed of conductors, it is
increasingly clear that the maestros of the big symphony orchestras, such as
Mehta, find it difficult to articulate this music. Too often it just sounds
vague.
To say that Bruckner requires the same insight is not as improbable as it
might sound. When Jochum came with the Vienna Philharmonic to perform the
Seventh Symphony, he inflected the opening statement in such a way as to
presage all the underlying tensions he felt in the music. Under Mehta the
same phrases were broad, spacious, unfolded with rapturous beauty of tone,
but otherwise featureless. And that, no less, anticipated his performance as
a whole.
Time and again one registered passages that sounded more beautiful than ever
before - orchestral textures so lusciously blended, violin lines that soared
so radiantly, that one momentarily forgot that a symphonic argument should
also be going on. In this awesome symphony there is a great journey to be
undertaken, from self-doubt and loss to hard-won triumph. But the only
significant movement here was up to one blazing climax and down again.
The London Philharmonic played for Mehta at near the top of its present high
standards. The conductor evidently enjoys a rapport with the players and it
is disappointing that the results are not as impressive as one feels, by
right, they ought to be.
</TEXT>
<PUB>The Financial Times
</PUB>
<PAGE>
London Page XVIII
</PAGE>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>FT911-385</DOCNO>
<PROFILE>_AN-BELAGAFKFT</PROFILE>
<DATE>910511
</DATE>
<HEADLINE>
FT  11 MAY 91 / Outdoors: Violets, lovely violets - An almost-forgotten
flower variety
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ARTHUR HELLYER
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
SOME YEARS ago a friend gave me a violet which he called Wellsiana and told
me he regarded it as the best variety he knew for growing in the garden.
At first I thought the name must be wrong because this was clearly not a
wild species but a garden plant, a selection of the sweet violet, Viola
odorata, and it is unusual - indeed against present rules of plant
nomenclature - to use names in this botanical style for garden varieties.
However, it did not take me long to establish that Wellsiana was a valid
name for it is used by Roy E. Coombs in his authoritative book Violets
published by Croom Helm in 1981.
It was given this name by its raiser, Mr Wells of Fern Hill, Windsor, and in
1884 he was awarded a first class certificate for it by the Royal
Horticultural Society, the highest award it has to give to a garden plant
and one sparingly used.
Clearly Wellsiana must have been special. It was predicted then that it
would become the most widely cultivated of all violets grown from cut
flowers.
Yet despite this triumphant start Wellsiana now seems to have almost faded
away, in fact I cannot recollect ever having heard of it until my friend
showed it to me. So what went wrong? Was it not as good as at first appeared
or did it develop some fatal fault along the way and is my friend wrong in
still rating it so highly?
It is even possible that the plant he has acquired under this name is not
the original Wellsiana. Mistakes when propagating free-growing plants can
occur and unless there are other correctly named stocks around for
comparison, memory can fade and it can become impossible to recollect the
subtle differences that distinguish one garden variety from another.
This is one reason for establishing national collections of ornamental plant
varieties and for taking urgent steps to see that the plant names in these
collections are checked while there are still people living able to
recollect them clearly.
All I can say with certainty is that the plant I am growing as Wellsiana is
a good one. It was particularly attractive this spring, filling the air with
its perfume and covering the ground rapidly and densely with healthy green
leaves so making a fine carpet to smother weed seedlings.
The flowers are fairly large, their colour deep violet blue, their scent
strong and sweet and widely spread. The plant is sturdy and easy to
propagate simply by pulling it apart at almost any time of the year.
In fact it is weather more than season than matters most as it is best
divided when conditions are moist and likely to remain so for a few weeks.
However, that is a difficulty that can be overcome by watering and shading.
This violet has never been attacked by red-spider mites in my garden, often
the most troublesome pest of these plants, living on the undersides of the
leaves in vast numbers and sucking the sap from them so that they turn from
green to dull bronzy yellow.
However, that may be due partly to the moistness of my soil and air for
these mites thrive where it is hot and dry and frequent syringing with plain
water is often the most effective, and certainly the cheapest, way of
keeping them away. However, I suspect that the vigour with which that
Wellsiana grows would give it considerable resistance.
So what did go wrong? I do not know for certain, but just about the time
that Mr Wells was raising his Wellsiana the great 19th century French violet
breeder Armand Millet of Bourg-la-Reine near Paris, was breaking what had
until that time been the top limits of violet flower size and flower stem
length.
At that period violets were in great demand as cut flowers and many
thousands of small commercial growers were employed in supplying them to the
flower markets.
Not only are large, long-stemmed violets more effective when cut but it is
easier and quicker to pick and bunch them. So it is natural that varieties
such as Princesse de Galles - always known in Britain as Princess of Wales -
which has larger flowers and longer flower stems than those of The Tsar,
captured this market before the newly arrived Wellsiana had a chance to
establish itself even in the private side.
What does alarm me is that it seems to have become so much forgotten that I
cannot find it listed in The Plant Finder, the latest edition of which has
just come to hand. It is enlarged to include 50,000 garden varieties and is
available through any bookshop, for Pounds 9.99, published by Headmain.
</TEXT>
