<HEADLINE>
FT  11 MAY 91 / Finance &amp; the Family (Briefcase): Taxing the inspector
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
I NEED some information in writing from my tax inspector who seems unable or
unwilling to answer my questions ie. does not reply to my letters.
Is there a superior being to whom I can write to ask that I be sent the
information I require.
As a first step, write to the District Inspector at your tax office -
marking both the letter and the envelope: 'For the attention of the District
Inspector'.
Whether you can insist upon being given the information depends upon what it
is that you want. Statement of Practice F1 (Limitations on Revenue advice to
taxpayers) stresses that 'the primary duty of the Revenue towards the
taxpayer . . . is to assess his liability after the end of the year'.
