<HEADLINE>
FT  11 MAY 91 / Finance &amp; The Family: Take care, volatile funds at large - A
look at the ground broken by new investment rules for unit trusts
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By SIMON LONDON
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
NEW INVESTMENT rules for unit trusts unveiled by the Securities and
Investments Board earlier this month have opened the way for mutual funds
which concentrate on futures and options.
Investors should tread carefully, because the rules are sure to prompt the
launch of some highly geared and volatile funds. For example, a fund which
invested 20 per cent of its assets (the maximum which can be invested in
futures and options under the SIB rules) in the FT-SE 100 futures contract
would be geared to around 700 per cent. This means that the assets of the
fund would be completely wiped-out by just a 15 per cent fall in the UK
equity market.
However, the mainstream of the UK unit trust industry is taking a cautious
approach. Many funds to be launched later this year are likely to maintain
relatively low gearing and to spread their investment in futures and options
across markets.
Unlike the US, where futures funds play a whole range of financial and
commodity markets, most UK fund managers said that they will concentrate on
areas they know - equities, bonds and currencies.
While the SIB rules allow funds geared up to 800 per cent or more, few funds
are likely to maintain such high levels of leverage.
'Gearing for the sake of gearing does not offer optimal investment returns,'
said Alan Wren, chief executive of Prudential Holborn.
Prudential Holborn expects to have its first fund ready for launch by
September. Wren envisages a fund with average gearing of perhaps 20 per
cent, moving up to 50 per cent on some occasions and down to zero gearing at
other times.
This is comparable to the level of gearing offered by investment trusts. The
difference is that investment trusts take on gearing by borrowing, rather
than by buying futures and options.
While the details have yet to be finalised, Prudential Holborn's favoured
fund strategy concentrates on an international portfolio of equities.
Futures and options would be used to adjust the exposure of the fund to
different markets at lower cost than buying or selling actual shares.
This sentiment is echoed by Trevor Robinson of Fidelity Investments, which
also favours an equity-based investment strategy.
In addition to new funds, a number of the off-shore futures funds already
run by UK institutions will move on-shore once the new rules are in force.
For example, John Govett already runs three open-ended off-shore futures
funds, which are highly geared investments. For example, the company's
dollar bond fund and dollar currency fund are geared at 800 per cent.
The company plans to seek a UK listing for its lower risk Managed Futures
Fund, which is geared to about 400 per cent. For the UK, however, it plans
only a low-risk futures fund without gearing.
However, while the bigger players are initially cautious, some new highly
geared funds are certain to be launched. Investors are advised to look
closely at what they are buying.
</TEXT>
<PUB>The Financial Times
</PUB>
<PAGE>
London Page IV
</PAGE>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>FT911-392</DOCNO>
<PROFILE>_AN-BELAGAFDFT</PROFILE>
<DATE>910511
</DATE>
<HEADLINE>
FT  11 MAY 91 / Finance &amp; The Family: Gilts may be boring, but they have an
edge
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By PHILIP COGGAN
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
INDEX-LINKED gilts are often dismissed by stock market professionals as
unexciting investments. But those planning for their retirement should find
a niche for them in their portfolios.
The capital value of such a gilt will be repaid on maturity in line with the
increase in the Retail Price Index over the lifetime of the bond. The
coupon, initially set at either 2 or 2.5 per cent of the original face value
is also increased in line with inflation.
At the moment, the trading price of index-linked gilts lags behind their
repayment price, and as a result the real yield on offer is around 4 per
cent, provided you hold the bond till maturity and assuming inflation
averages 5 per cent.
That is a very respectable return by historical standards. Most personal
pensions are invested in equity-based funds, on the grounds that equities
are the best vehicle for long-term growth. The real returns from shares are
good but variable. Figures from Barclays de Zoete Wedd show that the real
return on equities between 1968 and 1990 was just 4.2 per cent a year,
although it was as much as 14.1 per cent between 1974 and 1990.
But the BZW figures only show the returns available if you match the index.
Most fund managers do not do so. Take for comparison, the BZW figures for
the ten years to end 1990, which show growth with income reinvested of 395
per cent. The average UK equity general unit trust rose by 365 per cent over
the same period, on an offer-to-bid basis.
On an annual basis, that means the return was around 1 per cent lower than
provided by the index. The average UK balanced trust underperformed by
around 2 per cent a year.
Assume, for argument's sake, that a conventional personal pension will
underperform the index by 1.5 per cent a year. Then for an equity-based
personal pension to beat an index-linked gilt, where the real return is
effectively guaranteed, equities need to produce a real return of 5.5 per
cent a year.
The startling result from the BZW figures is that in 13 of the 26 20-year
periods since the Second World War (1945-65, 1946-66 etc) equities have
failed to produce a real return of more than 5.5 per cent.
Those figures make index-linked gilts look a better bet. Some managers will
allow you to set up your own personal plan, saving on commissions and
financial adviser's fees. You can invest in index-linked gilts directly and
as with a conventional personal pension, such investment will be tax
deductible and gains within the fund will be tax-free.
Index-linked gilts are not the perfect answer for everybody, or for all your
long-term savings. But investing in index-linked for your retirement would
save you from several worries:
your pension fund is guaranteed to outpace inflation,
you cannot be let down by a poorly performing fund,
you cannot suffer from a plunge in the stock market,
your credit risk - the government - is unimpeachable.
</TEXT>
<PUB>The Financial Times
</PUB>
<PAGE>
London Page IV
</PAGE>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>FT911-393</DOCNO>
<PROFILE>_AN-BELAGAFCFT</PROFILE>
<DATE>910511
</DATE>
<HEADLINE>
FT  11 MAY 91 / Finance &amp; The Family: Surveyors prefer caution
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By HEATHER FARMBROUGH
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
YOUR HOUSE purchase is proceeding smoothly until the surveyor's valuation
report lands at the building society where you have applied for a mortgage
loan. The surveyor says that the agreed price of the property is 5 per cent
too high. At once, you start to worry that you will not get the mortgage
loan The nagging suspicion creeps in that you are being ripped off.
The answer may not necessarily be yes. Surveyors have always erred on the
side of caution in preparing valuation reports since they are acting for
building societies or banks, advising whether the provision of the loan to
buy the property is a reasonable commercial risk. In other words, they have
to judge whether, in the event of a repossession the house could be sold at
a reasonable price. Although the surveyor's client is the lender rather than
the purchaser, they are in the invidious position of potentially being held
responsible by both parties should a serious structural problem be missed.
After two years of falling house prices across much of the country and a
rise in the number of repossessions, surveyors are understandably showing
even greater caution and a growing reluctance to accept market valuations,
particularly in the south where prices have fallen most.
As Peter Hutchins of Lawson and Daughters, a London estate agency, says:
'During 1987 and 1988, surveyors were very relaxed about valuing the
property at the price agreed. But we are finding that they are more cautious
nowadays, and recommending more and more retentions. This means they will
suggest, for instance, that the price is only fair if a damp proof course is
put in, and that some of the loan should be held back until satisfactory
structural work is carried out by a given date.'
This is probably enough to put all but the keenest purchasers off and to
send shivers down the vendors' backs.
'The first step I'd take is to go up the road to another firm of estate
agents and ask how much a property like the one I was buying was worth,'
said Tony Copping Joyce of the Royal Institution of Chartered Surveyors
(RICS). 'If the price seems reasonable, and there are no other problems, go
ahead.'
If it seems high, you have to weigh how much you want the house and how keen
you are to sell your present one quickly. If you try to renegotiate you may
jeopardise the transaction.
If a great deal of structural work is needed, such as dry rot treatment or
underpinning the purchaser is in a strong position to renegotiate. But if
all that is required is the replacement of a metre of guttering you probably
will not get far. If you are considering carrying out building repairs after
you have moved in, it is essential to get a full structural survey from a
chartered surveyor who is a member of the RICS  - a good idea in any case.
Although most surveyors will be unwilling to give an exact estimate of the
likely cost of building work, they should be able to provide a guide.
Unless there is serious structural work to be undertaken, the deciding
factor is often the attitude of the lender. This will depend on the
condition of the house and the estimated creditworthiness of the person
applying for the mortgage loan. If you are not borrowing more than 70 per
cent of the original agreed price, the lender may not worry if the valuation
is 5 per cent less than the agreed price. But if you want to borrow 100 per
cent, you will only be able to borrow 100 per cent of the valuation price
instead. Building societies are not allowed to lend more than the valuation
says the property is worth. If the building society agrees to lend you the
amount on condition you carry out specified structural work, it will
probably hold back a sum equivalent to their estimate of the cost of the
work. This may also mean that the insurance company covering the mortgage
loan will not grant full insurance on the property until the work is
completed.
Bear in mind, says Hutchins, that the surveyor is likely to think
cautiously. If vendors are caught unprepared, all they can do is play it by
ear.
</TEXT>
<PUB>The Financial Times
</PUB>
<PAGE>
London Page IV Illustration (Omitted).
</PAGE>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>FT911-394</DOCNO>
<PROFILE>_AN-BELAGAFBFT</PROFILE>
