<HEADLINE>
FT  11 MAY 91 / Accountancy firm to shed 225 jobs
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By DAVID WALLER
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
KPMG PEAT Marwick McLintock, the UK's second largest accountancy firm, is
making 225 qualified staff redundant, mainly in London and south-east
England - probably the largest single batch of redundancies made by a UK
accountancy firm.
Since December last year, Ernst &amp; Young, the UK's third biggest accountancy
firm, has made about 100 qualified staff redundant, and Coopers &amp; Lybrand
Deloitte, the largest firm, has said that at least 200 staff will go in the
next few months.
Other large firms have been discreetly 'counselling out' unwanted staff and
many medium-size firms have also been cutting employees.
Such redundancies were unheard of in the 1980s when the big firms grew
between 20 and 40 per cent a year in terms of fees and staff. The firms are
now being squeezed by increasing costs and falling revenues.
Mr Jim Butler, a senior partner in Peat Marwick, said the reason for the
redundancies was that young, newly qualified staff were failing to leave for
jobs in industry and the City and that as a result the firm had become
marginally overstaffed.
'In the past our problem was retaining people, but now we have the opposite
problem. There is virtually no movement at all.'
He said the redundancies should be seen in the context of Peat Marwick's
total professional staff of about 7,000.
The redundancies affect people with up to three years' post-qualification
experience, and will not change the firm's plans to recruit 850 graduate
trainees later this year.
</TEXT>
<PUB>The Financial Times
</PUB>
<PAGE>
London Page 24
