<HEADLINE>
FT  11 MAY 91 / International Company News: Banesto near to insurance deal
with French group
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By PETER BRUCE and GEORGE GRAHAM
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   MADRID, PARIS
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
BANCO Espanol de Credito (Banesto), Spain's third largest commercial bank,
is close to selling a large minority share of its insurance division, La
Union y El Fenix, to the French insurance group, Assurances Generales de
France (AGF).
The deal is also expected to include a possible exchange of shareholdings
between the two parent groups, as well as broader co-operation in insurance
marketing.
Trading in La Union y El Fenix shares was briefly suspended in Madrid
yesterday as the stock market commission announced negotiations to construct
a holding company in which Banesto, through its industrial corporation,
would hold a majority.
La Union y El Fenix is Spain's fifth largest insurer, with premium income of
Pta68bn (Dollars 660m) in 1989, while AGF's Spanish operation ranked 17,
with Pta22bn in premiums.
Banesto would not comment on the talks yesterday, but it has been expected
for some time that the bank would need to dispose of assets this year to
make up for heavy provisions forced on it by the Gulf crisis.
This week it confirmed it was selling its Catalan banking affiliate, Banc
Catala, to the Italian bank, San Paulo di Torini. It is also understood to
be contemplating the sale of part of its oil refiner, Petromed.
A merger of AGF's Spanish operations with Union y Fenix would open up large
parts of the country - western Europe's fastest-growing life insurance
market - to the French group. Not only would it be able to use Union y
Fenix's branch network, but, possibly, Banesto's network of almost 2,000
bank branches as well.
AGF has been among the most cautious of France's insurers in expanding
abroad.
Its French rival, Union des Assurances de Paris, has already bought a 3 per
cent stake in Banesto's closest Spanish banking competitor, Banco Central,
and is forming a holding company with one of Central's insurance companies,
Vasco Navarra, to sell policies through Central's regional banking
affiliates.
Allianz, the big West German insurance group, has a stake in Banco Popular,
whose branch network it also hopes to use to sell insurance.
Many Spanish banks see linking up with foreign insurance companies as a way
of increasing profitability at their branches.
</TEXT>
<PUB>The Financial Times
</PUB>
<PAGE>
London Page 12
</PAGE>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>FT911-403</DOCNO>
<PROFILE>_AN-BELAGAE2FT</PROFILE>
<DATE>910511
</DATE>
<HEADLINE>
FT  11 MAY 91 / International Company News: Californian regulator moves
against insurer
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By NIKKI TAIT
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
MR JOHN Garamendi, the rec-ently-appointed Californian insurance
commissioner, yesterday issued a 'cease and desist' order against First
Capital Life Insurance Company, a San Diego-based insurer whose parent
company is 28 per cent-owned by Shearson Lehman Brothers.
The order prohibits First Capital from making payments to its parent
company, First Capital Holdings, or to its affiliates without the
Commissioner's permission, and from writing new business.
It also places a moratorium on surrenders by First Capital policyholders and
on life insurance policy loans.
Announcing the order, Mr Garamendi said First Capital was in a 'hazardous'
financial condition. Concern about the company's position had triggered a
wave of surrenders in recent days, thus compounding its problems, he said.
First Capital is not large - its assets are Dollars 4.5bn and it has 190,000
policyholders - but the authorities' intervention comes at a sensitive time.
Last month, a much bigger Californian insurer, First Executive, was seized
by the regulators after concerns about its heavy junk bond portfolio
prompted a similar wave of surrenders and a collapse of its marketing
network.
Like First Executive, much of First Capital problems stem from sizeable junk
bond exposure.
The Commissioner has been putting pressure on Shearson to help shore up the
insurer, but no deal has emerged.
Shearson Lehman last night said it will take a Dollars 144m second quarter
pre-tax charge related to its investment in First Capital, Dow Jones reports
from New York.
</TEXT>
<PUB>The Financial Times
</PUB>
<PAGE>
London Page 12
</PAGE>
