<HEADLINE>
FT  11 MAY 91 / Letter: Dealing with the Arab boycott
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   From Mr MARTIN LEVER
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Sir, The removal of Coca-Cola and other American companies from the Arab
League blacklist of companies dealing with Israel ('Things go better for
Coca-Cola in Arab world', May 6) is to be welcomed, if only because it
recognises that these companies have had no intention of succumbing to the
Arab boycott and have continued trading with Israel. The move also
underlines the ability of companies to trade successfully with both Arab
countries and Israel.
American companies expanding in Middle East markets are encouraged by US
laws to ignore the boycott.
Indeed, many European companies also manage a growing business in both Arab
and Israeli markets, primarily because of commercial good sense and a
dislike of commercial blackmail, but increasingly because of the
encouragement given by European governments through the introduction of
anti-boycott legislation.
It is regrettable, however, that, against this background, the UK government
still steadfastly refuses to encourage, through legislation, British
companies to ignore the boycott. A recent survey by one of the DTI's own
export advisory boards suggests that British companies were annually losing
to their competitors more than Pounds 350m worth of non-military business
with Israel.
The effects of the Arab boycott, such as they are, do not prevent Israel
obtaining the products it requires in world markets. What it has done is to
demonstrate a lack of moral fibre by the British government and many British
companies which is resulting in a valuable and growing overseas market being
lost increasingly to overseas competition.
Martin Lever,
executive director,
British-Israel
Chamber of Commerce,
14/15 Rodmarton Street, London
</TEXT>
