<DOCNO>FT911-417</DOCNO>
<PROFILE>_AN-BELAGAEOFT</PROFILE>
<DATE>910511
</DATE>
<HEADLINE>
FT  11 MAY 91 / Leading Article: To buy or not to buy
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
MILLIONS of individual decisions will be taken today, and over the coming
months, in shopping malls and estate agents across Britain. The aggregate
effect of these will determine both the timing of economic recovery in the
UK, and the electoral chances of the Conservative party. Will consumers buy
now or save for a little longer? Worryingly for the government, and for the
economic forecasters, the answer is anyone's guess.
The uncharacteristically erratic behaviour of British consumers over the
past few years accounts in large part for the poor track-record of recent
economic forecasts. Back in 1985, economists failed to foresee the sharp
fall in saving and rise in borrowing and consumption that followed financial
deregulation.
Economists were caught out again last summer. Despite buoyant growth in real
personal income, an unexpectedly sharp and unforeseen rise in the portion
devoted to savings turned a mild downturn into what will be the second-worst
recession since the Second World War. The combination of high interest
rates, rising inflation and accelerating unemployment provoked consumers to
increase their savings as a percentage of disposable income to 10.8 per cent
by the end of last year, from a low of 4.5 per cent in 1988.
Undeterred, the Treasury has forecast a recovery beginning in the second
half of this year. It expects this to be driven by a recovery in consumer
spending, which is forecast to rise by 2 1/4 per cent in the first half of
next year.
Will the Treasury's optimism prove misplaced? There are signs that a
recovery in consumer confidence and business confidence has followed the end
of the Gulf war, though spring's arrival usually does boost confidence. The
rise in the Confederation of British Industry's quarterly confidence
indicator suggests recovery will arrive some time in the next six months.
Depressing picture
Mr Norman Lamont insists that people should focus on these forward-looking
confidence indicators. But his advice may reflect less on their reliability
than on the depressing picture painted by indicators of the economy's
current performance.
Such indicators provide scanty support for the chancellor's claim that an
economic recovery is 'just round the corner'. Such a recovery will not come
from a rise in business investment, as answers to the CBI's question on
investment intentions shows. Nor is an export-led recovery in prospect.
Companies have been unable to switch production away from the depressed home
market, with non-oil export volumes (excluding erratic items) up by only 0.1
per cent in the six months to March 1991, compared with the previous six.
Only the personal sector can add something significant to the modest rise in
government spending expected this year. Recent signs are not encouraging.
New car registrations in April were 24.2 per cent down from last year, while
growth in the monetary aggregates remains very low. The rise in retail sales
in March was distorted by a rush of durable goods purchases before the
budget's increase in VAT took effect, but sales in the previous three months
were depressed.
Little impact
Recent falls in interest rates and in headline inflation will undoubtedly
spark some rise in consumer spending. Yet the lags are long. Four rate cuts
this year have had little impact so far on the housing market.
Nor is next week's fall in headline inflation likely to prompt further
interest rate cuts. This is at least what Mr Robin Leigh-Pemberton, the
governor of the Bank of England, was saying this week when he warned against
perceiving 'false dawns' in the fight against inflation. This warning is
presumably addressed as much to Downing Street as to the public.
Mr Leigh-Pemberton is right to warn. Any significant further cut in interest
rates would be unwise until there is clear evidence that average wage
settlements and the annual rate of underlying inflation are on a downward
path. With UK rates of increase in unit labour costs more than twice as high
as in most of continental Europe, further increases in unemployment are also
inevitable.
A sustained rise in consumer spending is unlikely while unemployment is
still rising, especially if it continues to rise particularly rapidly in the
south. The borrowing classes are likely to be too frightened.
Despite the chancellor's optimism, the UK economy remains in a deep
recession, while the prospects for anything better than a limp recovery this
year remain poor. The Conservative party may take heart from the fact that
its popular support has held up remarkably well. Perhaps the electorate
believes Mr Lamont's predictions. He must hope so. For by persuading a
nervous public that recovery is, indeed, around the corner, he may turn out
to be right after all.
</TEXT>
<PUB>The Financial Times
</PUB>
<PAGE>
London Page 8
</PAGE>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>FT911-418</DOCNO>
<PROFILE>_AN-BELAGAENFT</PROFILE>
<DATE>910511
</DATE>
<HEADLINE>
FT  11 MAY 91 / Man in the News: Survivor out to settle an old score -
Franjo Tudjman
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JUDY DEMPSEY
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
It was known as the silent republic. For nearly two decades, Croatia nursed
its humiliation and injured pride after Tito crushed the Maspok, the
Croatian mass nationalist movement, in 1971.
The movement, backed by Croatia's Communist party and Matica Hravtska, the
nationalist cultural organisation, had tried to gain greater political and
cultural freedom for the republic from the federal/central authorities. But
Tito's tolerance level for nationalism which harboured the slightest hint of
autonomy was low.
He imprisoned scores of students, academics and journalists, and purged
Croatia's Communist party. The republic was closely controlled by the secret
police until last year, when each of Yugoslavia's six republics finally went
to the free ballot box. Franjo Tudjman's moment had come.
For the Croatian president, now 68, thrives on reawakening Croat
nationalism. It is an easy sentiment to tap.
In the neighbouring republic of Serbia, Mr Slobodan Milosevic, the staunch
nationalist Communist president, provided the perfect excuse for Croats to
revive thoughts about settling old scores with Serbia in their quest for
revenge and autonomy from the centre.
For Croats, the federal authorities are perceived to be dominated by Serbia,
a republic antithetical to Croat aspirations and outlook. Serbia is
communist, Orthodox by religion, Cyrillic in script, steeped in the Ottoman
tradition, and centralist. Croatia is Catholic, right-wing, uses the Latin
script and is influenced by the western tradition.
Croats also saw how Milosevic's uncompromising nationalist rhetoric directly
challenged their own quest for sovereignty. Who better to defend the Croats
from the Serbian leader's centralising goals than Tudjman? He has risen
magnificently to the occasion.
His election campaign in April 1990 was wrapped in the paraphernalia of
Croat nationalist symbols. The republic's citizens proudly draped the
once-banned chequered red-and-white flag on the city's 19th-century
buildings, which were modelled on Habsburg architecture.
The Croatian diaspora from Canada, the US, Australia, and the UK had finally
found a personality for its cause. It poured more than Dollars 4m into the
Croatian Democratic Union (CDU), Tudjman's right-wing Catholic party. For
emigres, and indigenous Croatians alike, Tudjman would make Croatia a proud,
free and independent republic.
But more circumspect Croats were worried by the overt, nationalist rhetoric
of Tudjman. Mr Drazen Colic, the editor of Danas, the republic's weekly
magazine, called him 'Croatia's le Pen', (a reference to France's demagogic
right-wing politician) because of his fiery denunciations of Serbs, who make
up 11 per cent of the republic's 4.6m population.
Tudjman, used to enduring criticism over the years, shrugged off attempts at
character assassination. He had waited a long time for the moment when
Croatia's Catholic bourgeoisie could find its voice.
Born in 1922, Tudjman joined Tito's communist Partisans during the second
world war. There seemed no going back for this fervent Marxist. Tito
rewarded him by putting him in charge of cadre policy in the Yugoslav
Peoples' Army. In 1961 he became the country's youngest general.
But a stint by Tudjman at the War History Institute in Zagreb, the capital
of Croatia, destroyed his ideological convictions and transformed him into
an ardent nationalist intent on setting Croatia's historical record
straight.
He set out to re-interpret what is the historical event which poisons
relations between Serbs and Croats: namely to suggest that the murder during
the second world war of tens of thousands of Serbs, Jews and gypsies by the
Ustasha, Croatia's Nazi-backed fascist government, was carried out by just a
handful of Croats; and that many Croats had been killed by the Cetniks, or
royalist Serbs.
Tito, a Croat, resented Tudjman's metamorphosis from Yugoslav ideologist to
Croat nationalist. He was sacked from the army in 1967, and imprisoned after
'Croatia's Spring' in 1971. His election as president last year revealed his
great capacity to survive. But his critics are beginning to think he might
be weakening.
If Tudjman is vulnerable, it is because - like Milosevic - his nationalist
constituency is becoming more radical and his authoritarian style of
governing is alienating liberals.
'Tudjman likes to control the political agenda - and this includes the
nationalist agenda as well,' explained a Croat academic who has worked
closely with the president.
'The problem is that he is obsessed with creating a cult of personality
which is embedded in nationalist rhetoric, symbolism and patronage at the
expense of tackling other issues. After a year in office, the CDU has done
nothing to reform the economy or, for that matter, the political
institutions in the republic,' he added. Tudjman's record in the economy has
undoubtedly disappointed the republic's reformers. Instead of introducing
property, ownership rights, and a privatisation programme, he has placed the
republic's five largest enterprises directly in the hands of the state.
'We have seen no signs of a programme aimed at decentralising the economy,'
explained an economist from Zagreb.
His supporters try to defend this poor record. 'Tudjman has had no time to
think about the economy because Serb nationalism will not allow him to focus
on other issues,' said an official from the republic's foreign ministry.
His aides are also quick to dismiss criticism that Tudjman has created his
own nomenklatura from the ranks of the party and nationalist opposition
which was quashed in 1971.
But what Croat liberal intellectuals are increasingly concerned about is
that Tudjman is losing control of the very constituency that catapulted him
into power.
'Croat nationalists are angry with this week's agreement by the presidency
to send in the army to disarm Croats and Serbs in our republic,' commented a
journalist from Zagreb.
'Tudjman does not seem to realise that nationalism has its own momentum.
Other political parties in Croatia will try and get on the nationalist
bandwagon and weaken the CDU. I don't think he will be able to control all
these Croatian hotheads who want independence tomorrow, and whose
nationalism is directed against decent, non-militant Serbs in the republic.'
If Tudjman panders to these elements, he will play into the hands of
Milosevic's nationalist supporters who want to believe that the Serb
minority is being persecuted in Croatia.
If Tudjman tries to temper the very constituency which created him, he will
be accused of betraying Croatia to pressure from Serbia. Milosevic is caught
in the same dilemma.
</TEXT>
<PUB>The Financial Times
