<HEADLINE>
FT  11 MAY 91 / Scottish Conservative Party Conference: Major pledges Pounds
15m aid for Ravenscraig area
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JAMES BUXTON, Scottish Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
MR JOHN MAJOR last night delighted Scottish Tories with a rallying speech in
which he promised immediate financial aid for Lanarkshire, which is
suffering from the closure of two British Steel plants.
He also announced that the European Community summit in December 1992, when
Britain will hold the presidency, will be staged in Edinburgh.
Mr Major said the government is to spend an initial Pounds 15m to help
Lanarkshire, where British Steel recently closed the strip mill at its
Ravenscraig plant and the Clydesdale tube mill.
Scottish Enterprise, the new official economic development body, will spend
the money immediately on site clearance and environmental improvements to
'green over the worst areas of industrial dereliction', he said.
Mr Major said the Scottish Office would shortly receive a study of projects
for the long term revival of the area.
'We will take the necessary steps to help Lanarkshire become once again an
area that will be attractive to new investment and new jobs,' he said.
Referring to the choice of Edinburgh for the European council, or summit, he
said: 'I want Scotland to play a leading role in international affairs. I
want it to be in Edinburgh that Europe signals the final completion of the
single market.'
Mr Major spelt out his opposition to creating a devolved Scottish assembly
with the power to raise taxes, as is demanded by Labour and the Liberal
Democrats, but he did not rule out the idea of Scotland having an assembly
without tax raising powers.
'I know that there is sometimes a feeling, not just in Scotland but in Wales
and England too, that Westminster can be too remote. I believe that
government should be - must be - more receptive to the aspirations of people
throughout the United Kingdom,' he said.
The prime minister's speech rounded off a conference in which the Scottish
Conservatives' mood steadily improved, as they contemplated the approaching
general election and the rise in their standing in the Scottish opinion
polls since Mr Major replaced Mrs Margaret Thatcher.
The audience, which gave him an 8-minute standing ovation at the end of the
speech, appeared genuinely delighted with the new prime minister who, unlike
his predecessor on occasions, did not appear to patronise Scotland.
Mr Tom King, defence secretary, disappointed conference delegates by not
ruling out the closure of the Rosyth naval base in Fife, which employs 2,300
civilians and 1,000 naval personnel.
No decision had been taken to close Rosyth, he said, but the government had
to look at all the possibilities for making savings.
</TEXT>
