<HEADLINE>
FT  11 MAY 91 / High noon for R-R's high flyer: Sir Ralph Robins explains
his company's strategy
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By PAUL BETTS
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
SIR Ralph Robins, the urbane chief executive of Rolls-Royce, yesterday
echoed the classic western line when he said that 'one has to do what one
has to do'.
It is high noon at Rolls-Royce. Hit like the rest of the defence and
aerospace industry by the decline in military spending and the recession in
air travel, the aero-engine maker this week announced plans to double its
job cuts this year to 6,000. It also warned it could be forced to make
compulsory redundancies for the first time since its bankruptcy 20 years
ago.
'I read that General Dynamics is laying off 30,000 people, and they are one
of the recent winners of the big US advan-ced tactical fighter contract,'
Sir Ralph said. 'If the winners are having to do that, what are the losers
going to do?'
Barely 18 months ago, Sir Ralph was brimming with confidence on the future
prospects of his company. Airlines were still ordering new aircraft and
engines in record numbers. The defence business was flat, but at least it
was not declining. After the bankruptcy of 1971, Rolls-Royce had
successfully expanded its family of aero-engines, increased its market share
in the civil-engine market to 20 per cent and built up a strong balance
sheet and healthy profits.
An engineer turned super-salesman, who has spent all his working life with
Rolls-Royce, Sir Ralph still appeared his old, confident self yesterday. 'We
can push ourselves in a very strong competitive position into the civil
business. We've started a five-year plan to improve efficiency. The latest
job cuts are an acceleration of that process,' he explained.
Job cuts are not new at Rolls-Royce, although enforced redundancies would
be. In the past 10 years the company has shed 26,000 jobs, or about one
third of its workforce. The newly-announced reductions not only reflect the
current difficulties of the market but are also part of a long consolidation
of the UK aero-engine and aerospace industry. 'We have sites all over the
country,' Sir Ralph said. 'We must reduce the number of sites. The same
thing is happening at British Aerospace. We are simply in too many places.'
The company plans to close its Leavesden, Hertfordshire, helicopter engine
factory by the end of next year and to concentrate Leavesden's activities at
its Bristol military engine plant. The Parkside industrial and marine engine
plant in Coventry will also be closed, with these activities regrouped at
the nearby Ansty factory. 'It's difficult to justify two sites in Coventry,'
Sir Ralph explained.
He insisted that the dramatic changes in both the defence and civil aircraft
markets had not altered the company's fundamental strategy. 'It is very
straightforward,' he explained. 'It is to become the leading supplier of
high-integrity power systems. That is our mission. It's a long term strategy
which simply doesn't happen overnight.'
But he conceded that this strategy made sense only as long as the company
was competitive. 'We are reacting to changed market forces,' Sir Ralph said.
'We are being more rigorous in the analysis and restructuring of all our
business processes. Our aim is to take out all non-value-added activities in
what we do. We started with our manufacturing processes three years ago. We
are now extending this approach to our business and management processes.'
As the smallest of the 'big three' aero-engine makers, Rolls-Royce has
always been regarded as more vulnerable to a downturn than its two larger US
rivals, General Electric and Pratt &amp; Whitney. Indeed, both US companies have
often said there is not room for three big manufacturers in the fiercely
competitive market.
'They would say that,' said Sir Ralph. 'Over the next 15 years we are
looking at a commercial jet market of some Pounds 120bn and even the
depressed military market is expected to provide about Pounds 100bn of
business. There's plenty of room for three companies.'
Sir Ralph acknowledged that, on the basis of output per man, the Americans
'are better than us'. But he emphasised it was very difficult to measure
productivity. 'How do you put the exchange rate in the formula? We were very
concerned when the pound was at Dollars 2 since 22 per cent of our turnover
is dollar-exposed.'
One way of reducing this exposure was to source more business in dollars.
'More capacity is currently available in the US because of the downturn. If
we find good suppliers , we will tend to use them. But we are not making a
drive to neutralise the dollar effect by sourcing in the US. What we are
seeking is the lowest net cost of supplies.'
Sir Ralph believed Rolls-Royce was closing the gap with GE and Pratt &amp;
Whitney. 'We took 20 per cent of the civil market last year. Pratt took 27
per cent and GE 25 per cent. This says we must be competitive.' But the US
companies are moving all the time, aggressively cutting costs. 'We can't
afford to be left behind,' Sir Ralph stressed.
Rolls-Royce is not worried by its relatively smaller size compared with the
two US companies. But Sir Ralph said he was still worried by the heavy
dependence of the group on the aero-engine business. To expand its business
base, Rolls-Royce acquired two years ago NEI, the power engineering company.
However, aero-engines still account for 60 per cent of turnover. 'I would be
more comfortable with a 50-50 split. A personal ambition is to get our
industrial group the same size as the aero-engine group.'
Sir Ralph also said Rolls-Royce planned to build up its new relationship
with BMW of Germany and this would include building a greenfield engine
plant in east Germany, probably in Berlin.
Rolls-Royce will continue to look for partnerships and joint-ventures with
other companies, but Sir Ralph could not see any chance of a broad alliance
with one of the two big US manufacturers, except on specific projects. He
had no regrets over the decision to break off seven years ago the
short-lived alliance with GE: 'If we had gone with GE, we would have been
squeezed out of the civil business.'
</TEXT>
