<HEADLINE>
FT  11 MAY 91 / Carsberg signals competition for local telecoms
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By PAUL ABRAHAMS and HUGO DIXON
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
A SWITCH towards promoting competition in local telecommunications was
signalled yesterday by Sir Bryan Carsberg, director-general of Oftel, the
industry watchdog. Previous government policy favoured competition in the
long-distance market.
The change in policy was announced as Sir Bryan defended his controversial
proposals to introduce access charges for competitors using BT lines.
The strength of opposition to the introduction of access charges has forced
him to delay completing the details until next month. 'Changes can still be
made if the need is established,' said Sir Bryan.
Sir Bryan denied allegations that the introduction of access charges was
linked to political pressure from the government in the run-up to its
planned sale of more shares in BT.
'Not once has the secretary of state raised the issue of flotation with me,'
he said. 'The decisions made have resulted from the financial analysis I
have made. Selling shares has had nothing to do with it.'
The controversy comes only two months after the publication of the white
paper on telecommunications policy. This proposed the abolition of the
duopoly of BT and Mercury Communications.
BT's rivals have criticised the access charge proposals, saying they would
pay so much to BT that they would not be able to compete.
But Sir Bryan argued that access charges - which compensate BT for its
obligation to operate uneconomical telephone lines - would encourage
Mercury, cable television companies and other groups to build local
networks. He said they would only pay BT if they used BT's lines.
'At present, most competition is in the high-volume, long-distance market,
rather than in the local arena,' said Sir Bryan. 'Over the last few years,
we have been assisting a particular type of entry - the long distance
business of Mercury's. This will help even up the balance in the local
loop.'
Sir Bryan said if new competitors did not pay a fair share of BT's costs,
this would encourage inefficient competition and costs might rise.
He emphasised that the access charge arrangements would be reviewed next
year when BT's main pricing regime is due to be re-examined.
Lex, Page 24
</TEXT>
