<HEADLINE>
FT  11 MAY 91 / Threat increases of Post Office strike
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By DIANE SUMMERS, Labour Staff
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THE THREAT of Post Offices throughout the UK being hit by industrial action
increased yesterday as the Union of Communication Workers said there were
early signs from a ballot that its members had voted for strike action over
pay.
The ballot of 14,500 Post Office counter and clerical employees followed
rejection by UCW negotiators of a 6.8 per cent pay offer.
A strong vote in favour of action would strengthen the union's hand in
further talks with management.
Mr Alan Tuffin, UCW general secretary, said: 'The im-proved finances and
productivity of the Post Office Counters business allows them to make a much
better offer than that.'
Voting on industrial action does not finish until today, and the full ballot
result is not due to be announced until the start of the union's annual
conference in Blackpool tomorrow. However, the UCW said early reports from
branches indicated a 'substantial 'yes' vote' from members.
Separately, the union claimed it had achieved a victory in the High Court by
getting an injunction lifted in a dispute in Liverpool involving postal
engineers. Individual UCW members had refused to cross National
Communications Union picket lines and Royal Mail management claimed the UCW
had taken industrial action without holding a ballot.
The UCW claimed throughout that it had taken no part in stopping members of
the union attending work and now says it wants to see the issue dealt with
fully in open court.
The dispute itself, which arose after the dismissal of two engineers
employed by Royal Mail Engineering and Construction, who went home early
after completing a job, has been concluded with both sides agreeing to abide
by the decision of an industrial tribunal.
