<HEADLINE>
FT  11 MAY 91 / PowerGen may halve order from British Coal
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JULIET SYCHRAVA
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
POWERGEN, the electricity generator, is expected to cut its order from
British Coal from 26m tonnes of coal to between 10m tonnes and 15m tonnes.
National Power, the other generator, also wants to cut orders in the current
round of negotiations with British Coal.
One of the generators also said it expected British Coal to cut its prices
to match cheaper imports. Meanwhile Mr Neil Clarke, British Coal chairman,
insisted at yesterday's annual British Association of Colliery Management
conference that the price struck with the generators should reflect 'the
true value of a large, reliable and consistent supplier'.
The generator added that if British Coal was prepared to cut volumes
substantially, it might secure a better price.
The value of UK coal varied, the generator added. Coal supplied inland was
more valuable than coal supplied on the coast, where imports were more
competitive. At least one of the generators may use the difference in value
to try to negotiate a range of contracts at different prices - in spite of
resistance from British Coal.
Talks between British Coal and the generators have begun informally. The
existing contracts expire in March 1993 but British Coal will want advance
warning if the new contracts are for much smaller volumes.
British Coal has suggested that the generators were unwilling to hold formal
negotiations before the end of the year. British Coal said that would give
it a tough year.
The two generators said yesterday they were willing to talk. 'We are already
talking to coal producers overseas, and are happy to talk to British Coal
when they want to,' said one generator.
Britain's coal industry must improve its productivity to compete with
competitors in countries in which productivity was often four times higher,
Mr David Heathcoat-Amory, energy minister, said at the British Association
for Colliery Management's conference.
Mr John Northard, British Coal's deputy chairman, said at the conference
that productivity in British Coal had increased by almost 9 per cent in the
year to March 1991.
</TEXT>
