<HEADLINE>
FT  11 MAY 91 / Talks on Hong Kong airport to resume
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JOHN ELLIOTT
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   HONG KONG
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
TALKS between Britain and China on Hong Kong's proposed HKDollars 100bn
(Pounds 7.5bn) international airport are to resume in Peking next Saturday
nearly a month after a deadlock over the degree of control China should have
over the project.
No new initiative has emerged for the talks, and British officials say the
UK and Hong Kong governments are not prepared to change their basic offer of
consultation.
They hope China will be prepared to soften its demand for a virtual right of
veto, which the UK rejects. This would open the way for talks on details of
consultation and project financing.
China has been criticising the size and cost of the project for about a
year. It has also been demanding a big say over the planning and execution
in the run-up to 1997, when it regains sovereignty over Hong Kong.
Mr Douglas Hurd, British foreign secretary, warned at the start of last
month's talks that the project might be shelved if the political price of
the control being demanded by China was too great. That possibility will be
considered if next week's talks do not succeed, although at that stage Hong
Kong's private sector might propose an alternative.
Although China has not indicated any definite willingness to compromise,
British diplomats say there have been some signs that it wants to clear the
way for the airport to go ahead. It could then have separate discussions on
its demands for increased consultation, verging on control, over a wide
range of government issues in the run up to 1997.
Britain said last night the talks would end after five days on May 22. This
has been arranged to fit in with other commitments of Mr Andrew Burns, a
senior diplomat from London who will lead the British team. But it serves
the dual purpose of demonstrating that the UK is not prepared for extended
talks if China refuses to compromise.
Hong Kong legislators warned last night that they were not prepared to
sanction finance for the construction of new accommodation for Vietnamese
boat-people. The warning, made by the security committee of the executive
and legislative councils, reflects concern about a sharp increase in the
number of Vietnamese arriving in the colony.
Mr Kwan Cheong Yiu, a 58-year-old broker who runs Golden Harvest Stock
Investment, was yesterday elected senior vice chairman of the Hong Kong
Stock Exchange council. He succeeds Mr Philip Wong, who resigned this week
after a row with the government and the Securities and Futures Commission
involving stock exchange reforms.
Mr Kwan now becomes a front runner to succeed Sir QW Li, chairman, who is to
retire in October.
</TEXT>
