<HEADLINE>
FT  11 MAY 91 / Martens on move to the heart of Europe: The Belgian PM's
plan to change constituencies
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ANDREW HILL
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
IF you're the European Community's longest-serving premier, it's a little
bit undignified to be accused of running scared.
Nobody would have dared level such a charge at Margaret ('I fight, I fight
on to win') Thatcher; as an interview revealed this week, Britain's
ex-leader comforts herself with the knowledge that she was 'never defeated
by the people'.
But Belgium's premier, Mr Wilfried Martens - Mrs Thatcher's successor as the
EC's longest-serving PM - suffered the ignominy of coming second in his
constituency at the last election. In the UK he might have been denied an
eighth term; under Belgium's electoral system he retained his seat.
Political opponents and commentators say fear of defeat was the real reason
why Mr Martens announced yesterday that he would switch constituencies for
the next election, due on January 19 1992. He will head the candidate list
for the Flemish Christian Democrats (CVP) in Brussels, ending 17 years as
member for Ghent in the Belgian chamber of representatives.
'These insinuations show that some politicians will do everything in their
power to dissuade me from my task and to put my decision in the wrong
light,' griped Mr Martens, announcing his candidature for Brussels' elected
upper chamber, the Senate.
Mr Martens wants another four-year term so he can complete the third phase
of Belgian constitutional reform. However, as a committed Europhile, his
'deeper motivation' is that he wants to spearhead efforts to bring all the
EC institutions to Brussels, most notably the European Parliament, which
Strasbourg and the Belgian capital are squabbling over.
Hence his choice of constituency, and his decision not to be tempted into
the race for next president of the European Commission. 'If we don't win
this fight over the site of the Parliament then it goes without saying that
the other political institutions (the Commission and the Council of
Ministers) will leave Brussels,' he warned yesterday.
This clearly cuts no ice with Mr Guy Verhofstadt, the young leader of the
Flemish Liberals, who pipped Mr Martens to the post in Ghent four years ago.
'Le wonder boy' told Flemish television this week that he considered these
were 'phoney arguments' aimed at veiling Mr Martens' retreat from Ghent's
Flemish electorate.
In fact, by standing in Brussels, Mr Martens should increase CVP support in
the bilingual, bicultural capital. But an interesting campaign is still in
prospect.
The constituency chosen is equally divided between Flemings and
French-speaking Walloons, and although Brussels natives seem indifferent to
the festering issue of where the European Parliament should sit, there is
nothing they enjoy more than a nice helping of Fleming-Walloon friction.
</TEXT>
<PUB>The Financial Times
</PUB>
<PAGE>
London Page 2
</PAGE>
</DOC>
