FT  11 MAY 91 / US plans increased access to phone lines
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By MARTIN DICKSON
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   NEW YORK
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
THE Federal Communications Commission (FCC) has taken a big step towards
stimulating competition in the monopolistic local telephone system with a
proposal which would force service providers to allow rivals to plug into
their networks, writes Martin Dickson in New York.
The FCC, which oversees the US telecommunications industry, would like to
see the plan adopted within the next year.
It would primarily benefit independent telephone companies which have sprung
up in cities and which use new fibre optic lines to link businesses and
long-distance telephone carriers.
The independents allow customers to connect to long distance networks much
more cheaply that the local monopolies, which rely on long distance charges
for much of their revenues.
The plan will initially cover private, or 'special access" lines used by
companies to connect their own buildings.
</TEXT>
