<HEADLINE>
FT  11 MAY 91 / Peace move rejected by Croats and Serbs
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By LAURA SILBER
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   BELGRADE
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
THE Yugoslav state presidency's attempt to avert a civil war between Croatia
and Serbia threatened to collapse yesterday following growing criticism from
the republics' political parties.
There was no sign that Croats or Serbs were planning to hand over their arms
to either the republic or federal authorities as ordered after an agreement
was hammered out by the country's collective presidency on Thursday.
A statement from Croatia's main opposition parties said: 'Croatia is at war,
and the defence of the republic is the duty of all it citizens. The
authorities must use all means to defend the republic.'
In Serbia Mr Mirko Jovic, head of the Serbian National Defence, an
ultra-nationalist opposition party, called on volunteers to fight to defend
Serbs in Croatia. He said Serbs would 'not recognise any decisions made by
Yugoslavia's puppet presidency'.
The agreement ordered the disarming of citizens and the demobilisation of
Croatia's police reservists in areas of ethnic turmoil in the western
republic.
The accord also gave the federal army and police authority over the
predominantly Serbian province of Krajina, which has declared independence
from Croatia.
Croats regard the army as pro-Serbian and have criticised the presidency's
decision to give the military sweeping powers.
Yesterday's statement by Croatia's 12 opposition parties said the
presidency's plan 'threatens the sovereignty and integrity of the republic.'
It also called for the resignation of Mr Stipe Mesic, Croatia's
representative to the eight-member state presidency.
Mr Mesic, a moderate, is scheduled to become federal president next
Wednesday as part of the annual rotation among the republics of the post.
Serb extremists and army hardliners have wanted to prevent him from assuming
the presidency.
Mr Frane Golem, the foreign minister of Croatia, said in an interview in
Austria and reported in Vjesnik, Croatia's newspaper: 'We (Croats) are ready
to fight, to use any occasion to become independent.'
Western diplomats are pessimistic about the prospects for any long-term
peace between Croats and the Serbian minority in the western republic in
which 18 people were killed in clashes last week.
Man in the News, Page 8
</TEXT>
