<HEADLINE>
FT  11 MAY 91 / Major pledge on public services
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By PHILIP STEPHENS, Political Editor
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
MR JOHN MAJOR sought to set out his personal agenda for the general election
campaign yesterday with a pledge to unveil this summer the most
comprehensive initiative ever launched to improve the quality of public
services.
Addressing a packed rally to end the Scottish Conservative conference in
Perth, the prime minister discouraged speculation that the election could
come as early as next month. Earlier, he gently chided journalists for being
in a 'hurry' for the election campaign.
Senior ministers said it was 'touch and go' whether the Tories would hold
Monmouth in next week's by-election. A poor performance at the seat, where
the party is defending a majority of more than 9,500, would confirm the
cabinet's view that the autumn is the earliest possible time for Mr Major to
seek a fresh mandate.
Mr Major's speech, building on his proposals earlier this year for a
Citizens' Charter to underpin a more efficient public sector, came at the
end of week which has seen government and opposition locked in a bitter
pre-election battle.
Attempts by the Tories to push Labour on to the defensive over its tax and
spending - emphasised again by Mr Major yesterday - have been hampered by
the continuing political row about the impact of the health service reforms.
Even as Mr Major was speaking, Mr Neil Kinnock was completing a week of
assaults on the Tories' health service reforms at a rally in the Monmouth
constituency.
Calling on voters to signal their dissent by voting 'no' to the government,
the opposition leader launched a fierce personal attack on the prime
minister for his part in formulating Tory policy during his time in
government.
Mr Major, in a move designed to put in place one of the central building
blocks of his election manifesto, said he would publish later this summer a
white paper on the Citizens' Charter. It will include a mixture of
incentives for public sector workers to deliver better services and measures
to compensate consumers who receive poor treatment.
Mr Major cited the regulatory framework for the performance of privatised
industries such as telecommunications and gas supply as a model for services
which remain in the public sector.
The charter programme would have four main strands: more competition and
privatisation; improved incentives and penalties to improve performance; new
inspectorates; and, where possible, mechanisms for direct compensation to
consumers.
If the general election date is pushed back further into 1992, Mr Major
plans to introduce legislation in the autumn to implement the charter.
In a reference to the furore over the health service, the prime minister
said he remained determined to push ahead with reforms which provided better
patient care by ensuring that NHS resources were properly spent.
He said Labour's plans on public spending and National Insurance
contributions could add as much as 10p to the present 25p basic rate of tax.
He sought to build on the Tories' recent modest recovery in Scotland by
announcing plans to inject a further Pounds 15m aid into the depressed
region of Lanarkshire.
Conference reports, Page 6
Putting on a new face, Page 8
Long View, Weekend I
</TEXT>
