<HEADLINE>
FT  11 MAY 91 / Bank damps hopes of rate cut
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By RACHEL JOHNSON, Economics Staff
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THE BANK of England yesterday moved to stamp out speculation of an early cut
in interest rates - but left the markets half expecting one next week.
Hopes of a cut have been building strongly ahead of the sharp fall in
inflation likely to be announced next Friday, the day after the Monmouth
by-election. The government has, in cutting base rates four times since
mid-February, twice done so on the same day as it announced falls in the
retail prices index.
In a deliberate squeeze on the market which it agreed with the Treasury in
advance, the Bank damped speculation of a cut by lending Pounds 965m at the
current base rate of 12 per cent for a period of 14 days.
As it had declined to buy Treasury bills yielding 11 1/2 per cent from the
market earlier in the day, this tightened monetary conditions and underlined
its desire to see the 12 per cent base rate stick.
It is thought the Bank took tough action after earlier signals failed to
take effect. On Thursday it was forced to keep the market short of funds the
day after Mr Robin Leigh-Pemberton, the governor, cautioned against reading
too much into the predicted fall in inflation to 6.2 per cent.
He warned then that the headline rate's fall from 8.2 per cent would reveal
'no more' than the effect of last year's imposition of the community charge
dropping out of the 12-month figures, aided by recent interest rate
reductions.
However, as next week is expected to bring a fresh crop of recessionary data
as well as a sharp fall in inflation, hopes of a  1/2 percentage point cut
remain alive.
In the City, analysts pointed out a recent precedent for a cut in interest
rates during a period of central bank lending at the current base rate. In
late February, the rate was cut to 13 per cent just five days after the Bank
lent to the market at 13 1/2 per cent for seven days.
Sterling rates are already discounting a cut, while the pound is firm on the
foreign exchanges. It closed yesterday in London at DM2.9650 from DM2.9700,
well above its European exchange rate mechanism rate. The three-month
interbank rate was unchanged from Thursday's closing level of around 11 1/2
per cent.
In a market survey yesterday, MMS International, the financial research
company, suggested that the authorities may 'sneak in' a cut before the
Monmouth poll.
Money Markets, Page 13
Lex, Page 24
</TEXT>
<PUB>The Financial Times
</PUB>
<PAGE>
London Page 1
</PAGE>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>FT911-462</DOCNO>
<PROFILE>_AN-BELAGADFFT</PROFILE>
<DATE>910511
</DATE>
<HEADLINE>
FT  11 MAY 91 / Clocks, Watches &amp; Jewellery: Double about-turn at auction -
Richard Garnier picks his way through the sales and the different sectors of
the market
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
YOU might be forgiven for thinking a watch is a watch is a . . . until you
come to buy, or sell, or collect them at auction, that is. For the market
divides several ways into decorative, early and precision for pocket
watches, which have recently been joined by wristwatches.
The most serious section of the market is decorative - watches, mostly
dating from the 18th and 19th centuries, whose chief attraction is the style
and decoration of the case and dial.
These are to be distinguished from early watches, that is those from before
the 1680s. Early watches were always abysmal timekeepers and should not have
been altered to improve performance. They were created as expensive toys for
courtiers; as a result, they have some of the most sumptuously decorated
cases ever made.
Precision watches are the youngest sector of the pocket watch market. They
include complicated watches with multitudinous features, such as
minute-repeating, perpetual calendar work allowing for leap years and double
or triple split second-hands for timing two or three runners in tandem, as
well as those which are just very accurate timekeepers.
Decorative watches had been the staple of sales until the 1970s, when early
watches shot to prominence, soon followed by precision.
In the early to mid-1980s, however, wristwatches came into play, and the
term 'estate watches' was coined to cover quality wristwatches from the
1950s to 1970s which were not strictly vintage. It was all so easy, as long
as you stuck to the six big names of Patek Philippe, Vacheron and
Constantin, Rolex, Audemars Piguet, Cartier, and Breguet.
It is a story that has parallels in the Impressionist and Post-Impressionist
art market. The signs were all there in a recent April sale at Christie's in
London. The sale was 66 per cent sold overall, but that was held up by the
90 per cent success rate in the clocks section of the sale. Christie's Tim
Bourne admits that estimates will have to be revised downwards next time.
A similar trend was evident at Phillips' Bond Street sale earlier this
month, where wristwatches took a severe knocking and accounted for the
majority of unsolds. Rachel Cameron at Phillips cites estimates that were
very reasonable in terms of past market levels, yet which failed to excite
much interest. This was particularly true of Patek but less so with Rolex,
which has a more rugged appeal.
Early Rolexes in octagonal or cushion cases, many in 9 carat, held up quite
well at Phillips, but these are less significant, being down market. More
upbeat models, including the Rolex Submariner (still in production), are in
very short supply, being all the rage for Italians as beachwear. With the
majority of other marques it is hit and miss, so the reorientation of the
market may not have completely run its course.
However, it is not all gloom in the wristwatch sector. Tina Millar of
Sotheby's points out that an octagonal arrow-dial wristwatch made Dollars
209,000 this February in New York, in the middle of the Gulf crisis. It is,
of course, a very rare watch and a similarly dialled pocket watch commonly
sells for around Dollars 10,000 at auction.
Similarly, at Christie's in Geneva, Ruth Zandberg has hopes for a 1924
Audemars Piguet square dialled wristwatch in a white gold case. In itself,
that would not be exceptional, but its minute repeating facility makes the
difference - and also explains the bullish pre-sale estimate.
Patek Philippe watches are generally not so rare, whether perpetual calendar
or less complicated examples. Gone are the days when the prices realised in
one auction established the benchmark for the low estimates in the next
sale, which was then left far behind. The market has changed from those
halcyon days of 1989, when Habsburg held their themed sale of Pateks.
Habsburg repeated the formula with the House of Breguet in mid-April.
Projected to total FFr15m (Pounds 1.49m), the final result of some FFr12.34m
was only partially satisfactory as nearly 25 per cent of lots remained
unsold. Nevertheless, the sold total shows that those that did sell
performed well, particularly when mechanically interesting or associated
with a good historical prominence.
For instance, a watch picked up at a Phillips London sale in 1989 for a song
at Pounds 1,500 or so as an unrecognised Breguet, once reunited with its
English Royal prominence, was resold at the theme sale for FFr36,000.
Christie's gets in on the act with a theme sale of Swatch watches in 178
lots on June 15, preceded by a talk by Ernest Thomke, president of S. M. H,
the manufacturers. This Swatch classics sale is an attempt to follow the 100
per cent sell-out success of Sotheby's similar sale in Milan of September
last year.
The June sale includes such low number production models as the chronographs
(stopwatches) and the Mimmo Paladino, estimated at SFr40,000 plus and made
in a limited edition of 120. The Mimmo Paladino was given as a prize in the
1989 'Draw Your Swatch' competition, and presented to leading figures in
politics, finance, sport, the arts and show business.
Meanwhile, Crott of Germany have offered 144 lots by the German precision
makers Lange &amp; Sohne of Dresden, ranging from published literature, through
wristwatches, to grande complication and tourbillon pocket watches.
The Crott sale was dominated by pocket watches, which seems to be the
healthiest sector of the market at the moment. Lange is principally a German
(and to a lesser extent American) market, but both they and other superb
precision watches had performed well against the general run of pocket
watches over the last five or six years.
Most other pocket watches have been so lacklustre since the mid-1980s that
not only had many become less valuable in market terms since then but were
even making less in real terms.
That was until this spring. The first signs were evident last summer. To
start with, the number of unsold decorative pocket watches at auction fell.
Now a definite price advance is in progress.
Rachel Cameron at Phillips is delighted by the prices achieved for enamel
watches in its sale - many with damage. One such, dating from the early 19th
century, seemingly correctly estimated at Pounds 400 to Pounds 600, realised
Pounds 1,700: another similarly estimated made Pounds 1,150.
The exception in this sale was Patek, which followed its own house form, as
Gondolo models were down to about half their previous level of around Pounds
2,000. Tina Millar's May 30 sale at Sotheby's London includes an 1857
hallmarked Parkinson &amp; Frodsham watch in a diamond set gold case
attractively enamelled with portraits of unidentified sitters. There must be
a premium for the buyer who can solve their identity on a pre-sale estimate
of Pounds 3,500-Pounds 5,000.
A stunning ladies pendant watch by Cartier set with rubies and with a black
enamelled mosaic pattern (Pounds 5,000-Pounds 7,000 estimate) is also
included. If this bears out the delight Tina Millar expresses for it, along
with a Dittisheim Chronometre de Bord watch (for surveying purposes,
estimate Pounds 3,000-Pounds 4,000), it should mean the heart is back in
watches for collecting, to be appreciated for what they are, rather than to
be used as an adjunct to a social trend. Genuine collectors must always be
best for the market.
Richard Garnier is Head of the Antique Clock Department at Garrard
</TEXT>
