<HEADLINE>
FT  11 MAY 91 / Clocks, Watches &amp; Jewellery: The jewellery that packs a
punch - The creativity of the younger designers
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By LUCIA VAN DER POST
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
LONG ago, when our mothers were young, the only jewellery to be seen out in
was real jewellery. Those were the days when all life's great rites of
passage - the 18th birthday, the engagement, the marriage, the first child,
the anniversaries - were marked by judicious visits to the family jeweller
to find suitable offerings with which to celebrate the day.
It wasn't until the 1920s, when Coco Chanel imbued her loops of artificial
'pearls' with a chic beyond price, that costume jewellery began to take off.
While the design of the conventional 'haut jouallerie' remained static,
relying on the inherent value of the materials and the size of the stones to
do the selling, costume jewellery took off, appealing to those for whom
design was more important than worth.
While costume jewellery flourished, there were other tastes that needed
satisfying, and in the 1960s it became clear that the role of jewellery was
changing. Chanel had intuitively sensed that the days when jewellery was
primarily a means of displaying wealth and power were over, and cleverly
tapped the desire for some highly fashionable, modish women to cock a snook
at accepted values with her outrageous fakes, but there was now a role for
jewellery with high artistic content. Jewellery didn't need to convey wealth
or status; it could be an outlet for serious creative talent.
We began to see a blossoming of talent among young designers whose work was
genuinely creative, even innovative, part art, part craft, part technical
skill. Whereas much high street jewellery used to be churned out by
manufacturers content to produce designs that machines could handle, the
artist jeweller was much more concerned with the excitements of genuine
innovation than with the intrinsic worth of the materials used. Young
designers began to turn to semi-precious stones, to materials like wood and
stone, rubber and paper, excited by new shapes and forms.
The Goldsmiths' Company, sensing that things were changing fast, began to
foster exhibitions in which the work of young jewellers could be seen and
bought. The work was often astonishing value for money - young designers
working from home or small workshops, usually ill-informed on matters of
time sheets and overheads, sold wonderfully creative, innovative work for
very low sums.
Over the years, the Goldsmiths' Company's annual touring exhibitions and the
host of art/craft galleries that sprang up all over the country have done a
great deal both to find a market for the artists' work and to introduce the
public to these new and sometimes intriguing jewellery forms.
Galleries such as Electrum, in London's South Molton Street, were the
pioneers of this movement, providing a platform for the most creative and
avant-garde talents. Today, jewellers like Gerda Flockinger, Jane Allen,
Karl Bartosik and Wendy Ramshaw have international reputations and have
opened the eyes of many to the potential excitement of truly innovative
jewellery.
The establishment jewellers, too, have had to adapt to changing times.
Modern-minded jewellers have needed to create affordable lines for the
growing legion of working women. At Tiffany's, Rosa Monckton says they
always have a line of jewellery that the working woman can buy when she
feels she deserves a reward. 'When she gets promoted or lands a new job, she
will spend anything up to about Pounds 1,000 on a piece by Paloma Picasso or
an Elsa Peretti to add a spark to her designer suit.'
At Garrard and Mappin &amp; Webb, they began to notice that the call for tiaras
and diamond pendants was no longer pressing enough to sustain a modern
business. They have introduced lines that might tempt a woman out
window-shopping or a chap who wants to woo but doesn't have a trust fund to
back him. As more women than ever are going out to work, the demand for real
jewellery that packs something of a fashionable punch has grown - they need
pieces that can take through from the school-run first thing in the morning,
to the boardroom meeting and on to dinner in a restaurant.
Even the grandest of grand Bond Street names have found the last few months
tough going, and there is an increasing realisation that though the very
rich will always be with us (and at Boucheron, interestingly, they have
found that sales of the very high-priced items have suffered less than sales
lower down the scale), there may well not be enough of them to keep them in
the style to which they have grown accustomed.
Changing times need changing attitudes, and the challenge for the big
jewellers is to make sure that the women who feels in need of a little
'retail therapy' chooses to find it with them rather than in among the
designer jackets. Not only does she now have the confidence to buy her
jewellery for herself rather than waiting for her lover or her husband to do
it for her, but she makes a much more demanding buyer - value alone is not
enough to bring the credit cards out, what she wants is something that
speaks of her discerning taste, her wit, her chic as well.
</TEXT>
<PUB>The Financial Times
</PUB>
<PAGE>
London Page XXII Photograph Gold beetle and bug bracelet by Paul Preston
(Omitted).
</PAGE>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>FT911-467</DOCNO>
<PROFILE>_AN-BELAGADAFT</PROFILE>
<DATE>910511
</DATE>
<HEADLINE>
FT  11 MAY 91 / Clocks, Watches &amp; Jewellery: Bright spot in the gloom - In
spite of the recession, prices for antique jewellery are holding up well and
sales seem little affected
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By LUCIA VAN DER POST
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
The jewellery business is one of the few bright spots in an otherwise gloomy
economic scene. Right at the top of the market, in that world where rising
mortgage interest rates hold no fear, and right at the bottom, where a pair
of earrings can do wonders for a woman's morale, sales seem little affected.
In the sale rooms, the main bar to ever-increasing volume is not the lack of
willing buyers but the fact that supplies, far from rising, are strictly
limited.
In times like these there is something infinitely reassuring about antique
jewellery. Prices for signed pieces by the great French jewellers -
Boucheron, Cartier, Van Cleef &amp; Arpels, La Cloche - have held their own and
more through the months of war and recession, while truly remarkable pieces
 -such as the huge, beautiful sapphire brooch that Christie's sells next
week in Geneva, or the Van Cleef &amp; Arpels mutli-gem set brooch that Phillips
sold, again in Geneva, last November  - continue to command the sort of
attention and prices that made the 1980s boom.
At the less extravagant end of the market, Georgian rings, Victorian
brooches and turn-of-the-century necklaces not only have considerable charm
and are a delight to wear but, most important, their value is tried and
tested. Buying modern may be exciting, but it is usually a much less secure
investment.
There is a salutory tale told of what happened when one of London's leading
modern jewellers needed to sell most of his wares. In spite of a
high-profile name and a reputation for exciting design, the auction house
charged with the sale only managed to realise, on average, some 10 per cent
of the listed retail price - in other words, his rent, mark-up and
manufacturing costs were so high that some 90 per cent of the price of each
piece was attributable to things unrelated to its intrinsic value.
At auction, for example, although each house charges commission, there are
no high retail mark-ups, no long line of people who all need to take their
cut. All this means that it is still possible to find a good Georgian or
early Victorian piece for anything between Pounds 800 and Pounds 1,000;
those with up to Pounds 2,000 to spend are almost spoiled for choice. On top
of that, if ever the owner needs to sell, he or she stands a fair chance of
getting their money back.
To the would-be buyer the best advice is the oldest - choose pieces that
give you real pleasure, for then you will always have a bargain, no matter
what you paid. Go, if possible, for a piece with a designer's name. The
collector's market for named pieces is increasing daily: Mark Twain's
memorable remark about land - 'they aren't making any more of it' - applies
just as surely to antique jewellery. An instantly recognisable piece by a
known designer can do nothing but become more sought-after.
As antique real jewellery becomes more scarce, a new market has recently
opened up - costume jewellery. The craze for the costume jewellery of
certain distinguished houses started in the US, but in the last few years it
has spread to this country. Christie's, for instance, now holds regular
sales at its South Kensington auction rooms. It all started about two years
ago when an elderly woman with a large personal collection came in wanting
to know if they could sell it. They could and they did, proving that here
was yet another market to explore.
Costume jewellery from before the Second World War and the late 1940s and
early 1950s is usually of high quality, but when it comes to collecting, a
certain lineage is everything. Trifari, Chanel, Christian Dior, Schiaparelli
are the golden names at the top of collectors' lists but look out, too, for
Mazer, Jomaz and Boucher.
However, some auction houses (Phillips, for instance) have found that
whereas a year or two ago old costume jewellery was a hot seller, the market
has since settled down and only the best, the really wearable, finely-made
pieces are reaching the prices their sellers hope for.
If you are looking for single pieces to wear and enjoy, you may well find
dealers a better bet than sale-rooms. For instance, Christie's now has a
minimum commission charge of Pounds 20, so only the larger and more valuable
pieces are sold individually - the less distinguished or less expensive
pieces are grouped in lots ranging from Pounds 150 upwards.
Rooting around an individual dealer's collection can still bring its rewards
 -there are some who were buying individual pre-war pieces by Miriam Haskell
for well under Pounds 40 just last year. There are less distinguished pieces
of costume jewellery (often only in the sense that they are of unknown
provenance, not of inherently less charm) lurking in stalls at Gray's
Antique Market, at Alfie's and all the usual marketplaces that represent
wonderful value for money compared with the offerings in the costume
jewellery departments of most stores.
As with any jewellery, the golden rule is to buy the highest quality you can
afford. There are few undiscovered bargains to be had. Everybody seems
agreed that buyers are becoming more knowledgeable - about stones, settings
and designs - so anybody risking their own taste at an auction had better do
their homework first.
Serious collectors need to know whether the piece is good for its type, how
its setting or workmanship relates to similar pieces, how its designer is
rated and just how fine the intrinsic materials are before investing their
hard-earned cash in a valuable piece. Some auction houses (Phillips, for
instance) have found that whereas a year or two ago, old costume jewellery
was a hot seller, the market has settled down and only the best, the really
wearable, the finely-made pieces are reaching the prices their sellers hope
for.
</TEXT>
<PUB>The Financial Times
</PUB>
