<HEADLINE>
FT  11 MAY 91 / Clocks, Watches &amp; Jewellery: Luxury route out of recession -
The renewed interest in mechanical watches
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JOHN GOODALL
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Like every other industry, the watch market is in recession - but recession
for some watch manufacturers would be the envy of their counterparts in
other trades.
Take, for example, Cartier and its sister brands, Piaget and Baume &amp;
Mercier. Just days before April's European Watch Clock and Jewellery Fair in
Basle - generally considered the most important of its type in the world -
they organised their own break-away up-market trade exhibition in Geneva.
The Cartier brands invited only their most important customers so that they
could buy in luxurious, dignified surroundings, without the noise, crowds
and bustle of the very much larger Basle Fair: yes, even in recession, the
watch halls of the Basle Fair were bustling.
Imagine the expense of flying 2,500 guests from around the globe to Geneva
for a few days. Add the cost of luxury accommodation, meals and
entertainment, not to mention limousines to collect guests from the airport
and shuttle them between hotels, entertainment and, not least, the
exhibition. What results would be needed for such an exercise to be judged a
success?
Speaking for the three Cartier group companies and the two top independent
brands (Gerald Genta and Daniel Roth) which joined the new show, Cartier
president Alain Perrin said they were very happy: the number of buyers
greatly exceeded expectations and sales for the five brands in the first two
days of the five-day exhibition totalled Dollars 166m.
Compared with the first two days of the Basle Fair last year, before
recession had begun to bite and before the Gulf war had savaged demand from
the Middle East, sales by the five watch companies in the Geneva show were
up almost 18 per cent. On top of this awesome performance, the same brands
were also exhibiting in Basle and no doubt picked up further orders from
those customers who were not invited to Geneva and from those unable to
visit the new luxury show.
Mr Perrin has already confirmed that the International Salon of Fine
Watchmaking will take place next year and the organising committee will be
prepared to consider accepting up to four more participants. However, any
expansion of the Geneva venture would cause considerable political upheaval
in Switzerland's normally tranquil industry and no major company will make
such a move lightly.
Mr Perrin and his associates undoubtedly want to attract Rolex and Patek
Philippe to join them in the sophisticated surroundings they have created
for their new exhibition, but it seems that neither company is likely to
fulfil his dream - at least until the new salon is firmly established.
In Geneva and in Basle, it was clear that interest in mechanical watches is
returning, but it would be wrong to suggest that quartz timepieces have had
their day. As Cartier's managing director, Pierre Hacquet, explains, some of
his clients want a watch only as a piece of jewellery. They do not care
about the technical side; but others are now more concerned about what is
inside a watch.
'We could not ignore the evolution of technology. Demand for some years has
been for more precise watches. Today, the trend is towards mechanical
movements. I would now like clients to recognise that the movement of a
watch is as important as the case', he says.
Quartz watches are certainly far more precise than mechanical watches will
ever be, but buyers are beginning to rediscover the satisfaction of knowing
that inside their watch is a marvel of mechanical engineering, often
decorated and polished by hand to make it almost a work of art.
Perhaps such buyers also realise that whereas spare parts for many quartz
watches will not be available in 10, 20 or 30 years' time, a good watchmaker
should still be able to produce a single spare part for a mechanical watch
in 200 or 300 years' time. Quartz watches do not have built-in obsolescence,
but with such rapid progress in electronics, it is evolution which will make
quartz watches obsolete as each model is superseded by a more advanced
replacement.
At the moment, mechanical watches account for only 10,000 of the 300,000
watches sold by Cartier each year. Pierre Hacquet now anticipates expansion
of Cartier's mechanical watch production at the rate of 25 per cent a year
until it reaches 25,000 pieces - far higher than is achieved by any of the
top firms which specialise in fine mechanical timepieces.
This year's other trend, also noticeable in Geneva, was towards the
production of limited editions of special watches. This year, for the first
time, Cartier are producing four, including a reversible version of the
classic 'tank' design.
Philippe Leopold-Metzger, Cartier's managing director in the UK, says that
Cartier now plans to produce three or four limited editions of mechanical
watches every year. Each series will be limited to between 250 and 350
pieces.
The author is Editor of International WristWatch
</TEXT>
<PUB>The Financial Times
</PUB>
<PAGE>
London Page XXI
</PAGE>
