<DATE>910511
</DATE>
<HEADLINE>
FT  11 MAY 91 / Clocks, Watches &amp; Jewellery: Basle shows the collectable
face of watches - The latest trends and recent developments at the European
Watch, Clock and Jewellery Fair
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JOHN GOODALL
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
FOR nine days every April, the Musternesse in picturesque Basle,
Switzerland's equivalent of the National Exhibition Centre, becomes the
Mecca of the watch world. Attracting professional watch buyers (and
collectors and enthusiasts) from all over the world, the European Watch,
Clock and Jewellery Fair is considered by many to be the world's most
important trade exhibition; it is also open to the public.
Each year, thousands make the annual pilgrimage to Basle to try to pinpoint
the latest trends and to catch up on the latest developments - not only in
the Swiss watch industry, but also in other parts of the world, now that
Japanese and other manufacturers are admitted to what was once a strictly
European fair.
There is little doubt that in many countries, watches are becoming more
collectable than ever before. The last two or three years have seen the
start of a new industry: publishing consumer magazines for watch
enthusiasts. These, in turn, have stimulated interest, awareness and
understanding. They have enabled people to appreciate watches more for their
beauty and for the immense technical skills and creativity which go into the
production of fine mechanical watches.
To some extent, this is a chicken and egg situation: watch magazines have
given readers the information necessary to be able to appreciate watches to
the full, but at the same time growing levels of interest in watches have
stimulated the appearance of such publications.
To a growing and appreciative audience, the watch is much more than merely
functional. Wristwatch sales in the auction rooms over the last two or three
years have seen prices rise sharply. Time and time again, new world record
prices have been established, some of them during the worldwide recession.
At the Basle Fair, where some of the exhibitors' stands cost Pounds 1m or
more to build, there was mood of relief that the buyers were back. A few
months ago, during the Gulf war, many feared the show would prove to be a
disaster for the watch industry, but with worst of the crisis over, business
was better than might have been expected.
It would be wrong to imply that order books were bulging, but many
exhibitors claimed they could see light at the end of the tunnel of
recession. Times have been tough for most manufacturers, but a few of the
most prestigious brands still admit with some embarrassment that there is a
waiting list of three or four years for some of their finest  - and most
expensive - models.
This year, soft, curved lines are the order of the day and complicated dials
are still popular in both quartz and mechanical watches. Moon phase dials
have been very popular for several years, but their popularity is beginning
to wane. The craze for chronographs - watches which incorporate stop watches
 -continues, but this fashion may have peaked. At the moment, it is the
designers of the finest mechanical watch movements who are being put to the
greatest test as public demand for ever more complicated watches continues
to grow.
Another clear trend has been the announcement of limited editions. There has
long been a tradition among the top houses to produce limited editions of
some important pieces, but the last 12 months have seen manufacturers at
every level of the industry jumping on the limited edition bandwagon.
Undoubtedly, consumer interest in limited editions has been spurred on by
thoughts of higher values at auction, in years to come, for a numbered
specimen of special watch. This belief was perhaps boosted by the remarkable
prices paid at an auction in Milan last autumn of Swatch watches, where some
limited editions attracted spectacular and totally unexpected prices.
However, as more and more companies join in the fray, the importance of a
limited edition may be devalued.
Patek Philippe, as always, attracted attention for the remarkable design and
workmanship in their complicated watches, but they also produce designs
whose attraction lies in their classical simplicity. At the other extreme,
they offer lavishly gemset creations. They are one of the companies still
embarrassed by the length of the waiting lists for a few of their most
complicated models.
Girard-Perregaux commemorated their bicentenary by producing a new version
of their famous Tourbillon with three golden bridges. Only two editions have
been made before - one in the 19th century and the other at the beginning of
the 1980s - but both were pocket watches. (A tourbillon is a watch in which
the entire escapement is fitted into a cage which constantly revolves, a
device invented by A. L. Breguet). Girard-Perregaux have spent the last
three years creating a superb wristwatch version. The first was completed in
January and about 20 specimens will be made this year. Production will
continue over a period of five years. Girard-Perregaux will also mark their
bicentenary with a limited series of watches, called Anno 1991 and produced
in two sizes.
Ebel announced limited editions of their Voyager self-winding world time
watch in 18 carat gold, which they have called Atlas. The dial features a
map of the world, enamelled either with the continents in various colours
or, for the sports-minded, in the five Olympic colours. On a strap, the
price is Pounds 6,285; on a gold bracelet, Pounds 11,840. There are four
series - combinations of the dial variations and strap or bracelets, each
numbered from one to 80, and all water resistant to 30m.
The other new design from Ebel is named after one of the finest wines: the
attributes of a truly distinguished Bordeaux wine, a Grand Cru Classe called
Lichine, provided the inspiration for this new model, the pride of the
Beluga range which was already the company's flagship collection. In perfect
harmony with today's watch fashions, it has generously rounded lines and
adds a distinctively masculine accent to the Beluga line. Like its namesake,
the Lichine is expected to attract connoisseurs. Interestingly, it is
available not only with an Ebel-designed quartz movement, but also with a
twin-barrel self-winding movement.
This year, many of the top houses are incorporating power reserve indicators
(to show the amount of power remaining in the mainspring) in some of their
finest models. Ebel's Lichine is a good example, with the power reserve
display featured on one of three subsidiary dials on one of the more
complicated executions of this important new design.
Jaeger-leCoultre are perhaps best known for their Reverso design, the body
of which can be flipped over, with the dial innermost, for added protection.
This well-established classic is 60 years old this year, and to mark the
occasion Jaeger-leCoultre have produced a special version with a power
reserve indicator in the top left hand corner of the oblong dial. The case
is slightly larger than that of the classic Reverso, but in the same
proportions. Its 37 components are cut out of a block of rose-coloured gold
and polished, decorated and assembled by hand. The beautiful hand-wound
movement can be admired through the transparent sapphire crystal case-back.
The rose-gold version is being produced in a limited edition of just 500
pieces. From May next year, yellow and grey versions will be produced in an
unlimited series with traditional rhodium-plated movements.
Breitling offered an interesting new selection in their Astromat collection.
Of particular interest was the Astromat Chron Longitude. This chronograph
provides a permanent second time zone indication by means of a second hour
hand which, when not needed, can be concealed beneath the first one at the
touch of a button. A self-winding, high frequency mechanical movement
provides a small seconds hand and date indication, and it also has a
short-term time measurement function by means of the centre seconds hand, as
well as 30-minute and 12-hour totalizers.
A limited series of 38 watches with dials carved out of rock from Mars has
been introduced this year by Corum. For several years they have been making
meteorite watches whose dials are thin slices of meteorite, but the dials of
this latest series are produced from fragments of Martian rock which landed
on Earth in 1962. Proof that the meteorites came from Mars was provided by
analysis of the planet's surface carried out by the Viking Mars probe in
1976. These watches have cases in platinum and red gold, as well as a
certificate of origin for the unique dials.
A new name is about to appear in the British market and first recations
suggest that it will prove very successful. Sector is a collection of sports
watches which combine Italian design with Swiss technology. Following
tremendous success in the Italian market, one of the most important in
Europe, Sector watches will soon be appearing in British shops. Although the
brand is quite young, worldwide sales are expected to reach 450,000 units
this year and to double in 1994.
For those seeking the ultimate in precision, there are radio controlled
watches by Junghans. Radio controlled clocks have been available for three
or four years, and now Junghans have miniaturised the same technology for
use in a wristwatch. Last year they produced a digital version, but this
year they have introduced the much more acceptable analogue version.
Radio controlled watches never need adjustment: they receive time signals
from the world's most accurate clock, and should be accurate to within about
one second in one million years. Each watch has a quartz movement which is
regulated every few minutes, if necessary, by the radio time signal. As a
result, the watch will set itself to the correct time after a new battery
has been put in, and will change from summer to winter time and vice versa.
The eternal problems of showing the day of the week, the date and the month
are also handled automatically.
Technically advanced electronic watches are not, of course, the exclusive
preserve of European manufactures. In Basle, Seiko introduced the world's
first perpetual calendar watch which shows the right date for 1,100 years.
Most perpetual calendar watches will face problems in the year 2100, when it
will be necessary to lose one day. Most pre-programmed mechanical and quartz
perpetual calendar watches will no longer show the correct date, but Seiko's
latest technology overcomes this problem. As a bonus, this model also
incorporates an alarm which can be set as much as one month in advance.
For the fast-growing band of watch enthusiasts from top sports personalities
to musicians, politicians, financiers and advertising agency executives, the
choice is enormous and manufacturers are responding quickly to changing
demand. The last few years have shown the finest examples to be excellent
investments, but a wise adviser is always likely to point out that, like
most other investments, values may go down as well as up.
The author is Editor of International WristWatch
</TEXT>
<PUB>The Financial Times
</PUB>
<PAGE>
London Page XX Photograph Ebel chronograph with perpetual calendar and
moonphase. This 18 ct gold watch is self-winding, and comes on a leather
strap (Pounds 14,320) or on a gold band (Pounds 21,490). It is
water-resistant to 30m (Omitted). Photograph Blancpain chronograph - but has
the craze peaked? (Omitted).
</PAGE>
</DOC>
