<HEADLINE>
FT  11 MAY 91 / Books: Bodily rituals
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By PAUL DRIVER
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
IN PRAISE OF THE STEPMOTHER by Mario Vargas Llosa Faber Pounds 13.99, 149
pages
THE PERUVIAN Mario Vargas Llosa's new novel is a book of intimacies and
fantasies. Seldom have I encountered such a sensorily immediate piece of
writing, one which better evokes bodily odours or summons up what might be
called the body's organ music. Not since Joyce's Ulysses has the act of
human excretion been so crisply and vividly rendered in prose.
Daily ablutions, rituals of personal hygiene and far-flung exotica of the
marriage-bed make up Llosa's chief subject-matter; though he also sustains a
plot about the corruption by - rather than of - innocence, and builds a
fancy novelistic structure whereby the chapters of the main narrative are
interspersed with fantasy elaborations of (mostly) famous paintings, here
reproduced on colour plates.
The narrative concerns the second marriage of Don Rigoberto, cultivated
manager of a Peruvian insurance company, and the complex reaction of his
schoolboy son to the presence of his 40-year old stepmother Dona Lucrecia.
The 'structure' focusses on the mythological prototypes, as represented in
paintings, that lie behind the modern action and its psychology. Thus Don
Rigoberto's delight in Dona Lucrecia's rump gives rise to Llosa's
dramatisation of Jacob Jordaens's 1648 canvas, Candaules, King of Lydia,
showing his wife to Prime Minister Gyges. Dona Lucrecia's feelings of
attraction to her stepson are developed in a commentary on a Francois
Boucher bower of bliss. A Francis Bacon elephant man becomes the mouthpiece
for Don Rigoberto's feelings of monstrosity; and an abstract painting (1977)
by one Fernando de Szyszlo is seen by young Alfonso as depicting his
stepmother in all the fullness of her eroticism.
The method, like Llosa's approach in general, may recall the work of Julian
Barnes, whose History of the World in 10 1/2 Chapters contains a fold-out
colour reproduction of Gericault's Raft of the Medusa. Here it makes, not
illogically, for an essentially decorative sort of novel. Serious themes, it
is true, are adumbrated: for instance, Don Rigoberto's attention to the
minutiae of lavation and love-making is repeatedly seen as his 'personal way
of bringing about a utopia' and even an apotheosis; while Dona Lucrecia's
sexual entanglement with a minor is a fairly momentous issue.
But the tone is ultimately light and exquisite. The language (in what seems
a brilliant translation by Helen Lane) is fastidious, graceful, and
sprinkled with scent. It is an audacious caprice of a book, most memorable
for the accuracy and humour of its corporeal descriptions. The chapter
devoted to Don Rigoberto's cleaning of his ears is a writerly tour de force.
(A collection of Vargas Llosa's early short fiction is published
simultaneously: The Cubs and Other Stories, Faber paperback Pounds 4.99, 139
pages.)
</TEXT>
<PUB>The Financial Times
</PUB>
