<HEADLINE>
FT  11 MAY 91 / Books: Magic from the mundane - Fiction
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ANTHONY CURTIS
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THE BURN: STORIES by James Kelman Secker &amp; Warburg Pounds 13.99, 244 pages
HARDIE AND BAIRD AND OTHER PLAYS by James Kelman Secker &amp; Warburg Pounds
14.99, 180 pages
WHENEVER A new novel or volume of stories by James Kelman appears Scottish
reviewers say 'brilliant' in chorus. South of the border most of us haven't
taken heed. Kelman has now published 11 books, and it is high time we did.
Kelman's fame started to spread a couple of years ago when the Booker judges
put A Disaffection, Kelman's novel about a Glasgow schoolmaster, among their
last six novels. It didn't win the prize, which was given that year (1989)
to Kazuo Ishiguro, but the short-listing of Kelman's work prompted many
people to read him for the first time and some even to compare him with
Beckett. Jeremy Beadle, a reader who entered for our FT Booker Prize
competition, took another view:
'What Kelman has achieved (he wrote) is to work outwards from the ordinary
and the everyday in the manner of the great 19th century British and French
novelists - to reveal the extraordinary in the human condition. Not for him
the imposition of 'magical' or symbolic events. Patrick Doyle his hero tries
to wrest magic from the mundane - a pair of ordinary pipes, a pointless
romantic lust - and his failure provides an illumination which speaks
directly to more people than any other novel this year.'
The two books just published are an easier point of entry into Kelmanland
for the first-time reader than that long novel. The Burn contains stories
varying in length from one to 40 pages, the other book scripts of three
plays produced on the Fringe at Edinburgh, on Radio Scotland and at the
Traverse Theatre. The constraints imposed by the small-cast play and the
short-story suit Kelman, and he handles them with great variety.
The most substantial story in The Burn - 'events in yer life' - traces the
career of one of Kelman's lame dogs with typical precision. The basic theme
is that of a prodigal son - a Glasgow artist who returns home after a long
absence for his mother's funeral. He tries to pick up the forgotten threads
in conversation with his sister and his former mate. In his talk with both
he suffers from a crushing sense of displacement, and gradually we see that
his alienation is just as strong when he is away from Scotland. He now
belongs nowhere. Continual intake of alcohol breaks down initial
embarrassment and reserve to reveal how the fissures of the present are even
greater than the traumas of the past, and all the while Kelman's dialogue
crackles with insights. What should have assuaged his outsider-hero's guilt
only serves to heighten it.
An equal load of guilt - often far too much for any one person to bear  -
afflicts all Kelman's chief characters. Sometimes it is inexplicable,
Kafka-like as in 'Naval History' where a man is mysteriously framed for
theft in the innocuous setting of a high street bookshop. In a longer story,
'A Situation', a young man has slept with his fiancee's sister. Here, as in
'Pictures' where a boy remembers a homosexual encounter in a public
lavatory, the un-atonable moment is plainly identified.
Both these, like many of Kelman's stories, are virtual monologues, peppered
with the four-letter expletive that is Kelman's trade-mark. But the
language, however demotic, is always disciplined. The local words like
'greet' for 'weep', 'wouldni' for 'wouldn't', are carefully placed
indicators. One brief violent story is written entirely in dialect. And as
is clear from Hardie and Baird, a moving play set in the 18th century,
Kelman can when he wishes elevate his diction. Here, in occasional soaring
flights of grandiloquence, he reconstructs the last days in prison of two
weavers before they were hanged for insurrection.
In a recent interview Kelman has described himself as an existentialist,
citing authors such as James Hogg, Dostoevsky, Camus as his forebears. After
reading these fables of unresolved guilt the label stands, but he might more
accurately be described as an existential Jansenist, someone who believes
that most of us are doomed to damnation however hard we try to avoid it. A
bleak message, but one that is indelible in Kelman's work.
</TEXT>
<PUB>The Financial Times
</PUB>
<PAGE>
London Page XXIV
</PAGE>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>FT911-477</DOCNO>
<PROFILE>_AN-BELAGAC0FT</PROFILE>
<DATE>910511
</DATE>
<HEADLINE>
FT  11 MAY 91 / Books: A domestic minister - The man from middle England
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By MALCOLM RUTHERFORD
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
MINISTERS DECIDE by Norman Fowler Chapmans Pounds 18, 372 pages
NORMAN FOWLER has always seen himself in politics as the man from middle
England. He represents a Midlands seat, Sutton Coldfield, where in the 1979
general election when Mrs Thatcher became prime minister he had the highest
Tory majority in the country. As a former journalist - he was the home
affairs correspondent of The Times - and one of the very few cabinet
ministers to serve almost throughout Thatcher's administrations, he is well
qualified to write about the experience. Perhaps not surprisingly, he has
produced a middling sort of book.
Some of it is very interesting, especially the parts about before he held
senior office. Fowler is grammar school/Cambridge, part of what he describes
as the Cambridge mafia which has held so many seats in recent Conservative
governments. It was between school and university, during his officer's
training course for national service, that he says that he discovered that
the Britain of the 1950s was 'still a class-ridden society'. The less-well
educated boys from the public schools looked down on the better educated
products of the grammar schools.
That is a revealing comment, which helps to explain what some of modern
Toryism has been about. Politicians like Fowler, and indeed Thatcher, wanted
greater equality of opportunity, and they wanted it within a competitive,
efficient system. They had little to do with the old Tory paternalism, which
too often went hand-in-glove with the paternalism of the trades unions.
Nevertheless, the new Toryism had its limitations. Fowler records Thatcher
saying as early as 1975 that she had spent all her time in home departments
and now needed to learn about foreign affairs. Some of the new Tories left
the learning process even later. Fowler spent his entire ministerial career
in domestic ministries and never really caught up with Europe. At heart and
in his head, he is a middle English nationalist.
Curiously, that was what led to one of his most decisive interventions in
government. By threatening to resign from the cabinet, he helped to stop the
sale of the former British Leyland to an American company. In a way, he was
right. The cabinet committee system had never thought to consult the member
who sat in the heart of the motor industry. Fowler says that Thatcher
promised at once that never again would regional and constituency interests
of a cabinet member be so overlooked.
By any but the very highest standards, Fowler had a successful ministerial
career. He helped to bring about the management buy-out in the National
Freight Corporation, one of the first of the privatisations. He pushed
through the electrification of British Rail against the opposition of Sir
Alan Walters. He was a prime mover in bringing in portable pensions. Mrs
Thatcher must have been genuinely sorry to see him go when he decided that
he wanted to spend more time with his children.
Probably he should have been made party chairman. He understood the Tory
party in the country, and he probably understood what makes middle England
tick. He records that he did not vote for Thatcher in the fateful party
leadership election in 1975, but along with Norman Lamont was instrumental
in seeking to persuade Sir Keith Joseph to run. When that enterprise failed,
he supported Sir Geoffrey Howe, but came quickly to admire the winner.
In the leadership election last year, he voted for Thatcher in the first
ballot and Michael Heseltine in the second. He thinks that Thatcher could
have won on the first if only she had been in the country at the time and
had bothered to campaign properly.
As a former journalist, Fowler should be mildly ashamed about the length of
his book. The more personal parts are the best. No-one would accuse him of
using a ghost-writer and it is rather courageous of him to seek to remain in
the House of Commons rather than accepting the peerage that would
automatically come his way if he were to step down at the next election.
</TEXT>
<PUB>The Financial Times
</PUB>
