<PROFILE>_AN-BELAGACXFT</PROFILE>
<DATE>910511
</DATE>
<HEADLINE>
FT  11 MAY 91 / Arts: Heavenly choirs - Records
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By RONALD CRICHTON
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
WILLIAM BOYCE was a chorister at St. Paul's who later became Master of the
King's Musick and organist to the Chapel Royal. He edited an important
collection of English cathedral music and was a prolific composer of
masques, anthems, chamber music and symphonies. He was one of our 18th
century masters, sturdy, clean-cut and spruce. He wrote too little for the
theatre. As his music for Dryden's The Secular Masque and the score put
together by Constant Lambert for the ballet The Prospect before us show he
had the genuine dramatic spark.
That spark is present in the Serenata Solomon (1743), a setting of words by
the Dublin writer Edward Moore based on the Song of Songs but falling on the
profane side of the fence. This is a delightful work in the vein of Handel's
Acis and Galatea, with amorous airs for He and She (as the lovers are
called) with occasional choruses. Don't be put off by the initial
nervousness of the soprano Bronwen Mills. She recovers in time to prove a
worthy partner for the stylish tenor Howard Crook. Good support from choir
and orchestra of The Parley of Instruments under Roy Goodman.
Sir John Stainer, Eminent Victorian musician par excellence, was also a St
Paul's chorister and later organist to the cathedral for many years. Like
Boyce he did valuable musicological work. As a composer he was less
productive and, to judge from The Crucifixion (1887), less rewarding. This
'Meditation' on the Passion was hugely popular in its time and still, it
seems, has loyal admirers.
The present Cathedral Choir is joined by the Special Service Choir founded
by Stainer. The recording has just enough of Wren's echo. Andrew Lucas is
the organist, John Scott conducts. They do their predecessor proud. In the
narrations the two soloists, while sounding totally sincere, manage to skirt
mawkishness. The baritone David Wilson-Johnson is more successful than the
tenor Maldwyn Davies in avoiding the genteel pronunciation (guilt-ee,
glor-ee) once thought seemly for religious texts. Did I hear someone sing
'Here in a basement'? Perhaps it was the echo.
The form of The Crucifixion, with hymns doing duty for chorales, owes
something to the Bach Passions, yet it is depressing to realise that the
style, five years after Parsifal, 40 years after Elijah, is still
mini-Mendelssohn. Yet Ethel Smyth's powerful Mass in D and Elgar's Gerontius
were only a decade or so over the horizon. Meanwhile, go back to Boyce for
comfort and still better to Purcell. A splendid bunch of his canticles and
verse anthem (with the Funeral Sentences for the Death of Queen Mary),
recorded by Decca during the 1970s with the choir of St John's College
Cambridge under George Guest, is now available on CD. These works, blazing
with vitality and originality, should restore anyone's faith in English
music.
Rossini's sanguine Stabat Mater (1842), gives a very different view of the
crucifixion to Stainer's, as ebulliently Latin as the other is piously
Anglo-Saxon. The new Philips recording from Bavarian Radio under the
enlivening direction of Semyon Bychkov sweeps all before it - the concluding
Amen chorus (does anybody still believe Rossini couldn't write a fugue?) has
tremendous drive. The male soloists (Araiza and Furlanetto) are good, the
women (Vaness and Bartoli) are outstanding (listen to the two latter in the
duet 'Quis est homo'). But I hope the soprano won't admit any more vibrato
into her tone.
The EMI L'Enfance du Christ made in the chapel of King's College Cambridge
by the Choir under Stephen Cleobury is decent but too soft-focussed. The boy
angels are faultless, the men's unison recitatives in the soothsayer's scene
unimpressive, the Choir as a whole is as expert as one would expect. Ann
Murray's Mary is vividly human. Likewise the Herod of David Wilson-Johnson.
The final, unaccompanied number threatens to go flaccid.
Nothing flaccid about the Erato recording of 1988 under John Eliot Gardiner,
made in the medieval church at Perouges near Lyons, and now available on CD.
This conductor's acute understanding of Berliozian colour and accent,
clearly conveyed by the Lyons Opera orchestra, provides exactly the sharp
focus the music requires. The Monteverdi Choir is its usual excellent self,
never more so than when they nobly sustain a slowish speed for the
Shepherds' Farewell. Jose Van Dam gives an account of Herod's scene which
one can hardly hope to hear surpassed for perfect legato suffused with
expressive shading. Both narrators are British. Tear (EMI) and Rolfe-Johnson
(Erato) are intelligent, musical and deeply committed artists. I recall
years ago a Columbia 78 by the French tenor Jean Planel, whose serene
objectivity seems in retrospect more appropriate than the modern singers'
involvement.
Boyce: Solomon (a serenata). Mills, Crook/Parley of Instruments/Goodman.
Hyperion CDA 66378 (2 CDs).
Stainer: The Crucifixion. Davies, Wilson-Johnson/St. Paul's Cathedral
Choir/Lucas/Scott. Conifer CDCF 193, cassette MCFC 193.
Purcell: Canticles, Funeral Music, Anthems. Choir of St. John's College
Cambridge/ various soloists and instruments/Guest. Decca 430 263-2, cassette
MC 430 262 4.
Rossini: Stabat Mater. Vaness, Bartoli, Araiza, Furlanetto/Bavarian Radio SO
and Choir/Bychkov. Philips 436 312-2.
Berlioz: L'Enfance du Christ. Murray, Tear, Allen, Wilson-Johnson/Choir of
King's College Cambridge/RPO/Cleobury. EMI CDS 7 49935 2 (2 CDs).
Berlioz: L'Enfance du Christ. Von Otter, Cachemaille, Van Dam, Bastin,
Rolfe-Johnson/Monteverdi Choir/Lyons Opera Orch./ Gardiner. Erato
2292-45275-2 (2 CDs).
</TEXT>
<PUB>The Financial Times
</PUB>
