<HEADLINE>
FT  11 MAY 91 / Arts: Dramatic hot potatoes in Berlin - This year for the
first time the Theatre Festival has opened to a united Germany
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JACKIE WULLSCHLAGER
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THE NATIONAL Theatre, One; Glasgow Citz, Three, the Royal Shakespeare
Company, Nil. Imagine an annual scoreboard like this and you get a sense of
the fevered response to Germany's Booker Prize of the stage, the
'Theatertreffen' ('Theatre Meeting'), in which the 12 'top' German-speaking
productions of the season are elected by jury and invited to Berlin for a
festival jamboree.
Who's in, who's out, which theatre has squeezed most productions into the
flurried three weeks (May 1-20) of full houses, roaring crowds and smoky
seminars about the future of drama? For the first time in its 28-year
history, the Festival opened last week in a united city, focussing the
familiar annual post-mortems on Berlin's bid for cultural dominance as part
of the fight to become the new German capital. Only one of the nine-critic
jury comes from Berlin - Dieter Kranz from the east - yet cultural centrism
has already taken root.
An unprecedented six of the Festival's dozen offerings are home-grown,
though the jury - unpaid and unloved - scrutinised some 400 new productions
across Germany, Austria and Switzerland. Outside Berlin, directors like the
Vienna Burgtheater's Claus Peymann huff about attempts to manufacture Berlin
as 'metropolis of the theatre', while Festival director Torsten Mass is
adamant: 'Since unification Berlin is the theatre capital of Germany'.
The hot potatoes this year are two works which turn on the nature of the
unified state, by Germany's best known living dramatists, Heiner Muller and
Botho Strauss. Teutonic heavyweights both, they are political allegories
whose painful topicality makes them recommended viewing for anyone trying to
fathom the divided background of the new Germany.
At the Deutsches Theater in the east of the city, Heiner Muller directs a
mammoth uncut Hamlet with his own contemporary postscript Hamletmachine
added on to make a seven-hour-plus show. 'We thought about what was topical
and really only found Hamlet to be so', says Muller. Erich Wonder's set
dramatises the shock of a literally changing climate - ice blocks melt and
drip into a pool of water - and Ulrich Muhe plays Hamlet as helpless
individual caught between two epochs. His 'To be or not to be' fumes with
dashed hopes, guilty impotence in a corrupt world, the certain knowledge of
crimes committed in an unaccountable past. Horatio (Jorg-Michael Korbl)
scrutinises the audience for fellow-travellers, and the murdered king
crosses the stage to the commentary from Stalin's funeral.
The ghost, says Muller 'is at once Stalin and the Deutsche Bank, the ghost
of communism and the phantom of an anti-social market economy'. His
Hamletmachine heralds the repression of the new order: Hamlet rises from the
deathfield and declares Denmark a prison - for which a better prison system
must be invented.
Muller has an Ophelia in flames; Botho Strauss's Schlusschor (Final Chorus)
 -in Dieter Dorn's production from the Munich Kammerspiele, has the German
national eagle released from the zoo by a woman who wants to copulate with
it, then destroys it because it is impotent. But where Muller turns drama to
up-to-the-minute metaphor, Strauss's theatre topples into symbol-heavy
indulgence.
Strauss was writing the play when the Wall came down and was then inspired
by Bernstein conducting Beethoven's Ninth in the uniting Berlin. The
symphony chants through the work along with Bach, folk songs and a
stereotyped portrayal of shabbily dressed 'Ossies'. Following a shriek of
'Germany's disappeared', a mirror (self-revelation) and a camera (preserver
of the historical moment) dominate the early acts before the wretched bird
proves so unserviceable in the final 'chorus'.
I shall return next week to two exceptional Festival Shakespeare
productions, the Schaubuhne's Winter's Tale and Timon of Athens from Bochum,
which also dally with contemporary metaphor but are much more besides.
Shakespeare, with three plays, tops the Festival bill; with Ibsen, Schiller,
Chekhov, the selection is representative of the strong classical bias of
theatres across Germany.
The two quirkiest choices come from Berlin. My schedule excluded the
Schiller Theater's Tales from Grimm, a one-man show by the Big Daddy of the
Berlin theatre, Bernhard Minetti, which opened on his 86th birthday. But I
did catch the Schaubuhne's Mothers and Sons, translated from the Spanish,
about two Mummy's boys which comedians Udo Samel and Gerd Wameling (the
Winter's Tale's clown) play as absurdist duet.
The piece is the interview between bank manager Krugger and 30-year-old Juan
D who lives with his mother and is applying for his first job, as the bank's
night watchman. But the bank doesn't come into it: through asides, farcical
gestures, crawls across partners' desks, hypochondriac fits, they argue
about maternal cooking, toy trains, tastes in women - hypothetical, as
neither has ever talked to one other than Mother.
Obsessions are mirrored by surrealist events - a frog crosses the plush
carpet and is wordlessly squashed, a thunderstorm breaks out within the
office - which Tomeo suggests are no odder than corporate life: daily
electronic renderings of Eine Kleine Nachtmusik before the 5pm announcement
wishing all employees a happy evening with their families, for example.
Berlin audiences have poured into this off-beat critique of work and the
adult world since it opened. Such eccentricities are as much part of the
Berlin culture as doughnuts and drunks and gallows humour and gruff
greetings. But will they last? Midseason, the Schaubuhne's budget was cut by
DM2.4m, aborting new productions and throwing the future of west Berlin's
most famous theatre into doubt. And as the festival opened last week, the
four directors of the west's super-tech Schiller Theater, the biggest
theatre complex in Germany, threatened to resign over financial problems.
In the east, Max Reinhardt's Deutsches Theater stands in preserved
fin-de-siecle splendour in the run-down Friedrichstrasse. Outside, the
Mercedes and BMWs parked along with the Trabbies suggest that the stage is
one of the few places where East and West Berliners are looking one another
in the face. Eighty per cent of Deutsches Theater audiences now come from
the west, and directors like Thomas Langhoff, the intendant elect, have
emphasised the political role of the Berlin theatres in this respect. But
Langhoff is also refusing to take up his post until adequate funding is
agreed: Deutsches Theater subsidies are currently DM12m against the Schiller
Theater's DM36-40m a year.
Another row bubbles away over the resignation of Manfred Wekwerth, intendant
of Brecht's Berliner Ensemble, ordered by Berlin's Senator for Culture,
Ulrich Roloff-Momin. Wekwerth was a member of the repressive SED Central
Committee which had curtailed artistic freedom in the city; he had also
worked with Brecht in the 1950s. Last week, Roloff-Momin was discussing the
rights to the plays with Brecht's heirs; should they now withhold them,
Brecht, staple diet of the Berliner Ensemble, will be suddenly off the
repertoire. And trouble also in the east for Heiner Muller's Akademie der
Kunste, which is to close at the end of the year. As Andrew Clark reported
on these pages about German musical life after reunification, so it is for
drama. Too many good theatres now offer too much at too high state
subsidies. There will be cuts all round and some of Berlin's most historic
stages may not survive. The offerings from Berlin in the Festival this year
are of the finest quality, but behind the scenes, the joke is to read 'To be
or not to be' as a dilemma off rather than onstage, while Langhoff, waiting
to sign his contract, is said to have recast The Sorcerer's Apprentrice as
his favourite villain - a bungling wizard in Bonn.
</TEXT>
<PUB>The Financial Times
</PUB>
<PAGE>
London Page XVIII Photograph Political allegory, Heiner Muller's
Hamletmachine (Omitted).
</PAGE>
