<HEADLINE>
FT  11 MAY 91 / Travel: The happy isles - Snapshot
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ANGELA WIGGLESWORTH
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THE Isles of Scilly are a group of 100 tiny islands clustered in a deep blue
sea with white sand on their long curving beaches, palm trees in cottage
gardens, fields of daffodils in November, wild orchids in the hedgerows in
summer.
Huge rocks hewn into primeval shapes jut from the sea where seals and
dolphins swim and the grass on the coastal paths is springy underfoot.
Winters are mild, summers generally sunny and visitors return year after
year not just for walking, boating, fishing and bird-watching but for the
peace and friendliness they find.
The islands lie 28 miles south-west of Land's End, the most southerly point
of the British mainland. Only five are inhabited (pop: 2,000) and there is
accommodation on all five. St Mary's, three miles by two, is the largest and
the only place where private cars are allowed . With its shops, restaurants,
pubs, cafes, hotels and guest houses, it has a bustle that is noticeably
absent from the other islands.
Tresco has sub-tropical gardens. St Martin's, with a population of 84, has
recently acquired a 24-bedroomed luxury hotel. On St Agnes you can hunt for
beads buried in the sand from a 17th century wreck and have delicious
pasties at The Turks Head. On Bryher, waves crash spectacularly on to the
gigantic rocks of Hell Bay.
The great pleasures of the Scillies include inter-island boat trips, with St
Mary's boatmen visiting hotels and guest houses at breakfast to announce
their programmes for the day. Other islands have their own boats and,
weather permitting, visit most places most days.
An old poem still seems to sum up the Scillies: 'Rocks and sand and barren
land, a church without a steeple. Houses made of ship-wrecked wood, full of
happy people.'
Tourist Information Centre, St Mary's, Isles of Scilly, tel: 0720-22536.
</TEXT>
<PUB>The Financial Times
</PUB>
