<DATE>910511
</DATE>
<HEADLINE>
FT  11 MAY 91 / Sport: At play with a double-edged blade - Cricket
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By TERESA MCLEAN
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   IT IS obvious what cricket has to gain from sponsorship
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
money, one of the game's permanent needs. But what do businesses stand to
gain from sponsoring cricket? That is a much trickier question and produced
some tricky answers when I tried it out on companies which sponsor first
class cricket today or have sponsored it in the past.
Cricket and money have always been bed-fellows, but in the good old days
uncertainty about profit and loss was part of the fun. In the 18th and 19th
centuries a game was only a good game if it was played for a spectacular sum
of money, which was raised by wealthy patrons with an interest in the game.
The interest was primarily financial and these patrons were big time
gamblers.
In his classic The Young Cricketer's Tutor John Nyren recalls the Hambledon
Club in the 1770s and 80s playing matches against All England teams for
massive sums of money: Pounds 500, even Pounds 1,000 a time, of which the
players got only Pounds 5 each if they won a fortune for their patrons,
Pounds 3 if they lost. Such was the 'heart-stirrring' excitement on these
occasions that Hambledon's most generous patron, Sir Horace Mann, spent his
time 'walking about . . . cutting down the daisies with his stick - a habit
with him when he was agitated.'
By the 20th century patrons like Mann were a thing of the past. As The Times
reported tersely in September 1908, 'cricket has ceased to attract the
betting-man, although there are few signs that he did the early game much
harm.' Indeed, without betting patrons to support and enliven it, first
class cricket soon found it hard to pay its way.
Those who are old enough to remember the Gillette Safety Razor Company
launching English one-day cricket and commercial sponsorship in 1963, in the
form of the Gillette Cup, will remember the desperation of county cricket in
the preceding years. Fewer people were going to county matches; clubs were
losing money and appeal, after a post-war revival. Gillette's Pounds 6,500
was a life-saver, though the limited overs competitions it inspired have
been sucking the life-blood out of the county game ever since.
The Gillette Cup was a success - for one-day cricket; for players such as
Ted Dexter with one-day, cavalier appeal; for commercial sponsorship, only
adopted as a last resort by cricket's nervous and straight-laced
establishment, and, one would have thought, for Gillette, whose name quickly
became synonymous with one-day cricket.
Gillette is a big, American, multi-national company and one of its publicity
squad told me that it went into cricket sponsorship to acquire an English
identity that would outdo the crossed swords and traditional English image
of its razor blade rival, Wilkinson. He added with a weary chuckle,'That's
the official line, but you're never really sure what you want out of
advertising or sponsorship.'
Why did Gillette stop its sponsorship in 1980? 'We left because the Test and
County Cricket Board got too greedy for funds and asked for too much money.'
Modern sponsors, then, are not sure when their sponsorship is making them a
profit, only when it is making them a loss. I think Sir Horace Mann would be
cutting down more than daisies if his money had been put into a wager where
it did not matter which team won and he would not have known when he had won
something because he would not have known what he was hoping to win in the
first place.
But that seems to be how modern cricket sponsors like it. They talk about
identity and public profile, not profit. Cornhill Insurance sponsored its
first Test Match in 1978 when, according to a company survey, less than 2
per cent of people had heard of Cornhill. Apparently the figure has risen
enormously with the company's Test Match sponsorship, but Cornhill's
marketing manager said he could not say how many more customers and how much
more money the 'improved name awareness' had brought in; that would be 'too
crude an evaluation.'
Sponsors' aims are long term. Most companies continue their sponsorship for
long spells, at least ten years, usually longer. I was assured by Alan
Smith, Chief Executive of the TCCB, which is in charge of national
sponsorship, that if any of cricket's eight current large sponsors were to
withdraw, there are companies queueing up to replace them. It is the TCCB
which lays down the terms and conditions of sponsorship. Take it or leave
it. When Gillette left National Westminster Bank took its place and has just
extended its sponsorship into its eleventh year.
No-one at NatWest had any doubt that the money and effort required for
sponsorship on this scale were worth while and that its sponsorship was a
success, in spite of hard times in the counting house. Success may be hard
to measure but it is easier if the head of the company concerned is 'a
cricket nut', which is how Lord Alexander, Chairman of NatWest Bank, happily
describes himself.
The more nuts the better. Unlike most things in English first class cricket
at the moment, sponsorship looks good. I dislike myself for saying this, but
I can not help feeling that it all sounds just a bit too good to be true.
Does not the 'happy, friendly, working relationship' which the TCCB enjoys
with cricket's sponsors have an element of danger for the spectator who only
goes to cricket matches to watch, without powerful money to back his or her
views? What is to stop a company offering money for the privilege of laying
down some of the conditions in its sponsorship contract?
Alan Smith did not waste words: 'If we were offered Pounds 20m in return for
letting a sponsor put his name in the middle of the wicket we would refuse,
not for aesthetic but for practical reasons; it would distract the players.'
Cricket without an aesthetic dimension - does that mean logos on the
outfield; stripes, numbers and colours and, before long, sponsors' names on
cricketers' clothes; the thin end of a wedge where only money is valuable?
A crisp official reply. 'We may try out one or two names painted on the
field of play this summer. We don't know yet.'
I sighed sadly.
'Oh, come on. We can't afford to be impractical. If outfield advertising
brings in money to help school cricket, we have to take it.'
I suppose so, and soon we will have logos on cricket shirts too. But with
many a wistful glance to the handsome cricket we inherited from Hambledon in
its prime, when it was the excellence of play that spoke for its sponsor, as
celebrated by Rev Cotton in his noble song 'Cricket':
'The parties are met, and array'd all in white
Famed Elis ne'er boasted so pleasing a sight.'
</TEXT>
<PUB>The Financial Times
</PUB>
<PAGE>
London Page X Photograph Cavalier at the crease, dashing Ted Dexter appealed
to sponsors and fans (Omitted).
</PAGE>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>FT911-499</DOCNO>
<PROFILE>_AN-BELAGACEFT</PROFILE>
<DATE>910511
</DATE>
<HEADLINE>
FT  11 MAY 91 / Sport: Cucumber sandwich set samples the Euro-hoopla -
Croquet
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By NICKY SMITH
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
CROQUET is THE game for the 90s (although it can be played by any age
group). It is family oriented, 'green' and 'caring' - it is astonishing how
much the average croquet player cares when he fails to win - and it is the
coming Eurogame.
To appreciate how obvious this is you only have to look at the language.
'Croquet' is a French word which according to Larousse means petit biscuit
sec aux amandes. Under another entry however, it is referred to as: (mot
anglais) jeu qui consiste a faire passer sous des arceaux des boules de bois
avec un mallet. This somewhat careless admission by the French that croquet
is an English word (although the Oxford English Dictionary suggests the word
is 'perhaps northern French, a dialect form of 'crochet' meaning 'hook'')
makes it possible to permit the continentals to play. Having established
that croquet is British, the rest may join in.
There has been a spirited attempt to claim that the word croquet is of Irish
origin, deriving from the Celtic cluiche (pronounced cloo-ic-ee). This
should delight the denizens of Dublin in the year their city holds the title
of Cultural Capital of Europe. No doubt, the EC Ministers who awarded the
title were mindful of Ireland's contribution to croquet when they made their
choice.
They will have known that croquet's most likely route to England was from
the beaches of northern France (where it was played with crooks by peasants)
via Ireland. Here, the son of the ivory turner John Jaques whose name has
become synonymous with English croquet, claimed that he picked up a set of
croquet implements which he brought back to London and decided to copy and
manufacture.
His family were fanatics for inventing or reproducing games including 'Happy
Families', 'Tiddley Winks' and 'Ping Pong' and their company was
instrumental in popularising croquet in Victorian England.
In the mid-nineteenth century, croquet was exported to Australia, New
Zealand and North America and the British contrived to ensure that almost
everyone played to their rules. The exception was the US which kept an early
version of the game. This rather startled members of the Croquet Association
of Great Britain, who visited in the 60s and found the Americans playing to
rules the British had abandoned at the turn of the century.
Now, croquet is booming in the US. Championship games are played on
immaculate lawns in the prestigious surroundings of Palm Beach but the
'backyard' version, a nine wicket (ie hoop) game, continues to be popular.
Recently croquet claimed to be the third fastest growing sport in the US
(after surfing and volleyball). There are signs that the Americans have
astutely recognised the importance of croquet in the European context.
Rumour has it that a full-sized croquet lawn is being laid in the heart of
the Euro-Disney Park, where a version of the famous game played by Alice,
will be annually reconstructed using MEPs as hoops and black puddings as
balls, with prawn cocktail crisps accompanying the Pimms at tea intervals.
Balls will be directed by laser beams to music composed by Jean-Michel
Jarre. There is a historical precedent for this form of musical
entertainment. One of croquet's greatest champions was George Frederic
Handel Elvey, a country parson whose father had been organist at St George's
Chapel, Windsor, hence his son's resounding first name.
Margaret Thatcher, the former British Prime Minister, was a contender for
the part of the Red Queen in the Euro-game and following his recent
revelation that he is a croquet enthusiast (who has even played on snow),
Lord Jenkins of Hillhead - known to the French as 'Le Roi Jean Quinze' - is
a candidate for the role of king.
The French are the reigning Olympic champions. They produced a team of 20 on
the last occasion that croquet was in the Olympics - in Paris in 1900. They
were the only entrants.
Manchester was, of course, chosen as Britain's candidate for the 1998
Olympics because of its convenient proximity to Bowdon Croquet Club where
the prestigious annual croquet invitation event, the President's Cup, is
played. This is an attempt to move the game away from London which has been
the centre of the croquet universe.
Each year competitors have streamed to Hurlingham from all corners of the
earth to take part in the World Croquet Championships (another version of
which is sometimes held at a winery in California). The current champion is,
of course, British; a young man called Robert Fulford who, when he is not
playing croquet, studies mathematics at Durham University.
Croquet's recent progress is largely due to the work of the game's
Development Officer, Chris Hudson, a member of the Bowdon, who has done more
in the last few years to galvanise croquet into taking a serious place in
the sporting world than has been achieved in decades. This has been
accomplished through Sports Council grants and careful planning, resulting
in more domestic competitions designed to encourage garden players (the
cucumber sandwiches and tea-set) to take up the 'official' game, more
schools competitions which have produced the influx of young players such as
Fulford, and more international events.
Croquet has always been an international game. Test matches have been played
between Great Britain, Australia and New Zealand since the 1920s. The US
will join the triumvirate for the next Test, and Japan is also making
progress. Croquet resembles the Japanese national game of Gate Ball and has
become popular particularly among women. Fourteen countries will be at the
World Championships this summer at Hurlingham.
English croquet players visit Italy on a regular basis to teach the Italians
and their pupils are so entusiastico that they have even contributed their
own cup to the World Championship event. They call it the 'Fun Cup' and it
was presented the first year to Jerry Stark of the US for sartorial elegance
(he plays in plus fours held aloft by red braces) and in 1990 to Japanese
competitor Toro Takano, for simply being there.
Last year, the French hosted a tournament in the Loire valley where the food
and wine were excellent and the lawns appalling. No doubt, the effect of the
first had something to do with the judgment on the second.
The latest European entrants are the Spanish and the Swiss. The Santa Clara
Croquet Club at Jerez de al Frontera in Spain, founded in 1979, has around
16 members and a motto: 'No dues, no don'ts'. The Swiss have been keen
garden players for years and are teaming up to play the Italians and the
French for a Coupe des Alpes but the only official club to date is based at
CERN, the European Organisation for Nuclear Research.
The idea that croquet is a daft game for old ladies and colonels stands in
sharp contradiction to the kind of people who currently make up the top 100
players in the official British league. Most are young men in their 20s who
play other sports. Ask them why they play croquet and they will simply
answer that it is a 'good game'.
Association croquet combines the best of snooker and chess. It is an
intellectual exercise in tactics played in the open air, mentally
challenging and mildly energetic. It requires more psychological than
physical stamina and, above all, a great deal of patience. Time moves slowly
in croquet. A player can wait more than an hour for a turn and it has taken
more than a century to try to codify the rules - which are still open to
interpretation, as every croquet player, 'official' or otherwise, is well
aware.
Croquet can involve the kind of incessant quibbling and procrastination
which makes the EC taking 22 years to make a law about jam seem a rather
hurried affair. The history of the game is riddled with infighting, petty
squabbling and 'personality clashes' which are at odds with the outward
'etiquette' of croquet. It is a game known for its style and a degree of
Edwardian elegance and restraint which has all but disappeared from the rest
of the sporting scene. For, whatever their internal rivalries, croquet
players are generally undemonstrative in public. They are not given to
throwing their arms about each other or taking anything stronger with their
tea than a couple of distalgesic. Best of all perhaps, croquet is a game at
which the British excel.
With the exception of a handful of New Zealanders, the British really do
play croquet better than anyone else which only goes to to prove the truth
of the old saw, les Francais inventent, mais les Anglais perfectionnent. Now
THAT should go down well in Europe.
If you want to play croquet contact: The Croquet Association, The Hurlingham
Club, Ranelagh Gardens, London SW6 3PR, Tel 071 736 8411).
Nicky Smith is author of 'Queen of Games, The History of Croquet" Weidenfeld
and Nicolson, Pounds 16.95
</TEXT>
