<HEADLINE>
FT  11 MAY 91 / Finance &amp; The Family: Directors' transactions
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ANGUS MACDONALD
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Directors made more share sales than purchases in April, with the ratio of
sales to buys reaching 1.6 to 1, writes Angus MacDonald, of Directus Ltd.
There has been more buying interest in smaller company shares in the last
couple of weeks, and the launch of two new smaller company investment trusts
by Aberforth and Moorgate should help to rekindle demand in this area of the
market.
A series of hefty rights issues by building and construction companies has
helped to halt this sectors's considerable underperformance since the turn
of the year.
The building, timber and roads sector was particularly heavily bought by
directors last autumn, but the situation has now changed and directors'
share sales outweigh buys by 7 to 1 in this area. Beazer share sales
illustrate the point. Seven directors bought Beazer shares in the autumn at
around 95p. The share price has almost doubled subsequently, and two
directors have reduced their holdings in recent weeks.
Several directors of Usher Walker, the printing ink business, have bought
large amounts of shares as can be seen from the list. At the same time, it
was announced that David Williams, who recently resigned from Mosaic
Investment, has purchased 10.2 per cent from Southern Newspapers.
Sir David Alliance, chairman of N Brown, the home shopping concern, followed
the announcement of a placing and open offer with the purchase of over 1m
shares in the company. His family trusts also intend to take up their
entitlement in full.
