<HEADLINE>
FT  11 MAY 91 / Finance &amp; The Family: Playing with your life - The hard sums
behind annuities
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JOHN AUTHERS and PHILIP COGGAN
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
ANNUITIES are not for the squeamish. This becomes clear as soon as the
calculations behind the rates offered by different life insurance offices
are examined - when you take out an annuity, you are effectively placing a
bet with the life insurance office on how long you will live.
An annuity is a contract to pay a given amount each year, while the annuity
holder remains alive. The capital is eaten into, allowing for a particularly
high income.
However, in practice they will not appeal to those under 55, and become
enticing once you have reached the age of 70. You will be in competition
with inflation, which erodes the value of your annuity with each year that
passes.
The other disadvantage is that the life office will keep all the money you
have deposited, even if you die very soon afterwards. You can opt to
guarantee the product for a certain number of years, or to ensure that you
at least receive back the capital, but this is not necessarily a product to
endear you to your heirs.
However, this could be viewed as an advantage. By the time you stop
receiving your annuity, you will have been completely released from the
problems of personal finance.
As the accompanying list shows (see right), annuities come in a bewildering
variety of packages. The law provides that you must buy an annuity with the
bulk of the funds you receive from your pension scheme or plan when you
retire. As the rates being offered vary substantially between different life
offices, it is worth shopping around to find the best deal.
When not bought as part of a pension arrangement your annuity will receive
more favourable tax treatment. Annuity payments are classed as return of
capital with some interest element, and you will only be taxed on the
interest, making the package attractive to higher-rate tax payers.
When taking out an annuity this way, you should be careful with timing, as
well as with your choice of life office. Annuity values tend to fluctuate in
line with UK government gilts, and it is worth locking in while interest
rates are high.
Temporary annuities pay a fixed income for a given period, or during the
purthe shorter. The capital disappears on death and the rates are higher for
older people.
Such annuities thus convert capital into income, and have tax advantages.
They can be used to pre-fund lumpy calls on income, such as school fees,
although Michael Chadwick of Chase de Vere says better rates of return can
be achieved with other products.
Often temporary annuities are linked to other investments, such as a with
profits endowment policy. Part of the income from the annuities is used to
fund the premiums for the policy; the hope is that the endowment will grow
sufficiently to replace the capital invested in the temporary annuity. Other
deals aim to maintain your wealth, making them more useful for inheritance
tax planning.
THE ANNUITIES ON OFFER
SEVERAL ANNUITIES are available. Your choice is as follows:
Temporary Annuities. These have a fixed term, and thus offer larger returns
than annuities which only terminate on death. A typical term would be ten
years.
The best rates available at present on a nine-year annuity for a 70 year old
man paying Pounds 10,000 initially are Pounds 2069.79 from Generali, and
Pounds 2,067.40 from Friends Provident, according to Baronworth Investment
Services.
Immediate Annuities. The basic and best-known form, which keeps paying you
the same amount each year until your death. Best rates according to
Baronworth, keeping assumptions constant from the previous example, are
Pounds 1,647.00 from RNPF Nurses, and Pounds 1,604.64 from Sun Alliance.
Compulsory Purchase Annuities. These are similar to immediate annuities, but
the sum to fund them comes from the proceeds of a pension scheme. You are
obliged by law to buy one out of the bulk of the proceeds of your matured
pension plan, although you do not have to buy the annuity offered by your
pension scheme or provider. Unlike immediate and temporary annuities these
pension-type contracts are treated as income, without a capital content, and
are taxed accordingly.
Joint Life Annuities. These involve annuities on the lives of two people,
and they keep paying out until both have died. There are attractions for
married couples who feel that they are both in good health, but the amounts
paid are much less than for annuities on a single life. For example,
Baronworth quotes the following example: a 75-year-old man paying Pounds
10,000 can receive a Pounds 1,907.04 annuity for the rest of his life. If
the same man spent the same amount on an annuity for himself and his
70-year-old wife, with the same company, the couple would receive Pounds
1,316.04 between them per year.
Index-linked Annuities. These are a particular triumph of actuarial science.
The life office agrees to increase the amount you receive each year by the
rate of increase in the retail prices index. This means that your income is
inflation-proofed, but it will start at a substantially lower level.
Increasing Annuities. These are similar in some ways to index-linked
annuities. However, in these cases the life insurance company will guarantee
a fixed percentage increase in your annuity each year until you die. If you
think inflation is going to be less than the rate of increase offered, then
these may make sense - although bear in mind that you are pitting your wits
against the actuaries and the financial markets.
</TEXT>
<PUB>The Financial Times
</PUB>
