<HEADLINE>
FT  11 MAY 91 / Markets: Oh no, postman's knock again - Serious Money
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By PHILIP COGGAN, Personal Finance Editor
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THE NIGHTMARE is this. I am trapped in a room with no doors or windows, only
a letter box through which junk mail from financial companies pours
unceasingly. It reaches my waist, then my neck. I am finally suffocated by a
bumper package on life insurance.
We are all on somebody's mailing list. The vast majority of banks and
building societies is either tied to, or owns, a life company. A credit card
bill, it seems, is not complete without an accompanying leaflet and
brochure.
It is hard to escape this onslaught. Commercial breaks on television seem
dominated by the financial sector. Open a magazine or Sunday newspaper - and
the chances are a leaflet from an insurance company will fall out.
The TV adverts are primarily about name recognition. Few people, confronted
by an advert for Eagle Star, will say 'Good Lord. It has all become clear. I
will ring up and insure my life tomorrow.' But a financial adviser will find
it easier to sell an Eagle Star product, if the client knows the name.
However, the expense of these campaigns needs to be watched. Nationwide
Anglia, a mutual building society, did not have the cash to notify its
depositors of the abolition of some of its accounts. But it could afford to
finance the TV campaign in which a bearded father reads aloud a pretentious
letter to his son.
The tide of junk mail is mainly directed at selling specific products. Much
of it is depressing. 'What would happen to your wife and family if you died,
Mr Jenkins?' or 'How would you cope if you fall seriously ill?' Absolve your
worries with a monthly premium.
The alternative approach is to promise riches. Save just Pounds 40 a month,
we are told, and in 25 years, we will have a sum equal to the Gross National
Product of Canada.
It is tempting to throw the material straight in the bin, or better still,
take it down the recycling plant, in the hope that it is turned into
something useful.
Before you do, check that the material is not from a company with whom you
already have a relationship. If it is, check again to see if the glossy
brochures relate to a product you already use. Changes in terms and
conditions may be hidden in the small print.
One popular tactic is to trumpet some new service such as free travel
insurance (which you did not ask for) while sheepishly mentioning some
adverse development to the existing service in a later part of the document.
If you are tempted to buy a with the illustrations or projections provided
in the brochure. These are only designed to meet the standards of the
regulators, not the consumer.
If you are being offered a savings-related product, the chances are that the
company will give an illustration of the kind of sum you will receive after
a certain number of years. This will probably be based on an assumed 7 or
10.5 per cent growth rate.
But do not forget inflation. Write back to the company and ask them what the
real value of that sum would be, assuming 5 or 7 per cent annual inflation
respectively. The figure will not sound quite so impressive, especially if
you compare it with the total of the monthly or annual payments you are
being asked to make.
Also ask the company about its charges. Recent Money Management figures
showed the effect of charges for a 29 year old man paying Pounds 30 a month
into a 10 year unit-linked plan.
On growth of 7 per cent a year, a policy without charges would earn a sum of
Pounds 5,161. But someone who bought a policy from the company with the
highest charges in the industry, Swiss Pioneer, would earn just Pounds
3,463. That is less than the total (Pounds 3,600) of his contributions.
The illustration the company will probably give (but only with the cooling
off notice) will be based on figures from the Life Assurance and Unit Trust
Regulatory Organisation. This will show expenses only as a percentage
deduction from the investment return.
Such an illustration is too obscure. Do not be satisfied with it. On such a
policy, the industry average level of charges eats up Pounds 875 of your
money (assuming a 7 per cent annual investment return) and Pounds 1,102
(assuming 10 per cent growth).
Going back to the subject of inflation, 7 per cent annual investment growth
and average industry charges would in nominal terms be worth Pounds 4,286 in
10 years time. Assuming 5 per cent inflation, that would be worth just
Pounds 2,631 in today's money.
The really impressive payouts come over longer periods. The same 29 year old
man paying Pounds 30 a month over 25 years might be enticed by the prospect
of a Pounds 29,689 payout at the end, based on a 10.5 per cent investment
return. That compares, however, with Pounds 40,317 if no charges were
applied and Pounds 35,300 if the lowest charges in the industry (from London
Life) were used.
But if one assumes 7 per cent inflation over 25 years, then the value of
Pounds 29,689 in today's terms is just Pounds 5,470. The policyholder would
have paid in Pounds 4,543, if one applies the same 7 per cent discount to
the annual contribution of Pounds 360. So all that saving earns a real
profit of just Pounds 927.
You may not have the time to waste on analysing your junk mail. But you
should ask these questions before buying one of these products, just as you
should check the mileometer and brakes on a second hand car.
</TEXT>
<PUB>The Financial Times
</PUB>
