<HEADLINE>
FT  11 MAY 91 / Markets (At a glance): Oil sector begins to bubble
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JOHN AUTHERS
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
The oil sector has seen some active dealing on the stock market in recent
weeks, most of it hinging on switches between BP, the largest company in the
sector, and other smaller companies with speculative potential.
The whole sector was shaken by the news on Wednesday that Elf Aquitaine and
Enterprise Oil had made a deal to to accquire Occidental Petroleum's North
Sea assets for Dollars 1.35bn. Enterprise dropped 6p to 551p, having at one
point hit 570p, but switching into its high-yielding convertible stock led
to drops in the share price of the major stocks in the sector. BP dropped
11p to 343p on Wednesday.
Dealers were discounting a loss by BP for the first quarter, which would
have been the first ever in the company's history. The results, published on
Thursday, in fact revealed a net income of Pounds 10m, and shares edged up
3p to 346p on the news.
</TEXT>
