</DATE>
<HEADLINE>
FT  11 MAY 91 / Markets: A taxing time but Trafalgar battles on - The Bottom
Line
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ROLAND RUDD
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
HOW WOULD Trafalgar House shareholders react if the final dividend was
skipped later this year? As far as the directors are concerned the scenario
is not worth thinking about. Yet passing the dividend would be the simplest
solution to what is proving to be an intractable problem: the tax bill.
Taxation for the shipping-to-property group has risen to 33 per cent - a
good 10 per cent higher than normal. The group's UK profits are not big
enough to offset tax paid on the dividend against advanced corporation tax
(ACT). But there is no reason for shareholders to panic. If Sir Eric Parker,
chief executive, was prepared to raid reserves last year to pay a dividend
he is unlikely to pass it on in September.
A less painful way out is to buy a few British companies with a healthy
balance sheet. But that could require Trafalgar taking on more debt. Not an
impossible feat for a group with gearing at 54 per cent, but by no means
ideal. The group's favoured solution is to issue convertible loan stock. The
interest paid on the stock would be tax deductable. However, as far as
shareholders are concerned the simplest solution is for Trafalgar to earn
more profits in the UK.
In the short term that looks like a tall order. The results this week could
have been worse, but not much. For the six months to March Trafalgar's
pre-tax profits fell from Pounds 116.9m to Pounds 51.5m. True, there were
unusual circumstances. Its not every year that one of your world cruise
liners has to be re-routed to avoid a war in the Gulf. A recession does not
help either.
Yet the simple point about a conglomerate is that if one sector goes into
the red another should remain in the black. In Trafalgar's case just about
everything went red. The exception being construction. Thanks to a record
Pounds 2.9bn order book the sector's operating profits rose by 40 per cent
to Pounds 38.3m (Pounds 27.4m). (It was so good some analysts questioned the
figures at a meeting with the company. But the order book looks real
enough.)
What potential investors want to know is what chance is there of the red
spots turning black? Sir Eric is cautiously confident that property and
investment, down from Pounds 64.9m to Pounds 19m, is set to recover. So too
is just about every analyst. The only argument is when?
Sir Eric has detected a revival in UK housing. But not many analysts have
seen simular signs. Yet even if he is given the benefit of doubt it still
does not help investors know whether the sector is on the road to recovery.
The key is commercial property - a big earner in the past  - where the
decision to reclassify about Pounds 200m of investment properties as fixed
assets should be read as a warning sign: there is still worse to come. When
the properties are revalued in September there will be the inevitable
write-down. But the reclassification means that any devaluation will go
straight into reserves instead of showing up in the profit and loss account.
Nonetheless, even the pessimist will concede that the outlook for commercial
property will improve. The group is building three big developments. The
Brooklands business park should be on stream within five years when the
sector is expected to be making record profits.
A business park in Chiswick, west London, and office development in
Paddington, central London, should be completed by the end of the decade. On
the shipping front, the company can be forgiven for feeling a little sorry
for itself. It was more heavily exposed to the impact of the Gulf War and
the recession than its rivals.
This was because Cunard, Trafalgar House's cruise shipping operation, places
a higher proportion of its vessels outside the US market. When there is a
war US citizens, who count for around 80 per cent of Cunard's market, tend
not to venture too far from home.
The fall in profits, from Pounds 30.1m to Pounds 7.6m, would have been worse
but for the fact that the Cunard Princess was chartered out for recreation
during the Gulf War. That said, the worst is behind Trafalgar. The group is
reporting signs of recovery in the cruise market. While it may not be soon
enough to affect this year's end results, it should make an impact by 1992.
In the long-term there is more reason to feel bullish about the company. The
group's 9.1 per cent yield, the second highest in the Footsie, is expected
to fall as its shares rise. Its net asset value of Pounds 165m includes out
of date valuations of the QE2 and other five star vessels. Analysts believe
the true asset figure is closer to Pounds 350m.
While Sir Eric has ruled out throwing any immediate sops to shareholders by
demerging he has reason to expect significantly bigger profits, particularly
from commercial property, within the next three to four years. By that time
he should even be able to reduce the tax bill.
</TEXT>
<PUB>The Financial Times
</PUB>
