<DOCNO>FT911-525</DOCNO>
<PROFILE>_AN-BELAGABOFT</PROFILE>
<DATE>910511
</DATE>
<HEADLINE>
FT  11 MAY 91 / The Lex Column: Granada
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
The most rumoured rights issue in recent history finally hit the screens
yesterday. Granada, though, must have gassed its mole before news could leak
of the accompanying 40 per cent dividend cut and the full extent of the
company's indebtedness. When the whole story was revealed, the shares
tumbled 13 per cent.
It is hard not to feel some sympathy for Mr Lewis, scapegoat for a series of
ill-fated adventures in which others played an equally central part. The
lurid boardroom drama has nevertheless served to obscure the fact that the
timing of Granada's operation was closely linked to the refinancing of
BSkyB. With or without Mr Lewis's scalp, no institutional shareholder could
have contemplated offering its support when the (admittedly faint)
possibility still existed that the terrestrial TV company's Pounds 130m loan
guarantee to its satellite cousin could suddenly be called in.
The new shares have been pitched at such a big discount that one wonders
whether the issue needed to be underwritten at all. Investors, however, must
face up to a period of uncertainty during the TV franchise bid and the hunt
for a new chief executive. With the prop of a high yield now removed, the
prospects thereafter will depend on how much the franchise costs, how
quickly computer services can be turned round, and whether BSkyB fulfils its
promise. That makes it more risky than a straightforward recovery stock.
</TEXT>
