<DOCNO>FT911-530</DOCNO>
<PROFILE>_AN-BELAGABJFT</PROFILE>
<DATE>910511
</DATE>
<HEADLINE>
FT  11 MAY 91 / World Stock Markets: Stale Japanese bulls explore pastures
new - Disappointed investors have stopped holding their breath
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ROBERT THOMSON
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
JAPANESE investors have been holding their breath for the past few weeks,
waiting for a reduction in official interest rates. But the cut has not
come, the stock market remains sluggish, and the recently expectant
investors are putting their funds elsewhere.
Over the past month, the Tokyo market has been characterised by low volumes
and a narrow trading range, in spite of Japanese institutions' best
intentions to begin the new financial year positively and to leave behind a
bruising fiscal 1990.
While the impact of a cut in the Official Discount Rate (ODR) on real
lending rates is questionable, the ODR still exercises a powerful influence
on the market's outlook. Shares were bought in February and March on the
presumption of a rate reduction.
It was expected that the ODR, now at 6 per cent, would fall to 5.5 per cent;
and, for the past two weeks, brokers have attempted to extract extra hope
and client purchases out of the situation by talking of a cut of 0.75 of a
percentage point.
The argument went that Japan was under severe international pressure to
reduce rates, and that a 0.5 per cent reduction would not be enough to keep
Washington happy.
Until now, the Bank of Japan has been unmoved, as has the Tokyo market.
Volumes have been around a poor 300m shares in recent days, and the Nikkei
average has alternately risen and fallen by small amounts, without any real
signs of buying confidence.
The central bank argues that further heat needs to be removed from an
overwarm economy, and that a cut in rates could prompt a return to the
speculative share-buying binges of 1989. The bank's argument seems to be
supported by the erratic movements of a few stocks, which have apparently
been targeted by still-active speculator groups looking for quick profits in
a dull market.
Among the more volatile movers have been Kawai Musical Instruments, the
world's second largest maker of pianos, and Taiyo Sanso, a semiconductor
cleaning equipment maker, both of which hit 1991 highs during trading
yesterday. Brokers indicate that they are typical of the small to
medium-sized issues chosen by investors more for their volatility potential
than for business-related reasons.
Japanese brokers are hoping that the business results season, which begins
next week, will inspire interest. Mr Paul Heaton, deputy head of research at
WI Carr, says that investors are likely to be more interested in the
forecasts for this year than in last year's results, most of which have
already been released on an informal basis.
'Most companies have already announced the revisions for expected results
for last year, so it will be more important to look at the predicted
profits. For example, companies in the service companies could be looking at
good profit growth,' Mr Heaton adds.
Mr Craig Chudler, investment strategist at UBS Phillips &amp; Drew, says that
the market would have fallen further but for strong arbitrage-related
buying. This has allowed the Nikkei average to settle at around at 26,000,
he says, but essentially it is not a reflection of confidence in the
market's strength.
Individuals and foreign investors were enthusiastic buyers of shares earlier
this year, but their interest has waned. The buying by foreigners followed a
realisation by fund managers, at the end of last year, that they were
underweight in Tokyo.
As for individual investors, officials at the Tokyo exchange and the Finance
Ministry have attempted to lure them back to the market by encouraging
companies to pay higher dividends. The focus on dividends was sharpened by
life insurance companies' threats to sell stock holdings unless yields were
improved.
So far, there has been little evidence of either an increase in dividends or
a sell-off of strategic stock holdings by the life insurance companies. A
survey released this week by the Nihon Keizai Shimbun, the leading Japanese
financial daily, indicates that Japanese executives remain convinced that
shareholders come low on the list of priorities.
The survey of 2,396 listed companies found that 41.3 per cent of executives
want earnings to be used for capital spending, while 30.2 per cent think
that they should be distributed among employees and 19.6 per cent believe
that shareholders should receive the benefits. Meanwhile, 86 per cent of the
respondents said that US companies' focus on high dividends was partly
responsible for their present financial problems.
Some Japanese companies are making an attempt to attract individual
investors by reducing their minimum trading units from 1,000 to 100 shares.
In recent weeks, Asatsu, the advertising agency, Tachikawa Corporation, the
leading maker of blinds and partitions, and Sega Enterprises, an amusement
equipment maker, have announced reductions, and brokers say that many other
companies will follow if the move proves to be successful.
</TEXT>
