<HEADLINE>
FT  11 MAY 91 / London Stock Exchange: Bank warning unsettles share prices
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
A WARNING from the Bank of England that it does not want UK base rates to
fall for the next two weeks, together with a batch of somewhat bearish
reports to shareholders from leading British companies, took the heart out
of the UK stock market yesterday. After challenging its all-time peak of
FT-SE 2,545.3 in an early response to the gain of 40 Dow points on New York
overnight, the London market turned down to close with a net fall of 17.5 on
the day.
The Bank of England's warning, conveyed by conventional signals to the
London money markets, stressed that it wanted domestic rates to stay at 12
per cent for the next fourteen days. This period takes in May 17, the date
on which a further fall in Britain's retail price index (RPI) is expected
and consequently the date marked by City analysts as the likely day for a
cut in base rates.
'This (the Bank's move) will be very depressing for some of the interest
rate optimists,' commented Mr Ian Harnett at Strauss Turnbull, although he
added that an interest rate cut remains merely a question of timing. 'We
still think base rates will be down to 11 1/2 per cent within the next
month.'
The early gain of 13.1 to 2,554.9 in the equity market was soon trimmed
after Granada, the leisure and television group, hit the market with a
widely-predicted rights issue call for Pounds 163m, together with a
depressing trading report. The equity market has faced funding calls almost
daily for the past three weeks as the Pounds 2bn rights issue list recorded
in the first quarter of the year has been steadily increased during April
and May. However, investment funds' cash holdings remain relatively high.
The gloom hanging over the market increased as the session progressed and
shareholders attending annual meetings of such leading UK companies as P &amp;
O, Bowater, Hawker Siddeley and Pearson were all given warnings on the
current state of business.
At the session's low point, the Footsie was down by more than 19 points.
However, by the close, the FT-SE Index had steadied at 2,524.3 for a net
loss on the day of 17.5 points. Over the week, which is the first leg of the
two week trading account, the market has moved very erratically as hopes for
an early cut in base rates have ebbed and flowed; by last night, the gain on
the week was a mere 1.4 points.
With its hopes for a reduction in base rates next Friday now severely
jolted, the equity market was looking subdued at the close of trading.
However, there was little significant selling pressure yesterday and
Seaq-recorded turnover of 423m shares was not the highest daily figure even
for a week which has been accompanied by a return to very low trading
levels.
Trading volume has again fallen below last year's daily averages in the face
of bearish views from British industry and a steady erosion of funds' cash
holdings by right issues.
</TEXT>
