FT  11 MAY 91 / UK Company News: Quotient receives approach
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ALAN CANE
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
QUOTIENT, London-based computer firm specialising in stock processing
software, confirmed yesterday that it had received an approach which might
lead to an offer. At yesterday's closing price of 118p, a rise of 28p on the
day, a full bid would be worth a little more than Pounds 16m.
Mr Tim Simon, Quotient chairman and chief executive, refused yesterday to
identify the potential suitor. Discussions about the approach were in
progress with Quotient's financial adviser, Samuel Montagu, but he could not
say when the company would be able to make a further statement.
The share price has risen by 34 per cent since April 5 when ACT, the
Birmingham-based computer services company, raised its stake from 0.9 per
cent to 13.1 per cent.
ACT sold its Apricot workstation business to Mitsubishi of Japan last year
leaving it with net cash of about Pounds 25m. Mr Roger Foster, ACT chairman,
has made no secret of his intention to use the cash for strategic
acquisitions, especially among companies weakened by the economic downturn.
ACT already has a strong financial services division. Some 20 per cent of
ACT's stock is held by Singer &amp; Friedlander, the merchant bank.
Quotient, which both processes stock and develops software packages for
brokers to use in-house, was badly hit by the fall in the world's stock
markets in the late 1980s and suffered a loss of almost Pounds 1.6m in 1989.
Last year pre-tax profits were a little more than Pounds 1m on sales of
Pounds 22.4m. It is developing an advanced trading system in partnership
with Fujitsu of Japan.
</TEXT>
