<HEADLINE>
FT  11 MAY 91 / UK Company News: Textile recession leaves Parkland Pounds
3.6m in red
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ALICE RAWSTHORN
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THE RECESSION in the textile industry claimed another victim yesterday when
Parkland, the Yorkshire-based wool textile group, announced a Pounds 5.64m
downturn to a pre-tax loss of Pounds 3.6m for the year ended March 1 1991.
The group was hit by the dramatic drop in the wool price as well as by the
depressed demand for textiles. The loss equalled 43.3p per share (earnings
23.9p on pre-tax profits of Pounds 2.04m), and the final dividend is cut to
1p (4.5p) for a total of 2.5p (6.7p).
Mr Paul Hanson, deputy chief executive, said the group had experienced a
'very difficult' year. The domestic and export markets were very weak and
the fall in the wool price - which left Parkland with over-priced wool
stocks - was 'the final straw'.
Turnover fell to Pounds 50.71m (Pounds 55.8m) and the group incurred an
operating loss of Pounds 1.14m (profits of Pounds 1.85m). The group paid
Pounds 351,000 (credit of Pounds 193,000) in interest on year-end gearing of
20 per cent.
The loss on wool stocks and rationalisation costs produced an exceptional
charge of Pounds 2.11m. Extraordinary costs of Pounds 159,000 were also
incurred because of the impact of the Gulf war on the Middle East export
business.
The ordinary shares slipped by 2p to 143p on the announcement yesterday. The
'A' shares also fell by 2p to 91p.
Mr Hanson said the group had 'dug deep' in its cost cutting by accelerating
the closure of two clothing factories and one weaving mill as its modernised
plants came on stream. The workforce was reduced from 1,800 to 1,450 during
the year.
He said trading conditions were still tough, but there were some signs of
slight improvement in the knitwear market and the cloth market had 'levelled
off'.
</TEXT>
