<HEADLINE>
FT  11 MAY 91 / Letter: Why there are no 'followers'
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   From Mr P J PACE O'SHEA
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Sir, Your columnist Joe Rogaly ('Business: ex cathedra', May 3) states that
the Pope 'is regarded by his followers as infallible on matters of doctrine
and Christian principle'.
I make no comment on the subject matter of the article but I would like to
say, as a Catholic, that the Pope has no 'followers'. There are certain
religions or sects within religions in which the members could be described
as the followers of a leader but that is not the case in the Catholic Church
or, for that matter, in the whole Christian Church. We Catholics and all
those who hold the Christian faith are the followers of Jesus Christ only.
And besides not being the Pope's followers many of us do not accept this
modern doctrine of infallibility. It is not an article of faith.
I should add that encyclicals are not Scripture. They are the views of the
'CEO' and those who share his views, but there is a great variety of
opinions in the universal church.
The arguments and opinions expressed in encyclicals change with the times
and contradict themselves over time.
P J Pace O'Shea,
45 Fellows Road, NW3
</TEXT>
