<HEADLINE>
FT  11 MAY 91 / US-Arab deals will be kept secret
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By PETER RIDDELL, US Editor
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   WASHINGTON
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
MANY important features of the general understandings reached between the US
and Saudi Arabia and other Gulf states about maintaining an American
military presence in the region will be kept secret because of Arab
sensitivity about too close an identification with Washington.
As he returned to the US yesterday from a visit to the Gulf states, Mr
Richard Cheney, the US defence secretary, said there was now 'broad
agreement on a regional basis for co-operation between the US and the
governments in the area on security matters. There is a significantly
enhanced willingness on the part of many of the governments in the region to
co-operate on security arrangements.'
Many issues have still to be decided in further negotiations, such as the
frequency of joint exercises between the US and Gulf states, the size of
forces involved, the nature of contingency planning, and arrangements for
storing equipment in the region. The US opposes having permanent bases but
wants forces to be involved in big sea, land and air exercises, with troops
rotated regularly.
Even after these matters are resolved, many will remain secret. 'It's still
the Middle East and therefore a certain amount of discretion is required in
terms of what you say publicly,' Mr Cheney said.
Mr Cheney also discussed sales of US conventional arms to Gulf states to
improve their ability to defend themselves.
The US aim is to strengthen local forces and pre-position supplies.
The number of US troops in the region has dropped from a peak of 540,000 in
late February to about 160,000.
</TEXT>
<PUB>The Financial Times
</PUB>
<PAGE>
London Page 2
</PAGE>
