<HEADLINE>
FT  11 MAY 91 / Tokyo house sales fall
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ROBERT THOMSON
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   TOKYO
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
SALES of new condominiums in the greater Tokyo area fell 46.3 per cent in
April from a year earlier, reviving fears that Japan's property market slump
will intensify in coming months, Robert Thomson writes from Tokyo.
April is generally a strong month for property sales in Japan, but the sales
figures announced yesterday by the Real Estate Economic Institute were the
worst April figures for 19 years.
The proportion of condominiums sold before being built in Tokyo and three
neighbouring prefectures fell to 56.8 per cent, down from 87.7 per cent in
the same month last year, while the year-on-year sales figure was lower for
the sixth month.
Japan's property slump has been uneven, with prices falling 10 per cent for
some condominiums on the fringe of Tokyo and larger falls recorded in Osaka.
The surprisingly poor figures for April will put further pressure on
apartment developers, who have been hit by the increase in interest rates,
declining sales and growing inventories.
</TEXT>
