<DATE>910510
</DATE>
<HEADLINE>
FT  10 MAY 91 / London Stock Exchange: Political factors return to the
market
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
THE UK stock market continued on its erratic course yesterday, climbing by
18 points on the FT-SE Index scale as interest rate optimism was encouraged
by some apparent indications of increased political pressures for an early
general election in the UK. Helped also by a firm opening to the new Wall
Street session, London closed virtually at the best of the day, although
trading volume remained disappointing.
The broader background to the equity market remained much the same as for
the past fortnight. Hopes for a further cut in UK base rates continued to
focus around the April retail price index announcement, due at the end of
next week. Uncertainty on the depth and length of the economic recession in
the UK was reflected in the market's cautious response to trading statements
from several UK companies.
The chief corporate hurdle of the day, in the form of a first-quarter
trading statement from British Petroleum, passed off well, with the oil
group's profits better than anticipated in the City of London. There was not
much movement in BP shares, however, and the oil sector settled down to wait
for trading figures due next week from Shell.
Share prices opened higher yesterday morning behind firm performances in
Tokyo and New York and, with many European markets closed yesterday for
Ascension Day, made further progress after the FT-SE June futures contract
came in strongly again and spurred the blue chip stocks ahead.
In the absence of significant buying support from the institutions, the
advance in equities slowed down and not until mid-session did the gain on
the FT-SE Index extend to around 16 points.
The market then paused until Wall Street opened, but pushed ahead again when
the Dow average, after a slow start, recorded a gain of nearly 30 points in
London trading hours.
At its final reading of 2,541.8, the FT-SE Index showed a gain on the day of
18.4. Dealers believe the market is currently trading in a range of FT-SE
2,520 to 2,550 at present, and unlikely to break out of the top end of this
bracket until a further half-point cut in base rates is announced, perhaps
after the RPI statement at the end of next week.
Seaq volume of 409m shares compared with 387.9m on Wednesday and 431.2m on
Tuesday, continuing the fall in average daily volumes since the end of the
first quarter of the year.
The dearth of trading volume again gave the stock index futures market
increased leverage on share prices. Both at the beginning of the session and
late in the day, activity in the Footsie set the pace for the underlying
equity market.
The stock market has another week to run before the end of the current
trading account. The retail price index (RPI) is not due until the last day
of the account and, with the corporate reporting calendar also relatively
light, strategists believe that share prices will continue to find
difficulty in making progress next week.
The possibility that the UK government might choose to hold a general
election in June rather than in the autumn or next year surfaced after the
Labour opposition party appeared to spell out its election priorities.
While the prospect of an early election might increase political pressures
for cuts in base rates, the stock market appeared unconvinced yesterday that
the political mood had changed significantly.
</TEXT>
<PUB>The Financial Times
</PUB>
<PAGE>
London Page 36
</PAGE>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>FT911-585</DOCNO>
<PROFILE>_AN-BEJAXAGIFT</PROFILE>
<DATE>910510
</DATE>
<HEADLINE>
FT  10 MAY 91 / London Stock Exchange: Relief at BP results
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
THERE WAS widespread relief around the market with BP's first-quarter
trading figures, which narrowly avoided showing what would have been the
first quarterly loss on record. The group disclosed net income of Pounds 10m
compared with the Pounds 344m for the same period last year.
A loss for the period had been expected, with some of the more pessimistic
analysts going for a shortfall of as much as Pounds 70m. Specialists
highighted the good performance of the group's downstream business. Mr Nick
Clayton at Smith New Court said: 'It augurs well for Shell's results, due
next week.'
Mr John Toalster at Societe Generale Strauss Turnbull remained cautious on
BP, pointing out that, on a historic cost basis, the dividend would still be
uncovered. The shares edged up 3 to 346p on turnover of 6.3m.
Also circulating in the market was a suggestion, triggered by a report in
the Spanish press, that BP might be about to buy a big stake in Petromed,
the Spanish refiner. BP said it holds an option to buy 8 to 15 per cent of
Petromed which remains valid until the end of this year.
Automotive troubles
Several automotive issues were unsettled by the combined effects of two more
cash-raising calls, a securities house downgrading of the sector and
cautious views on trading prospects from leading component manufacturers.
GKN fell after Smith New Court cut its estimate of current year profits to
Pounds 100m from Pounds 120m. The investment house pointed out that at the
new level the automotive group would have to dip into reserves to maintain
the dividend rate. Smith also lowered profits expectations for Laird Group,
BBA Group and T &amp; N.
GKN chairman Mr David Lees later informed the annual meeting that profits in
the first half will fall 'well below' those of the second half of last year.
The news thwarted any recovery in shares of GKN, which closed 8 down at
349p.
The second rights issue within a week by an automotive company came from BBA
Group. Shareholders are being asked to put up Pounds 79.1m in order to
reduce gearing. The chairman said non-automotive businesses constituted 64
per cent of operating profits last year, and it is intended to maintain the
dividend rate this year. The shares still dipped 12 to 127p.
T &amp; N shrugged off initial easiness brought on by the Smith New Court
downgrade after the chairman told the annual meeting yesterday he was
confident that 'our continuing commitment will yield substantial benefit
once demand improves'. The shares eventually settled 4 up at 160p.
Motor distributor Pendragon called for cash of Pounds 11m to repay
borrowings and fund development plans, news which left the stock 3 easier at
145p, after touching 140p.
BTR slips back
BTR suffered a delayed reaction to a cautious annual meeting statement. The
shares were only modestly held back initially but dropped sharply in the
afternoon session.
Marketmakers believed that some analysts would cut their forecasts for the
company today. Sir Owen Green, BTR's chairman, said: 'The unsatisfactory
trading levels that we experienced during the second half of last year have
persisted in most areas of our world. As a consequence, the results for the
first four months of this year have fallen short of those for the comparable
1990 period.'
Traders said a single persistent seller did most of the damage and recalled
BTR's downbeat annual meeting statement a year ago, which presaged a period
of share underperformance. One analyst added that the company's suggestions
after yesterday's meeting that it had ruled out wholesale disposals of
business might have disappointed some investors. BTR fell to 396p before
ending at 401p for a net decline of 5. Turnover was a busy 4.4m.
SmithKline Beecham continued to slide on profit-taking that followed
Wednesday's first-quarter figures. Traders said much of the selling came
from New York, where investors preferred Glaxo. SmithKline lost 9 to 800p
and Glaxo climbed 16 to 1121p.
Building issues raced higher, responding to the better outlook for mortgage
interest rates. Redland advanced 15 to 585p after some determined buying by
Hoare Govett; the broker hosted a presentation to institutional clients
yesterday.
Lilley held at 45p; Scottish stockbroking firm Parsons Penny, Lilley's joint
broker along with BZW, is believed to have placed a 12.6m line of shares in
the building group at around 43p. The shares were sold by former directors
of Hatfield Estates, taken over by Lilley just over a year ago. An attempted
placing of the same stake some weeks ago was unsuccessful.
National Power was one of the biggest traded stocks, with 18m shares
changing hands. It closed 3 1/2 higher at 137p and was said to have been
catching up on PowerGen after a period of underperformance. Brokers
connected to the flotation of the two generators will from Monday be allowed
to publish their own profits estimates for the companies. They are expected
to be bullish. PowerGen was a shade up at 142p on 7m.
Other utilities were strongly supported, the Electricity Package adding 60
at Pounds 2125 and the Water Package 48 at Pounds 3083.
British Gas, helped in recent sessions by a number of top broking firms
taking a more positive stance on the shares, rose 5 to 244p on 6.5m after
dealers reported the emergence of an unlikely story that Hanson is preparing
a bid for the utility. 'Hanson does not go for regulated businesses,' said
one Gas specialist.
Revived investment demand found sellers reluctant in ECC stock and the price
advanced quickly in thin trading to end 9 higher at 432p.
The celebrations continued for United Uniform Services which, on Wednesday,
reported greatly improved annual profits as well as a return to the dividend
list. The shares added 4 for a two-day advance of 21 at 109p.
Rentokil, the diversified group with activities in environmental services
and property care, was favoured and appreciated 9 to 286p. Researcher Mr Per
Chrom-Jacobsen of Baring Securities rates the stock a buy.
Sears was unchanged at 90p on turnover of 14m following lower than expected
final results. Once property profits were stripped out, the profits of
Pounds 107.1m compared with Pounds 169.6m last time and estimates of Pounds
110m to Pounds 115m, according to Mr Nick Hawkins of Kleinwort Benson. The
large turnover in the shares was caused by a two-way pull between buying by
income funds and selling by investors worried that the dividend may be in
jeopardy.
Albert Fisher put on 2 to 123p as Corporate Partners, the investment
affiliate of Lazard Freres, said it had bought 3m shares, taking its Fisher
holding to 36m or 6.09 per cent of the equity.
Land Securities advanced 13 to 529p in steady trade. Credit Lyonnais issued
a buy note on the stock, saying it had underperformed by 20 per cent this
year. 'Unless rents collapse . . . compound dividend growth of around 15 per
cent to March 1993 can still be expected,' concluded the broker.
Yorkshire Television outperformed most of the television contracting sector.
Market-makers said sentiment had been helped by press reports of sales of
the company's popular TV series The Darling Buds of May outside the UK. The
company said it anticipated worldwide sales and added yesterday that it was
still in talks with US networks. The shares gained 7 to 295p.
Emap's agreed bid for Radio City left the former 2 off at 229p and the
latter 92 up at 377p. Emap is offering 476p worth of its shares for each
Radio City voting share and 398 1/2 p in shares for each non-voting share.
The offer is worth about Pounds 10.7m.
A substantial review of the electricals sector by Hoare Govett triggered
some keen two-way interest in the area. Hoare's Mr Jim Ross said the
construction products side of the industry (cables, domestic plugs, switches
and fuseboxes) offered the best prospects at present.
The Hoare analyst said demand for electrical construction products is
forecast to grow by 8 per cent next year and 12 per cent in 1993. Hoare's
favourites in this area are BICC, FKI and Volex. BICC edged up 2 to 429p
while Volex moved up 3 to 264p. FKI held at 57p in spite of two big
individual trades. Hoare is bearish on the power and rail equipment market,
and in particular GEC and Hawker Siddeley.
