<HEADLINE>
FT  10 MAY 91 / World Stock Markets (America): Futures-related demand lifts
Dow
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By KAREN ZAGOR
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   NEW YORK
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
Wall Street
SEVERAL rounds of futures-related programme buying fuelled a late-afternoon
rally on Wall Street yesterday as US equities shrugged off paltry demand at
the 30-year bond auction and moved broadly higher, writes Karen Zagor in New
York.
At the finish the Dow Jones Industrial Average was 40.25 stronger at
2,971.15, its highest level since standing at 2,999.26 on April 18. The
Standard &amp; Poor's 500 climbed 4.74 to 383.25. Rises outpaced falls by 1,113
to 495 after a moderate volume of 180.2m shares, but an increase from the
previous day's 157m.
The Dow, which has been extremely sensitive to the US Treasury's quarterly
refunding auctions this week, overcame surprisingly weak demand at the
afternoon sale of Dollars 11.75bn in 30-year notes. Investors were
encouraged by the firmness of the bond market, where the treasury's
benchmark 30-year ent in late trading.
Technology issues contributed to the stock market gains, with IBM rising
Dollars 2 to Dollars 105 3/4 .
Mobil Oil, which said it will boost capital spending to Dollars 5bn from
Dollars 4.4bn, gained Dollars  7/8 to Dollars 69 5/8 . Exxon added Dollars 1
3/8 at Dollars 59 5/8 . Occidental Petroleum, one of the most active New
York SE issues for a second consecutive day following an agreement to sell
its North Sea oil interests for Dollars 1.35bn, climbed Dollars  7/8 to
Dollars 21 1/8 .
Ford Motor firmed Dollars  3/8 to Dollars 32 7/8 . At the company's annual
meeting the chairman said he could not rule out further lay-offs in the US.
Chrysler shed Dollars  1/4 to Dollars 13 but General Motors advanced Dollars
1 1/4 to Dollars 38 3/8 .
Wal-Mart moved ahead Dollars 2 1/8 to Dollars 42 after unveiling a 21 per
cent increase in first-quarter net income to Dollars 307m on sales up 37 per
cent to Dollars 9.28bn.
The secondary market also took part in yesterday's rally, with the Nasdaq
composite climbing 5.30 to 497.81.
Intel was one of the most actively traded over-the-counter issues, adding
Dollars 3 at Dollars 54 1/2 on expectations that it will make a line of
personal computers to be sold by Digital Equipment. The latter rose Dollars
 7/8 to Dollars 66 1/8 on the NYSE.
Bizmart forged ahead Dollars 1 3/4 to Dollars 15 in active trading after the
company said it is involved in talks about a possible takeover bid.
Immunex, which rose Dollars 1 7/8 to Dollars 42 3/4 , expects to break even
in 1991 with the help of sales of Leukine, its GM-CSF white blood cell
stimulant product.
Canada
THE SHARP Wall Street rise spurred Toronto forward in further moderate
trading. The composite index closed 22.5 ahead at 3,504.5. Advances led
declines by 314 to 221 after volume of 20.8m shares.
Memotec Data put on CDollars  3/8 to CDollars 9 in spite of turmoil
surrounding the election of its board at next week's annual meeting. Gordon
Capital Corp has issued a proxy circular in an attempt to replace three
nominees to Memotec's board, including the chairman and the president and
chief executive, with three Gordon Capital nominees.
Quadra Logic said clinical trials suggest that its Photofrin anti-cancer
drug can delay the occurrence of tumours in bladder cancer cases. The shares
added CDollars  3/8 at CDollars 10 7/8 after rising CDollars 1 5/8 on
Wednesday.
</TEXT>
