<HEADLINE>
FT  10 MAY 91 / Commodities and Agriculture: Oil prices rise on series of
mishaps
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By DEBORAH HARGREAVES
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
OIL PRICES moved higher yesterday as traders bought crude after a series of
accidents at oil refineries in the US and Saudi Arabia.
The price of North Sea Brent crude for June delivery rose by 25 cents to
Dollars 20.10 a barrel in an active market.
Saudi Arabia's Yanbu refinery on the Red Sea coast was operating below its
275,000 barrels a day capacity after the catalytic cracker unit - a key
piece of sophisticated refining equipment - broke down on Wednesday. There
were some indications there could be delays in deliveries.
Prices for unleaded gasoline moved higher in the US after news of a fire at
a Shell refinery in Louisiana. These later dragged up crude prices by about
5 cents to Dollars 21.83 for the June futures contract on the New York
Mercantile Exchange by midsession yesterday.
As traders rushed into the London market, the rally started to feed on
itself and some were puzzled about the strength in price.
'I'm confused,' said Mr Peter Gignoux, director of Lehman Brothers energy
desk, 'refineries are stuck with crude, but short of products and crude
rallies on the back of it.'
Refined products prices were also higher and gasoline moved up to Dollars
255 a tonne in Rotterdam from Dollars 246 a tonne.
Mobil, the US oil company, a joint venture partner in the Saudi Yanbu
refinery, reportedly notified customers of some May delivery delays.
