<HEADLINE>
FT  10 MAY 91 / Commodities and Agriculture: Fears for US cotton harvest as
torrential rain continues
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By NANCY DUNNE
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   WASHINGTON
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
A deluge has been keeping the cotton farmers of the Mississippi Delta
indoors and driving futures prices to their highest levels in years.
In Northern Louisiana, the rain has flooded thousands of homes and farm
acres. Some residents have been driven from their homes and others are
living without clean running water.
The Delta last year produced 4.9m bales of cotton. The forecast this year
was for 6.1m bales, but as the rain has continued, that estimate has been
slipping.
Usually one-half to three-quarters of the 1.5m acres of cotton lands are
planted by this time in Mississippi, Tennessee, Arkansas, Louisiana, Alabama
and Georgia.
In one Mississippi county, Coahoma, only 4 per cent of the 96,000 acres has
been sown so far.
Any planting after May 20 is considered late, according to Mr Terry
Townsend, a spokesman for the International Cotton Advisory Committee in
Washington.
American cotton requires 140 to 160 days of warmth before harvest, or yields
are considerably reduced.
'Even if it stopped raining today, it could take a week to dry out,' Mr
Townsend said. 'But the forecast is for additional rain this weekend. There
is some talk that the crop won't get planted until the last week of May or
the first week of June.'
Problems could arise if the harvest runs into the middle of October, when
the rains generally begin again. At that point, the quality may deteriorate.
With stocks at their lowest point in decades, the New York futures prices
have been jumping both on weather concerns and continued strong demand. The
May contract closed on Wednesday at 92.2 cents, up about 10 cents from a
month ago.
Concern has also focussed on California, which last year produced 2.8m
bales.
An early drought lowered the forecast for this year to 2m bales. Now
continued cool weather has depressed that estimate.
</TEXT>
<PUB>The Financial Times
</PUB>
<PAGE>
London Page 26
</PAGE>
</DOC>
