FT  10 MAY 91 / International Company News: TWA may swap debt for cash
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By NIKKI TAIT
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
TWA, the heavily-borrowed carrier owned by Mr Carl Icahn, said yesterday
that 'it is exploring the possibility of a cash tender offer for its debt'
next week, writes Nikki Tait.
The company declined to be more specific about what debt - some of which is
traded publicly, and some of which is owned by Mr Icahn himself - it might
try to buy, or how the current negotiations with debtholders and lessors
over the possible restructuring of the group's parlous finances were
progressing. Debtholders advisers, however, were sceptical of matters moving
significantly within a week.
There is, however, little doubt that any such offer would be at a very heavy
discount to the face value of the debt. With suggestions circulating that
TWA might offer 13.5 cents on the dollar for some issues, the airline's 12
per cent junior subordinated debentures due in 2001 rose Dollars  3/4 to
Dollars 13 1/4 , while the issue due in 2008 gained Dollars 1 3/8 at Dollars
13 3/8 .
TWA's announcement came shortly after the airline said that it had reached
an 'interim agreement' with the union representing its machinists, under
which TWA promised not to make any principal or interest payments to
debtholders while the two sides negotiate. These labour talks, it claimed,
could extend for 'several months'.
TWA has defaulted on a variety of debt and long-term lease payments this
year.
