FT  10 MAY 91 / International Company News: Monks loses battle for Sears,
Roebuck board seat
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By BARBARA DURR
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
MR ROBERT MONKS, leader of the battle to reform American corporate
governance, has lost his bid for a seat on the board of Sears, Roebuck, the
giant US retailing and financial services company.
A preliminary count from the company's annual meeting yesterday showed that
the management's slate of three candidates had won. Mr Monks vowed to try
again next year.
Mr Edward Brennan, Sears, Roebuck chairman, claimed Mr Monks' concerns 'were
more with corporate America than with Sears'.
'Our opposition to Mr Monks was based upon our belief that our principal
responsibility to shareholders is to improve our financial performance so
that we might enhance the value of their investment, not to use the Sears
boardroom as a forum for Mr Monks' personal agenda,' he said.
Mr Monks efforts, however, reflect serious shareholder discontent. Mr
Brennan faced many shareholder complaints yesterday, ranging from poor
service in stores to disappointing financial performance.
The chairman admitted the 1990 results were 'unacceptable,' but said they
underscored the improved first-quarter performance this year.
He also pledged that 1991 would be a better year overall given that the
company had deeply cut its costs and that the economy was expected to emerge
from recession. Sears, Roebuck's 1990 net income was Dollars 902m, or
Dollars 2.63 per share, down from Dollars 1.5bn, or Dollars 4.30 in 1989.
Cost-cutting helped first-quarter 1991 net income to grow to Dollars 202.7m,
or 59 cents per share, up 91 per cent from Dollars 106.3m, or 31 cents, from
1990.
Highlighting the first-quarter results, however, was only 'trying to put the
best face on things,' according to Mr Lawrence Spitzer, an individual
shareholder. 'Brennan has his back against the wall,' he said.
Mr Brennan, who is not only chairman and chief executive of Sears, Roebuck,
but also chief of its troubled merchandise group, came under fire from Mr
Monks for concentrating so much decision-making power in his own hands.
</TEXT>
