<HEADLINE>
FT  10 MAY 91 / International Company News: US court accepts CNBC bid for
FNN
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By KAREN ZAGOR
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   NEW YORK
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
THE PENULTIMATE battle over Financial News Network (FNN), the business news
media group, ended yesterday when a bankruptcy court judge accepted a bid
from CNBC, the cable television subsidiary of General Electric's NBC unit.
The bid comprised Dollars 145m in cash and Dollars 9.3m in assumed
liabilities.
The decision paves the way to end months of fighting between Dow
Jones/Westinghouse and CNBC over FNN's cable television and business radio
network operations. However, there may still be one more round to fight.
The Dow Jones group, which filed a civil anti-trust suit earlier this week,
is seeking a temporary restraining order in an attempt to prevent the CNBC
acquisition.
Analysts were sceptical about the prospects of the CNBC acquisition being
blocked on anti-trust grounds. Although CNBC operates the only serious
competitor to FNN's 24-hour business channel, the Federal Trade Commission
has already said it would not oppose a CNBC acquisition on anti-trust
grounds.
In February, FNN tentatively accepted a Dollars 90m bid from a joint venture
between Dow Jones and Westinghouse, but it later turned it down in favour of
a Dollars 105m CNBC offer.
The ensuing battle, in which both suitors sweetened their offers several
times, helped push the price to a level which some analysts said was more
than the failed company was worth.
FNN was put on the block in November, and filed for protection from
creditors under Chapter 11 of the federal bankruptcy code earlier this year.
Both sides have a vested interest in acquiring FNN. CNBC was launched less
than two years ago and provides business programmes during the day. The
acquisition is expected to bolster CNBC's subscribers from 18m to more than
30m.
Dow Jones, which owns the Wall Street Journal and the Dow Jones wire
service, has wanted to expand into cable television for some time.
The Dow Jones/Westinghouse partnership had bid Dollars 167.1m for FNN, but
the total cash component of Dollars 135m was less than the CNBC offer.
</TEXT>
