<HEADLINE>
FT  10 MAY 91 / UK Company News: Fuelling partnerships to explore mutual
interests - How BP is oiling the expensive wheels of progress via alliances
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By DEBORAH HARGREAVES
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
AFTER DECADES of growing on its own through takeovers and internal
expansion, British Petroleum is rediscovering the value of co-operative
ventures and alliances.
It will finalise soon, for example, a joint initiative with Norway's Statoil
to market and sell gas in the UK, launching a substantial challenge to
British Gas' dominance of the UK industrial gas market.
The deal, which covers other areas such as oil exploration, is part of a
wider understanding between the two companies. BP has dubbed it a strategic
alliance.
Indeed, it says that the Statoil deal could be followed by other strategic
alliances currently under discussion which could come to fruition later this
year.
This approach revives an idea which has been around since multinational oil
companies received concessions to explore for oil across the world in the
1950s, but which was buried as countries nationalised their oil interests
and the industry turned its eyes towards the mega-takeovers of the 1980s.
Under the constraints of today's chastened financial environment, a link-up
with a like-minded company to explore areas of mutual interest can be a
useful and much cheaper alternative to a hostile takeover bid.
'The mind-set of the 1980s has changed,' says Mr David Simon, BP's chief
operating officer and deputy chairman. 'People are understanding that it is
possible to have a common vision and work through a strategy without
worrying about the issue of control. In an alliance, you are pooling your
abilities to create value rather than worrying about who is stronger.'
For BP, with gearing of close to 40 per cent and a capital budget of Dollars
7bn a year (Pounds 4.1bn at the current exchange rate) just to fund
internally-generated projects, there is little room to contemplate a large
acquisition in any case. Mr Simon insists that the company is not forced
into alliances because it is cash-constrained, but that 'this is a sensible
way of growing the business and creating value for shareholders'.
BP's initiative with Statoil grew out of a personal relationship between Mr
Simon and Mr Harold Norvik, Statoil's chairman, both of which share similar
views on the development of EC energy markets in the run-up to the single
market in 1992 and beyond.
The link on gas between the two companies will give BP access to the largest
gas reserves in Europe to supply burgeoning gas demand in the UK and,
possibly, later export to a more liberated EC gas market.
Gas production and sales currently account for 10 per cent of BP's business,
but the company is putting more resources into its development and could see
its exposure to gas doubling over the next couple of years.
Another chief reason behind the move towards strategic alliances is the need
to share the risk of highly capital-intensive exploration projects which are
often located in politically-sensitive regions of the world. BP and Statoil
are looking to explore jointly for oil and gas in West Africa, offshore
China, Vietnam and the Soviet Union.
Under this arrangement, both companies can share the cost and technological
burden of searching for additional oil reserves outside the Middle East, an
objective which is important to both.
Much of the world's oil reserves are in the hands of state-owned companies.
Many of them are in severe need of capital and technological expertise to
maximise output. This could be provided by the large multinationals in
return for access to the oil. Some oil industry observers are expecting a
return to the partnerships of the 1950s which helped develop the reserves in
the first place.
At the beginning of April, BP signed an agreement with Venezuela's national
oil company, Petroleos de Venezuela, to co-operate in oil exploration and
production in the country. This was the fruit of a 10-year relationship
between the two companies which started as a partnership on technology.
Venezuelan oil is very heavy - which means it contains a lot of sulphur -
making it difficult to transport and to burn in power stations. The two
companies developed a technique of mixing water with the oil by a process
called Orimulsion and formed a joint venture to market it in Europe.
By courting the Venezuelans in this way, BP secured a deal to help develop
its reserves and co-operate on refining.
Similarly, research into new technology is a ripe area for link-ups between
large oil companies since they help defray the heavy costs. Statoil and BP
have also gone down a third route in the alliance and have set up a joint
venture research and development project. This will pool resources on some
aspects of technology development and, since BP has the upper hand on
research, Statoil has paid Dollars 20m for its part of the venture.
In another bid to rationalise costs, BP has joined with Texaco, the US oil
company, in upgrading two refineries in Rotterdam by linking them by
pipeline. The agreement pools up-to-date refining equipment owned by each at
the different sites and allows them to close the older parts of the plant.
Speculation about future alliances for BP have centred around the Far East
where demand for oil is growing at a faster rate than anywhere else in the
world.
The company would certainly like to gain more exposure to the Japanese
market, but it is very difficult to penetrate.
It is not a process that can be rushed, Mr Simon stresses. 'It is a way of
looking at the development of markets and political structures which means
you can do business together,' he says.
</TEXT>
<PUB>The Financial Times
</PUB>
