<HEADLINE>
FT  10 MAY 91 / Shine goes off Polly Peck's fruit machine: Meyna, central to
creditors' cash hopes
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By RICHARD WATERS
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
NESTLED among the palm trees and orange groves along a highway leading to
the Turkish Mediterranean coast, a line of warehouses and factories
stretches for almost 25 miles outside the port of Mersin.
At first sight, the two main factories of the Meyna group do not command
much attention. The outlets for Polly Peck International's Turkish mainland
subsidiary in the fruit and processing trade are lost in a seemingly endless
parade of garish company and bank signs.
Yet they - and other similar plants dotted around Turkey and northern Cyprus
 -are at the heart of any hopes that Polly Peck's 28,000 creditors have of
recovering the hundreds of millions of pounds they have pumped into the
group. There are signs already that creditors will have to wait years for
Meyna and other Near East operations to make a dent in Polly Peck's debts.
And even then, the wait could turn out to be fruitless.
Creditors were told this week that only about Pounds 500m of their Pounds
1.15bn was likely to be repaid. For the rest, they will have to rely on
future profits or asset sales from the Near East.
Meyna has long been thought by analysts and shareholders to be one of the
group's biggest cash generators. For instance, it was believed to have been
the biggest contributor to the Pounds 107m of reported profits from northern
Cyprus and Turkey in 1989, which made up two-thirds of total group profit.
The administrators this week cast serious doubts on the reliability of Polly
Peck's published figures.
Meyna is shown in reports at Polly Peck's head office to have made profits
of TL195bn (Pounds 47m) in the first half of 1990, on turnover of TL578bn.
The administrators warn that the limited access they have had to local
records indicates that these figures 'may be significantly overstated'.
This accords with the impression of Meyna given by former executives, and by
competitors - that of a medium-sized player from one of the Mediterranean's
less active fruit exporting nations. As one prominent Israeli fruit
exporter, who has observed Meyna closely, says of the reported profits: 'You
simply can't make that sort of money from a fruit business that size.'
The Turkish Mediterranean fruit and vegetable market is not large. The
Association of (Turkish) Mediterranean Exporters reported Dollars 110.4m
(Pounds 65m) in exports last year of fresh fruit, vegetables, and citrus
fruits.
Polly Peck's Turkish fruit and vegetable operations were developed after
1985, following substantial investment.
By the end of 1989, Meyna had 58,000 sq m of plant and two ultra-modern
packing stations. The plant could process 20 tons of fruit an hour and
seemed poised to challenge the Spanish and Italian fruit industries.
By 1988, Meyna was exporting 68,000 tons of fruit and vegetables. However,
problems in the overseas marketing arm handling Meyna's output led to
substantial cuts in exports in 1989, with output falling to 23,000 tons. It
is reckoned to be the fifth or sixth largest exporter in Mersin. Meyna then
turned to the domestic market, with products ranging from fruit concentrates
and cooking oils to plastic containers.
It is also possible to trace Meyna's growing involvement in importing
foodstuffs, including rice, sugar and coffee.
From what is known of these piecemeal businesses, it is hard to construct a
picture of a vibrant business generating substantial sums of cash.
So where will the profits come from to repay Polly Peck's creditors? Not
from Sunzest Trading, the group's original Turkish Cypriot fruit operation.
This is substantially smaller than Meyna.
Nor, on the face of it, from Unipac, the group's cardboard box factory in
northern Cyprus. Unaudited figures for the first six months of 1990 show it
made Pounds 14m profit - well down on the Pounds 1m-a-week profit it was
said to have been making at one stage. Even the Pounds 14m is in doubt. The
administrators have not gained access to the business, due to an injunction
taken out by directors of Unipac. But the administrators say of the
unaudited profits: 'The information available indicates the figures may be
overstated.'
If there is a big question mark over the profit-generating capacity of the
Near East operations, then what chance is there of selling assets to pay
back some of the Pounds 959m invested in northern Cyprus and Turkey by other
Polly Peck group companies?
On the evidence obtained so far, not good. The group was renowned for its
lavish investments in new processing plants. It is uncertain whether these
can be sold at anything like their original cost.
In addition, hundreds of millions of pounds of Polly Peck money has been
ploughed into holiday developments (although the administrators have not
been able to verify Pounds 230m said to have been invested last summer).
These have little resale value as incomplete developments. But it will take
years for these investments to show a return.
Despite this, Mr Michael Jordan, one of the three administrators of Polly
Peck, said yesterday that creditors had little option but to place their
faith in the Near East, and Polly Peck's chairman. For example, it is
through Mr Asil Nadir, the Turkish Cypriot chairman and chief executive,
that the administrators are trying to obtain legal title to assets bought
with Polly Peck money, but not held in the name of group companies.
Any legal attempt to gain control of assets, in a region not recognised by
the UK, would take years and could yield nothing, said Mr Jordan. His blunt
warning: 'If the creditors don't go along with our proposals and prefer to
pull the plug (on Polly Peck), then they may as well say goodbye to northern
Cyprus.'
Observer, Page 14
</TEXT>
