<HEADLINE>
FT  10 MAY 91 / Granada chief may quit as price of Pounds 150m cash call
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By RAYMOND SNODDY
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
GRANADA, the leisure and television group, is expected to announce today a
Pounds 150m rights issue and the departure of its chief executive, Mr Derek
Lewis.
The announcement will follow weeks of pressure and speculation that
Granada's financial adviser, S. G. Warburg, was seeking Mr Lewis's
resignation as the price of going ahead with a rights issue designed to
reduce the company's debt.
Several non-executive directors and a range of institutional shareholders
believed top-level management changes were needed following difficult
diversifications into electrical retailing and business services, and
growing levels of borrowing.
Those who were critical included Mr Peter Davis, chairman and chief
executive of Reed International, who is expected to resign from the Granada
board soon after the rights issue has been completed.
Although Mr Lewis will announce his intention to leave, he is expected to
stay until a successor is appointed.
Granada's new financial package is likely to include a dividend cut.
Despite accepting Warburg's arguments that Mr Lewis must go, there is no
sign that Granada plans significant changes in strategy.
Support will continue for the two high-risk ventures that have increased
pressure on Granada's balance sheet - the Pounds 232.4m commitment to
British Sky Broadcasting, the satellite television venture, and the Pounds
200m investment in business services which has only just moved into modest
profit.
Mr Lewis has admitted that Granada was slow to integrate its computer
servicing acquisitions into the main business, which delayed profitability.
Questions are likely to be raised about the apparent decision to sacrifice
Mr Lewis for policies that had the support of the board and are likely to
continue.
The uncertainty comes at a particularly sensitive time. By noon next
Wednesday, Granada Television has to submit its bid for a new 10-year
commercial broadcasting licence.
The Independent Television Commission has not ruled out takeovers of bidders
while franchise bids are being considered. However, once the franchises are
awarded there is a moratorium on takeovers until 1994.
In December Granada announced a 26 per cent drop in pre-tax profits to
Pounds 121m.
