<HEADLINE>
FT  10 MAY 91 / Tories cool on idea of June election
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By PHILIP STEPHENS, Political Editor
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
SENIOR Conservatives yester-day sought to damp speculation that Mr John
Major is considering a June general election as election fever gripped the
three main parties.
Close colleagues of the prime minister insisted that in 10 Downing Street
the idea of a snap election had gone 'colder than cold' after last week's
local election losses. Barring a 'spectacular' - and unexpected -
Conservative majority in next week's Monmouth by-election, Mr Major had his
sights set firmly on the autumn.
But the Labour party indicated that it would attempt to harry the
Conservatives into an early poll. Senior figures in the shadow cabinet
believe that next month would offer the strongest chance of a Labour
victory.
Mr Major is expected today to tell Scottish Tories of his plans for a white
paper this summer on a 'citizens charter' to promote better public services.
Proposals being considered include performance related pay for public sector
workers and compensation to consumers for bad services.
The refusal of several ministers to close publicly the option of a June
election left an impression that Mr Major is sufficiently anxious to secure
his own mandate to believe that he might win next month.
Ministers also stepped up their attacks on Labour's tax and spending
policies. Following a lead set by Mr Major in the House of Commons, they
charged that Mr Neil Kinnock's plan to abolish the ceiling on national
insurance contributions would hit millions of people in the south of England
whose incomes were barely above the average for the region. A Gallup opinion
poll in today's Daily Telegraph puts the Tories just half a percentage point
ahead of Labour.
Speaking in the Monmouth by-election campaign, Mr John Cope, the deputy
Conservative party chairman, refused to rule out the possibility of a June
poll. At the Scottish Conservative conference in Perth, Mr Michael
Heseltine, environment secretary, offered similarly opaque replies to
questions from journalists.
At one stage Mr Heseltine appeared to increase speculation with a series of
confident predictions of an imminent turnaround in the economy. He cited
this week's fall in mortgage rates and the expected sharp fall in inflation
due to be announced next week as a secure basis for a fourth Conservative
election victory.
Senior ministers are emphasising in private that the party's analysis of the
local election results does not provide a secure enough foundation for an
early election.
The interpretation offered to cabinet colleagues yesterday by Mr Chris
Patten, the party chairman, was that in spite of the loss of more than 900
seats, if a general election had been held last week the Conservatives would
have secured a majority of 20 at Westminster. But Mr Patten is believed to
consider that such a figure is well within the margin of error and to have
advised Mr Major to wait until the autumn.
At the Scottish conference today, the prime minister will develop further
the Conservatives' strategy for attacking Labour. But he may also use his
closing address to take some of the steam out of the speculation on June.
Citizens' charter, Page 10
Taxing question, Page 15
