<DATE>910510
</DATE>
<HEADLINE>
FT  10 MAY 91 / The Lex Column: EC insurance
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
UK insurers should sit up. The buzz from Brussels is that the long dormant
insurance accounts directive is poised for adoption by the EC council of
ministers next month. This seemingly obscure bit of legislation will
harmonise requirements for technical reserves and set common rules for
valuing assets and liabilities.
Not for the first time in EC matters the British are staging a belated
rearguard fight. The main grouse is that unrealised investment gains on
non-life business will not be allowed through the profit and loss account.
The Pru and Eagle Star do this at the moment, for example, though smoothed
over a longish period.
Another clause going down badly in London is a demand for detailed segment
information. Companies say they are happy to provide this to national
authorities but not to their competitors.
Last-minute lobbying on these points may or may not succeed. More important
is the fact that the Germans look like winning their battle to avoid any
mention of the market value of assets. This issue gets close to the heart of
the problem - different tax treatment - which the EC is signally failing to
tackle. German companies have no wish to draw attention to their
much-criticised privileges, notably the conservative reserving which enables
the likes of Allianz and Munich Re to understate their profits.
It is the financial firepower they have built up on the strength of this
which spells trouble for the UK insurers after 1992.
</TEXT>
<PUB>The Financial Times
</PUB>
<PAGE>
London Page 16
</PAGE>
