<HEADLINE>
FT  10 MAY 91 / Observer: Under cover
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
What lesson might be drawn from linking a Pounds 750,000 gift to Cambridge
University by Mitsui Marine and Fire Insurance yesterday, with Japanese
banks' worldwide expansion in the early 1980s?
The answer is that the international financial markets may soon be
undergoing the same sort of onslaught from hitherto domestically centred
Japanese insurance giants.
Mitsui's gift is a complete set of microfilmed publications of the 1868-1912
Meiji period, giving the university the biggest collection of Meiji papers
in Europe. But why Mitsui's generosity?
Takeru Ishikawa, its chairman, concedes that, while the gift marks his
company's change of name from Taisho Marine and Fire, that fact alone
conceals the intention behind the name-change. It's a marketing move to
heighten the company's identity, not least abroad where it is seeking to
broaden its business beyond its existing base in overseas-operating Japanese
companies.
Will more of its domestic counterparts follow Mitsui into the world arena?
Surely, says Ishikawa, although it doesn't necessarily mean renewed downward
pressure on already depressed international insurance premium rates. That
will depend, for instance, on whether a continued withdrawal of US insurers
helps to stabilise premiums.
Even so, considering what the Japanese banks did to banking margins when
they set out building market share, it's hard to be optimistic.
</TEXT>
