<DOCNO>FT911-626</DOCNO>
<PROFILE>_AN-BEJAXAFDFT</PROFILE>
<DATE>910510
</DATE>
<HEADLINE>
FT  10 MAY 91 / Fast-track at the end of the line: A vital US congressional
vote which could determine the fate of the Uruguay Round of trade talks
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By PETER MONTAGNON and NANCY DUNNE
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Soon - at the latest by the end of the month and probably sooner - the army
of trade negotiators who have been struggling to complete the Uruguay Round
of multilateral trade negotiations in Geneva will know whether their
four-and-a-half-year effort has been a total waste of time.
The US Congress is gearing up to vote on a two-year extension of the
administration's 'fast-track' authority to negotiate trade agreements.
Without that authority the administration's hands would be effectively tied,
and there would be no hope of completing the Uruguay Round, which has been
limping along since the Brussels trade ministerial meeting in December broke
up in deadlock.
As the deadline draws near amid some of the most ferocious lobbying Capitol
Hill has ever seen, most political pundits in Washington believe the
extension will be narrowly granted. But it will be far from a categoric
victory for supporters of free multilateral trade and an uncertain reprieve
for the most ambitious attempt to reform the world trading system since the
General Agreement on Tariffs and Trade (Gatt) was founded in 1947.
Under the fast-track rule, Congress agrees to refrain from amending any
trade agreements struck by the administration when implementing legislation
is brought to Capitol Hill. Instead of picking holes in the agreement and
discarding clauses that it does not like, it is committed simply to voting
the whole package in or out on the basis of a single vote.
It is thus a way of making sure that concessions granted by the US in trade
talks actually stick. Without the fast-track authority, the 100 or so other
countries who are involved in the Uruguay Round would not regard Washington
as a reliable negotiating partner and would refuse to bargain. So important
is the authority to Mrs Carla Hills, US trade representative, that she has
abstained from all foreign travel until the congressional vote is through.
Obsessed though Uruguay Round negotiators have become with the fast-track,
the debate in Washington has, however, had little to do with the Gatt.
Instead the focus has been almost exclusively on parallel plans for the US
to negotiate a free trade pact with Mexico for which the administration says
fast-track authority is also vital. Even in this context, the discussion in
Congress has had less to do with trade per se than with a panoply of other
issues such as jobs, the environment and investment.
With hindsight, it is not surprising that Mexico has assumed the importance
that it has. Unless their livelihood is in textiles or farming, most
Americans have only a vague idea of what the Gatt and the Uruguay Round are
all about, but they are all too acutely aware of what the proposed deal with
Mexico could mean.
It has sparked worries about the diversion of investment to plants south of
the border where labour costs are a seventh of those in the US, about
workers' rights there, and about environmental protection since Mexico's
laws are laxer than those of the US. Some say the AFL-CIO trade union
federation has exploited these worries to try to make the fast-track vote a
test of attitudes to organised labour. Congressmen are worried that if they
vote for extension, they may lose union financial support.
Overlaying the debate are the traditional concerns of domestic US politics -
the worry of northern smoke-stack states that they may lose their economic
clout, and the desire of Congress to assert itself over President George
Bush, with whom the Mexican agreement is closely identified.
Mr Niel Ritchie of the Institute for Agriculture and Trade Policy, a leading
player of the lobby opposing fast-track, wants to convince Democrats that it
is smart politics to 'stop playing footsie with Bush' and take control over
the negotiating process. The Mexican pact is unpopular because 'people in
the US don't want the government doing deals under the cloak of darkness.
For solutions to be politically workable they have to be made by the people
they affect'.
It is on issues such as these, rather than the actual state of play in the
Geneva negotiations, that the fast-track vote, and thus the immediate fate
of the Uruguay Round now depends. There are few clues offered by the debate
so far to US attitudes towards the Gatt itself.
Only since May 1, when the administration released an action plan containing
concessions on environmental and job issues, has the tide begun to swing in
the administration's favour.
'We've stopped the momentum of opposition and rolled it back. We're moving
ahead, but we're not yet winning,' says Mr Harry Freeman of the MTN
Coalition, a big business group which supports both the Uruguay Round and
the Mexican plan.
Administration officials believe the Senate would agree to an extension of
fast-track, but the vote is much closer in the House of Representatives -
and either can reject the extension request by a simple majority. Both Mr
Dan Rostenkowski, chairman of the House ways and means committee, and Mr
Lloyd Bentsen, chairman of the Senate finance committee, whose support is
vital, are in favour of extension. Mr Richard Gephardt, the House Democratic
majority leader and a supporter of unilateralist trade policy, yesterday
gave conditional support to the fast-track request, but warned 'if the
administration . . . trades away American jobs or tolerates pollution or
abuse of workers, we can and we will amend (the final agreement) or reject
it'.
Adding to the complexity are compromise proposals in both houses, which
would split the fast-track vote and allow the Uruguay Round to go ahead but
permit amendments on the Mexican agreement in a few important areas:
environment, rules of origin, health and safety standards, and dispute
settlement. The opponents of the Gatt - mostly farm groups and textile
interests - are trying to prevent a split because they know the Mexico pact
is more controversial.
The compromise, proposed by Senator Donald Riegle and Congressman Sander
Levin, both from Michigan, has appeal to the undecided. It will be difficult
to get through the Senate, but stands more chance in the House.
Mr Levin argues that the May 1 action plan is 'responsive but inadequate'.
He says: 'With Gatt you have 100-plus nations and you don't have integration
of economies. Here you have integration and negotiation with one nation so
you have a much higher objective and some added issues and risks. Because of
the disparities in the economies of Mexico and the US, there are major unmet
concerns ly.
'If they fail, we are left with weighing steel and autos with tomatoes. I
don't want to be put in that position. Congress needs a significant role
where you have significant problems. Being consulted is not enough.'
The decision by the AFL-CIO to focus the debate on Mexico has muddied the
waters by providing cover for congressmen whose instinct may be
protectionist but who are reluctant to speak out against free trade. The
AFL-CIO's concern, though, is not primarily with the Gatt.
Even if it loses the fast-track debate, labour will have won a victory of
sorts, says Mr Mark Anderson, AFL-CIO international economist, because the
terms of the debate have changed. Environment, labour rights, wage rate
disparities and job losses have been put on the agenda.
'Before these issues were being studiously ignored and, indeed, rejected by
the Bush administration. Now the issue is whether or not they will be
addressed in a useful fashion. Instead of spouting simplistic free-trade or
protectionist rhetoric, the coalition made trade issues as complicated as
they really are in real life.'
None the less, many in the pro-Gatt lobby believe the Uruguay Round has
gained by default, through being largely left out of the debate. While
politicians can satisfy one side of their constituency by admitting to
doubts over Mexico, they can refrain from offending their liberal supporters
by indicating support in principle for the Gatt. 'Compared with the Mexican
agreement, the Uruguay Round has come up smelling like a rose,' says Mr
Jeffrey Schott of the Washington-based Institute for International
Economics.
The danger, if a fast-track extension is agreed, is that this sentiment will
lead to over-confidence in Geneva about what sort of Uruguay Round agreement
would pass through Congress at the end of the day. 'The Uruguay Round is
not, at this time at least, very controversial,' says Mr Hal Malmgren, a US
trade consultant.
'The opposing forces who are interested in not having too much trade
liberalisation seem to have decided to narrow the focus to just Mexico. That
does not, however, mean that, later, an agreement in the Uruguay Round will
meet an enthusiastic reception.'
Pressure is growing in Geneva for the Round to be completed before the end
of the year so that the implementing legislation can be laid before Congress
before the 1992 presidential election campaign gets under way. With Europe
still reluctant to offer substantial new concessions on farm reform, some
trade diplomats believe that the heat will be turned on the US in an effort
to persuade it to scale down its ambitions in this sector.
This school of thought is encouraged by hints that the new US secretary of
agriculture, Mr Ed Madigan, is more conciliatory than his predecessor, Mr
Clayton Yeutter, towards Brussels on farm reform. Yet trade insiders in
Washington warn that the overall package will still have to contain a
critical mass of benefits for Congress to pass the deal. Almost certainly
this will have to include a strong package of farm reforms, not least
because, without that, other countries, notably farm exporting nations in
Latin America, will decline to deliver vital concessions on liberalising
trade in services.
Even while the fast-track debate has been raging, however, the forces for
unilateralism in US trade policy have been gathering pace. Car makers, led
by Mr Lee Iacocca of Chrysler, have sought protection against Japanese
competition, The US semiconductor industry has complained about Japan
withholding access to new technology, the aerospace sector has been lobbying
for an intensification of the dispute over Airbus subsidies, and Mrs Hills
has lodged new complaints against Japan on construction and against China on
intellectual property.
It is against this backdrop that any Uruguay Round agreement will be viewed.
One frequently-voiced argument in Washington is that the bilateral issues
which divide the US are largely outside the scope of the Gatt, but the
Uruguay Round is intended to bring some of them, such as services and
intellectual property, into its fold, and thereby restrain the US
determination to go-it-alone in sorting out its commercial problems.
According to Mr Bill Archey, head of trade policy at the US Chamber of
Commerce, the fast-track debate underlines the way in which Congress is
determined to take a strong role in trade matters. Having passed the 1988
Trade Act, US politicians turned their attention to other matters and gave
Mrs Hills very much a free hand. Now their are anxious once again to rein in
the administration.
This is not died-in-the-wool protectionism, Washington trade experts say,
but more a concern about competitiveness and ensuring that overseas markets
are opened up. In this context the US is coming to recognise that it is no
longer strong enough to hold the multilateral trading system together by
making the most concessions. There must be an offsetting gain for everything
it gives away.
So Congress is still likely to scrutinise any final Uruguay Round agreement
more closely than ever before and the administration will not be able to
push through concessions 'unless,' as Mr Archey says, 'they beget something
tangible for business.' That still looks like being the subject of another
contentious debate.
</TEXT>
<PUB>The Financial Times
</PUB>
