<HEADLINE>
FT  10 MAY 91 / The Property Market: A contrast in measurement
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By VANESSA HOULDER
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
AT THE risk of confirming Mark Twain's jibe about lies, damn lies and
statistics, Hillier Parker, the chartered surveyor, has come up with some
figures which suggest that property did not under-perform equities during
the 1980s, after all, writes Vanessa Houlder.
The market deluded itself, it says, by contrasting equities, which use
geared capital, with property that has no gearing. 'One is therefore
comparing apples with oranges,' it says
'We believe that the perceived problem of under-performance of property only
really arises from the different implicit financial structuring of the total
return indices for property and equities,' says Mr Alan Patterson, author of
the report.
To make his point, he adjusted the performance of a property index to
include a hypothetical debt component. The result is that the returns
achieved by property over a 10-year period are almost identical to those of
equities. (If, however, the chart had been brought up to date, equities
would be well in the lead).
Hillier Parker has chosen a level of gearing well above that of equities for
this exercise, on the grounds that each form of investment is geared to its
appropriate level. The property gearing ranged between 40 per cent and 45
per cent, so the investment income should service the current income
payments, compared with equities' gearing of between 30 and 40 per cent.
Hillier Parker claims that this method is no more an artificial contrivance
than constructing an index assuming 100 per cent equity capital. The
difference, however, is that institutions show no inclination to gear up
their property holdings. So it seems that the traditional way of comparing
equities and gilts has more validity where they are concerned.
Investors could interpret the results as making a case for introducing
gearing to a property portfolio. The disadvantage is that this destroys a
key traditional virtue of property, which is its lower volatility compared
with equities. A more surprising conclusion is that the counter-cylical
nature of property and equities actually increases when the property is
geared.
</TEXT>
<PUB>The Financial Times
</PUB>
