<HEADLINE>
FT  10 MAY 91 / The Property Market: Valuation values come in for scrutiny
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By VANESSA HOULDER
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
A SURVEYOR, it seems, is someone who knows the price of everything and the
value of nothing. As property companies see their balance sheets crumble,
they are arguing that the valuers' reliance on market evidence ignores the
true worth of their portfolios.
Critics say the pitifully low turnover levels this year consist largely of
forced sales and are thus a misleading guide to the remainder of the market.
'In the past, valuers may have overvalued,' says Sir Nigel Mobbs, of Slough
Estates, 'and the pendulum has now swung rather too far the other way.'
Disillusioned investors want changes to the philosophy underpinning
valuations.
Donald Gordon, chairman of Capital &amp; Counties, is sceptical about the
current 'open market' basis of valuation. 'There is no justification for
using, as the prime measure of performance, a system which produces such
volatility as we have seen in recent years in the values ascribed to
long-term property investments - values based essentially on short-term
perceptions and interpretations of prevailing economic mood, sentiment and
the interest rate cycles at random balance sheet dates,' he says.
Instead, he would like investment property to be assessed in terms of
expected earnings, discounted using a 'pragmatic' rate of return related to
a more stable weighted average.
His complaint has stirred controversy and exposed Capital &amp; Counties to the
criticism that, following a 13 per cent fall in its investment portfolio in
1990, it is simply making excuses for a poor year.
Even those who sympathise with CapCo's argument are shy of advocating a
switch away from a market-based valuation system in precisely the year when
the property market has collapsed. 'The property business didn't scream when
values were high,' says Mr John Parry, managing director of Hammerson. 'I
have felt for some years that it should be changed but this is not the time
for it to be changed. It should be changed when times are good.'
Not all advocates of change, however, risk the accusation that they want to
flatter their own balance sheets. Mr Nick French, a lecturer in land
management at Reading University, is an enthusiastic proponent of property
valuation using discounted cash flow methods.
Instead of relying uncritically on market evidence, he believes valuers
should be asking: 'Is it realistic? Shouldn't we be looking at other
scenarios?' he says.
Mr French also argues that the adoption of discounted cash flow techniques
would make it easier to compare the performance of property with those of
equities and gilts. As a result, it might help property win a larger share
of institutional money.
Argument about valuation principles is hardly novel. Discounted cash flow
methods were the norm before 1960 when the ravages of inflation and the
uncertainties of rent reviews forced a change.
There was debate after the collapse of the property market in 1973, which
was the catalyst for serious criticism of valuations. Indeed, bankers' blind
faith in flawed valuations was held partly to blame for the collapse in the
property and secondary banking sectors.
At that time too, property companies balked at the open market method of
valuation. British Land's 1975-6 accounts valued some of its long-term
investment property on its 'current actual and estimated income' because
'the valuers stated that they were unable to assess open market value in
view of the unlikelihood that the property could be sold at a price
reflecting true worth.'
This type of argument provokes unease from those who think the market,
however quirky and volatile, is the only true judge of value. 'At the end of
the day, the value of the property is what someone will pay for it. You can
not get away from that,' says Andrew Cherry, who is chairman of the Royal
Institution of Chartered Surveyors assets valuation standards committee.
Indeed, the argument that prices in the property market are irrationally low
risks the accusation of wishful thinking. When erosion of planning controls
has led to unprecedented oversupply, it may be suspect to assume that yields
will remain inside their traditional range. At times like this, judging the
'right' level of yields is so difficult, the market may be the best arbiter.
Defenders of the surveying profession, however, reckon they could - with
greater research - become credible judges of future rental values.
The criticism about valuation methods is just one several strains facing
valuers. The subjective nature of their profession came under intense
scrutiny last November, when a takeover battle revealed that one firm of
valuers believed Scott's Restaurants was worth nearly three times as much as
did a rival firm.
Another sign of pressure is the heavy toll taken on surveyors' professional
indemnity policies, because of alleged over-valuation of property in the
late 1980s bull market.
Nonetheless, the problems should not be exaggerated. The accuracy of
valuations was found to be remarkably high in 1989 when the Investment
Property Databank tested 2,500 valuations against the sale prices they later
achieved.
Admittedly, the test is likely to be less reassuring when it is repeated
this summer. There is plenty of anecdotal evidence that valuers have found
it hard to keep pace with the ferocity of the downturn in the market and the
virtual evaporation of turnover. However, in the exceptionally volatile
market that has exposed these weaknesses, it is unclear whether an
alternative approach to valuations would be much less controversial.
 --------------------------------------------------------------------
