<HEADLINE>
FT  10 MAY 91 / Parliament and Politics: Lang moves toward a more pragmatic
party - Scottish Conservatives' Conference
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JAMES BUXTON and PHILIP STEPHENS
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
MR IAN LANG, the Scottish secretary, yesterday attempted to shift the
Scottish Conservative party from its past emphasis on ideology towards a
more practical emphasis on meeting ordinary people's needs.
Mr Lang, a close associate of Mr John Major, the prime minister, told
Scottish Tories at their annual conference in Perth that 'perhaps too often
in the past we have expressed our policies in abstract or ideological terms
when we should have been relating them more clearly to every day issues.'
Echoing Mr Major, he spoke of citizens' rights in the areas of housing,
education, health and the environment.
The party, he said, had its ideals such as belief in the free market, sound
money and a property-owning democracy.
'But we are also the party that cares about quality and excellence and
opportunity. We are the common sense party, the party of good government.'
However the Tories had to demonstrate its care and common sense. 'We must do
more to explain our policies - to consult, to listen, to respond to people's
anxieties.'
Referring to the marked revival in Tory support in Scotland since Mr Major
succeeded Mrs Margaret Thatcher, he said that in the past few months there
had been a 'new buoyancy and vitality and enthusiasm amongst our supporters'
in Scotland.
Mr Major will use his closing address to the Perth conference tonight to
emphasise that a Conservative government under his leadership will satisfy
Scottish aspirations to strengthen their sense of national identity.
Environment secretary Mr Michael Heseltine won a standing ovation from the
conference yesterday, after a wide-ranging speech in which he claimed that
the Tories had proved themselves the only party which could effectively
safeguard the environment.
The enthusiastic if less than warm reception from the conference came after
his prediction that the government was firmly on course for a fourth
election victory.
</TEXT>
