<HEADLINE>
FT  10 MAY 91 / Charities watchdog tells Oxfam to keep out of politics
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By NEIL BUCKLEY
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
TRUSTEES of the charity Oxfam were told yesterday to stop mixing political
campaigning with charity work. They were warned that they may in future have
to reimburse funds which are wrongly used for political purposes.
A report by the Charity Commission, after a year-long inquiry prompted by
concerns over an Oxfam campaign about South Africa, concluded that the
trustees had occasionally exceeded the charity's objectives and had stepped
outside the law restricting charities from undertaking political activities.
Mr David Forrest, secretary of the commission, said in a letter to Mrs Mary
Cherry, chairman of Oxfam's trustees: 'The commissioners require the
trustees to accept that some of their current campaigning work is political
and not charitable. The unacceptable political activities of the charity
must cease.'
The commissioners said they had considered asking the trustees to reimburse
money that had been wrongly used for political purposes, but decided the
trustees had acted in good faith. They warned that they would not hesitate
to seek reimbursement in future.
'The trustees do not appear to differentiate between stating a possible
solution to a problem in reasoned fashion and campaigning to have that
solution adopted,' Mr Forrest said.
He said the commissioners could not accept Oxfam's arguments that its
political activities used up only a small part of its resources.
Mrs Cherry said the report would have serious implications for all UK-based
charities whose work involved an element of political campaigning. Oxfam was
committed to working within the law, Mrs Cherry added.
However, she said: 'Our primary object of relieving distress and suffering
cannot be achieved without advocacy on behalf of the people we are trying to
help'.
The Charity Commissioners first received complaints in December 1989 and
January 1990 about an Oxfam campaign on the Khmer Rouge and Cambodia.
</TEXT>
<PUB>The Financial Times
</PUB>
