<HEADLINE>
FT  10 MAY 91 / Retail margins on food higher than in Germany
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JOHN THORNHILL
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
QUESTIONS about the structure of the UK grocery industry will be raised by a
study showing that a sample basket of supermarket groceries costs 12 per
cent more before tax in the UK than in Germany.
According to a report by KPMG Management Consulting, the German basket of
goods was 5 per cent cheaper than a comparable range of UK products even
after the standard rate of food tax had been added. There is no equivalent
food tax in the UK.
Mr Hew Dalrymple, head of KPMG's food and drink strategy group, said the
findings destroyed the myth that UK food costs were among the lowest in
Europe and suggested that discount food retailers might have considerable
potential to expand in the UK.
The comparative basket contained 11 products ranging from staple foods such
as flour, white bread, butter, cheese and bacon to more exotic fare such as
frozen cheese-and-tomato pizza. The UK supermarket basket cost Pounds 26.36;
the German equivalent Pounds 23.53 before tax. The cost of the UK basket was
split between the manufacturers' selling price of Pounds 19.17 and the
retailer's margin of Pounds 7.19. The comparable split in Germany was Pounds
18.96 and Pounds 4.57.
The survey, which also covered Denmark and Sweden, found that prices varied
widely among products depending on the efficiency of local manufacturing and
patterns of consumption. Prices of bacon and salami were substantially lower
in Germany and Denmark because of the efficiency of local production. Frozen
pizzas and chips were cheaper in the UK and Sweden because of high
consumption.
Mr Dalrymple said that price competition in the UK market would increase
over the next three to five years as the big multiples completed their
expansion programmes.
'Once the market has fully grown you will only be able to grow further by
capturing other people's market shares, leading to more competition which
will be good for the consumer,' he said. 'In Germany there is a thriving
discount sector, and that clearly puts pressure on the multiples in terms of
their mark-up.' Mr Dalrymple said the study showed UK corner shops gave good
value compared with their German counterparts.
The same basket of goods cost Pounds 29.31 at an independent grocer in the
UK compared with Pounds 29.87 before tax in Germany.
Report from Food and Drink Strategy Group, KPMG Management Consulting, 8
Salisbury Sq, London EC4Y 8BB.
</TEXT>
