FT  10 MAY 91 / Developer is accused over damage to listed building
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By PAUL CHEESERIGHT, Midlands Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
NOTTINGHAM City Council has accused Grosvenor Square Properties, the
development subsidiary of AB Ports, of unauthorised alteration and
demolition work at a listed building in the city centre.
Nottingham Magistrates' Court has sent the case to the Crown Court.
Council lawyers are considering a second action to require Grosvenor Square
Properties to reinstate the parts of the building it is alleged to have
demolished.
The action is being taken under sections seven, eight and nine of the
Planning (Listed Buildings and Conservation Areas) Act 1990. It is alleged
demolition and alteration were carried out in the building 'in a manner
which affects its character as a building of special or historical
interest'.
The case concerns a scheme to turn an old department store into small shop
units. One frontage of the old store consists of three 18th century
cottages.
The dispute illustrates the more stringent attitude of local authorities to
conservation issues. Save Britain's Heritage, a pressure group concerned
with protecting historic buildings, said: 'Years ago councils were wary of
doing anything. Now they realise they can take tough measures.'
