<HEADLINE>
FT  10 MAY 91 / UK News (Employment): Civil Service move is opposed
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By MICHAEL SMITH
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
CIVIL SERVICE unions believe their members could suffer financially
following a decision by the government to end service-wide standards on
staff appraisals.
They fear the initiative, one of three planned by the Treasury as part of a
loosening of controls over personnel matters, will lead to fewer civil
servants being given performance-pay rises.
Ms Jenny Thurston, deputy general secretary of the IPMS civil service union,
yesterday described the initiatives as an attack on the employment rights of
more than 500,000 civil servants.
The Treasury wants to allow departments more freedom in appraising staff,
choosing people for redundancies and deciding on promotion procedures. It is
withdrawing existing instructions on these issues and replacing them with
less prescriptive guidance.
The IPMS is the most vociferous of the unions in its opposition to the
changes, although others are also concerned of their effect on members.
Ms Thurston said the changes would open the way to a plethora of different
standards and practices, especially among smaller departments and agencies.
The loosening of rules on staff appraisals worries unions because the
appraisals are used in determining pay and promotion.
Ms Thurston said loosening controls would make it easier for departments to
ensure that performance pay standards were much tougher and more difficult
to attain.
Mr John Ellis, general secretary of the CPSA, the largest Civil Service
union, said he believed there was pressure to reduce the number of civil
servants winning performance pay awards. Withdrawal of guidance on selecting
job losses could presage an end to the 'last-in-first-out' principle.
</TEXT>
