FT  10 MAY 91 / Stalemate on venue for Ulster talks
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By RALPH ATKINS
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
TALKS on Northern Ireland's future were yesterday postponed until Monday as
the province's main political parties failed yet again to reach agreement on
the venue for entry by the government of the Irish Republic into the
negotiations, writes Ralph Atkins.
Mr Peter Brooke, Northern Ireland secretary, expressed frustration after the
third successive day of bilateral meetings with unionist and nationalist
politicians and called on the participants to 'reflect on their positions
over the weekend'.
Mr Gerry Collins, Irish foreign minister, is to meet Mr Brooke in London
today to discuss the stalemate.
The continuing intransigence on a logistical detail has intensified the
gloom surrounding the talks process, which began two weeks ago.
The first 'round table', or plenary, discussions had been due to take place
on Tuesday. But discussions remain at the 'talks-about-talks' stage.
Mr Brooke's sense of disappointment was shared by participants at the talks,
but it appears little headway has been made in resolving differences between
the parties.
As he left the Stormont parliament buildings in Belfast, Mr Brooke said that
if agreement could not be reached 'then I think we would have to pause', but
he appeared confident that the 'loose ends' would be tidied up.
He added: 'I retain confidence that, because of the purposefulness with
which people have been discussing what they want to talk about when we sit
down in plenary, that we will find a way through.'
Unionists want the talks involving Dublin to be held in London. The
nationalist Social Democratic and Labour Party and the Irish government
would prefer a venue in Ireland. Continental European locations appear to
have been ruled out for logistical reasons.
Asked if he had underestimated the symbolism of the venue, Mr Brooke
replied: 'It may have been that I misread the situation as involving
slightly more flexibility than there was.'
Observer, Page 14
