<HEADLINE>
FT  10 MAY 91 / Institute of Economic Affairs Conference on Regulation: BT
network charges backed by Oftel
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By CHARLES LEADBEATER
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Sir Bryan Carsberg, director-general of Oftel, the telecommunications
industry regulatory authority, is unlikely to yield to complaints from
potential new entrants into the industry that British Telecom being allowed
to charge too much for enabling them to interconnect with its network.
The issue of the price it will cost new competitors to inerconnect with BT's
network is at the heart of the government's plans to open the
telecommunications market to greater competition.
Without access to BT's network to complement their own networks, new
competitors will not be able to provide a comprehensive service. BT has said
competitors should pay for interconnection to help the company cover the
cost of installing and maintaining its network.
Sir Bryan told an Institute of Economic Affairs conference on the future of
regulation that he had received a large number of submissions on the issue.
Many complained that the prices charged by BT would deter competitors from
entering the market. Sir Bryan indicated that he would not compromise on the
principle of charging for interconnection.
Those objecting to the charge would have to show that it was fair for BT to
carry the financial burden of the network while others did not, he said.
He pointed out that Mercury Communications, the Cable &amp; Wireless subsidiary,
already paid an interconnection charge, while cable television companies
planning to operate local telecommunications services would be able to
charge for interconnection with their local networks.
Sir Bryan said that none of the details of the interconnection arrangements
had been set in concrete.
He would carefully study detailed suggestions over the next few weeks.
</TEXT>
<PUB>The Financial Times
</PUB>
<PAGE>
London Page 8
</PAGE>
