<TEXT>
THE prospect for continued negotiations in the Uruguay Round yesterday
looked brighter after Congressman Richard Gephardt, the US House majority
leader, said he would support President George Bush's request for
'fast-track' negotiating authority.
The congressman's support was considered crucial in the administration's
embattled effort to get a two-year extension of the 'fast-track' authority,
which allows it to negotiate trade treaties the Congress cannot amend.
