<HEADLINE>
FT  10 MAY 91 / US plans controls for foreign banks
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By PETER RIDDELL, US Editor
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   WASHINGTON
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
THE US Federal Reserve and federal regulators would have new wide-ranging
controls over the entry and operations of foreign banks, under legislation
prepared in response to the scandals involving Banca Nationale del Lavoro's
Atlanta branch and Bank of Credit and Commerce International's American
operations.
The bill, drafted by the Fed's governors and introduced yesterday by leaders
of the Senate banking committee, would allow the Fed to screen the entry of
foreign banks into the US, to examine all foreign bank operations, to revoke
a foreign bank's licence to operate a US branch and prevent hidden ownership
interests by requiring the reporting of loans secured by the stock of a US
bank.
At present, foreign banks can choose state supervisors as the primary
regulators of their US branches. Supervisory weaknesses have allowed a few
banks to use the absence of federal oversight to engage in illegal
activities. BCCI secretly took ownership interests in US banks and last year
a US subsidiary was found guilty of running a money-laundering operation.
BNL's Atlanta branch made Dollars 3bn (Pounds 1.7bn) of loan commitments to
Iraq between 1987 and 1989 which were partly used for buying weapons
equipment, leading to the start of criminal proceeedings earlier this year.
At present 81 per cent of foreign banks choose state supervisors for their
US branches and the legislation would require foreign banks to obtain
federal approval.
Most other countries, including Britain, require approval by the central
bank for operations by overseas-owned banks.
In detail, the legislation would require prior federal approval before a
foreign bank can begin operating in the US, and set clear standards for
permitting and denying foreign banks to enter the US, including access to
information about the foreign bank to enforce compliance with US laws and
requiring that the foreign bank be subject to consolidated regulation and
supervision in its home country.
</TEXT>
<PUB>The Financial Times
</PUB>
<PAGE>
London Page 3
</PAGE>
