<HEADLINE>
FT  10 MAY 91 / Armenia is warned to curb guerrillas
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JOHN LLOYD
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   MOSCOW
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
SOVIET military chiefs yesterday warned the pro-independence government of
the Soviet republic of Armenia to curb guerrilla attacks on Soviet personnel
by Armenian armed bands, writes John Lloyd in Moscow.
Mr Arshot Manuchurian, the republic's interior minister, responded by saying
he could not control the guerrillas, who were retaliating against 'bloody
acts' by Soviet soldiers.
Soviet and Azerbaijani troops fired on and occupied two more villages
yesterday; a third avoided an attack by surrendering its weapons.
The military's warning is aimed at what Soviet forces have identified as a
widespread formation of guerrilla groups along the republic's border with
Azerbaijan, with which it is locked in conflict over control of the
Armenian-inhabited enclave of Nagorno Karabakh, in Azerbaijan.
</TEXT>
