<HEADLINE>
FT  10 MAY 91 / OFT seeks power to probe cartels
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By CHARLES LEADBEATER, Industrial Editor
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
A DEMAND for tougher powers to investigate and impose penalties on cartels
came yesterday from Sir Gordon Borrie, director-general of the Office of
Fair Trading.
It was the second time this week that Sir Gordon had criticised the
government's approach to competition policy.
On Tuesday he told a parliamentary select committee that the policy of Mr
Peter Lilley, the trade and industry secretary who has referred bids by
state-owned groups to the Monopolies and Mergers Commission, was in
disarray.
Sir Gordon wants to be allowed to impose fines of up to 10 per cent of
turnover on companies operating cartels.
He also wants the government to broaden the OFT's powers to investigate
cartels which operate within Britain. This would allow the OFT to match
within the UK the European Commission's power to investigate cartels
involving trade within the EC.
Sir Gordon told a conference on regulation organised by the Institute of
Economic Affairs: 'My officials accompany their counterparts from the EC
when they mount raids in Britain and come back telling me how useful wider
investigative powers would be.'
He said it was unfortunate there was no sign of legislation on the issue
even though the government had committed itself to such a measure in a White
Paper on competition policy in July 1989.
Sir Gordon hopes that a commitment to strengthen the OFT's powers to
investigate cartels will be included in a forthcoming speech by Mr Lilley in
which he plans to clarify the government's approach to competition policy.
Sir Gordon told the conference that the pace of regulatory reform over the
past 12 years - with the creation of powerful regulatory bodies to oversee
privatised telecommunications, gas, electricity and water utilities - had
created a patchwork of agencies and regulatory instruments.
He raised doubts about the effectiveness of self-regulatory bodies under the
Financial Services Act. The procedure under which he reported to the trade
and industry secretary was a 'special, awkward and peculiar regime'.
He said there was a risk regulations designed to protect investors were
counter-productive because they imposed heavy costs on a dwindling number of
independent financial advisers.
Regulators confer, Page 8
</TEXT>
