<HEADLINE>
FT  10 MAY 91 / FT Law Report: Director must come to court
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By RACHEL DAVIES, Barrister
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
IN RE SEAGULL MANUFACTURING CO LTD
Chancery Division: Mr Justice Mummery: April 30 1991
A DIRECTOR of an insolvent company in compulsory liquidation can be ordered
by the court to attend for public examination as to the company's affairs,
irrespective of his nationality and notwithstanding that he resides out of
the jurisdiction; and, at the court's discretion, he can be served with the
public examination order at his foreign residence.
Mr Justice Mummery so held when allowing an appeal by the Official Receiver
from Mr Registrar Pimm's decision setting aside an order for public
examination of Mr Colin John Slinn, director of Seagull Manufacturing Co
Ltd, and an order for service of a copy of that order on Mr Slinn in
Alderney.
HIS LORDSHIP said that Seagull, an English private company, carried on the
business of computer utility organisation from a registered office in
Dorchester.
Mr Slinn was a director from January 27 1986 to July 3 1988 and was the
tenant of the Dorchester premises. He did not deny that he was a British
subject, but he claimed that from January 1979 until July 1986 he resided
and was domiciled in the Isle of Man, and that since July 1986 he had been
resident and domiciled in Alderney, Channel Islands.
Seagull was being wound up by the court on the ground of public interest,
following a Department of Trade and Industry enquiry. It was alleged that
Seagull was insolvent. The estimated claims exceeded Pounds 2m.
Since April 4 1990, when the compulsory winding-up order was made, the
Official Receiver had unsuccessfully attempted to persuade Mr Slinn to
submit a statement of affairs and to co-operate by providing information
required in the winding-up.
On July 17 1990, on the application of the Official Receiver, Mr Registrar
Buckley (1) ordered Mr Slinn to attend the Royal Courts of Justice on
September 25 for public examination; and (2) ordered service of a copy of
the public examination order at Mr Slinn's address in Alderney.
On September 25 Mr Registrar Pimm set aside both orders on the ground that
they were made without jurisdiction, since Mr Slinn was in Alderney at the
material time.
The Official Receiver appealed on the ground that on their true
construction, section 133 of the Insolvency Act 1986 and rule 12.2 of the
Insolvency Rules 1986 empowered the court to order attendance of a British
subject who had been an officer of an English company in compulsory
winding-up, and to give leave to serve a public examination order on him,
notwithstanding his residence abroad.
Section 133 provided that in a winding-up by the court the Official Receiver
might apply for public examination of 'any person who (a) is or has been an
officer of the company'. Rule 4.211(1) of the Insolvency Rules provided that
after a public examination order was made 'a copy of the court's order shall
. . . be served on that person'.
Rule 12.12(3) provided that for purposes of insolvency proceedings, the
court might order service of process or court order 'on a person who is not
in England and Wales'.' Insolvency proceedings' meant any proceedings under
the Act or the Rules (rule 13.7).
There was a general rule of statutory construction that English legislation
was primarily territorial in effect.
In applying the territoriality rule the court must enquire as to the person
in respect of whom Parliament was legislating. In Clark v Oceanic
Contractors (1983) 2 AC 130, 152C Lord Wilberforce formulated the relevant
question as 'Who is within the legislative grasp or intendment of the
statute under consideration?'
In re Tucker (1990) Ch 148 the Court of Appeal held that section 25 of the
Bankruptcy Act 1914, which empowered the court to require attendance of the
debtor or 'any person' for private examination, did not assert a
jurisdiction over British subjects resident abroad. Lord Justice Dillon
rejected a contention that 'any person' in section 25 meant any person in
the world, or any British subject anywhere in the world.
Ultimately, however, the question as to who were the persons with respect to
whom Parliament was presumed to be legislating must turn on the language,
context and purpose of section 133.
The 1986 Act provisions for private examination of a bankrupt were in
sections 366 and 367. Section 367(3) provided that the court might order
examination in or outside the UK of 'any person who if within the
jurisdiction would be liable to be summoned under section 366'. In Tucker
Lord Justice Dillon said of equivalent wording in section 25(6) of the 1914
Act that it 'carries inevitably the connotation' that if the person was not
in England he was not liable to be brought before the court.
There was little doubt that on the authority of Tucker sections 366 and 367
were subject to the same territorial qualification as section 25 of the 1914
Act.
Sections 236 and 237 of the 1986 Act conferred a similar power to order
private examination of a company officer.
It was submitted for Mr Slinn that in the light of those provisions it was
unlikely that Parliament intended section 133 to apply to a person out of
the jurisdiction.
The section 133 public examination provisions were not territorially limited
in the same way as the private examination provisions of sections 236, 237,
366 and 367.
The private examination provisions were different from the section 133
provisions in two important respects.
First, the power to summon persons for private examination extended to a
much wider class than for public examination.
The power to summon for private examination applied not only to any officer
of the company or the bankrupt, but also to any person who might have in his
possession property of the company or bankrupt, or might be indebted to the
company or bankrupt. It even extended to any person who might be able to
give information concerning the company or bankrupt.
The second important difference was that the private examination sections
contained express provisions which conclusively and inevitably connoted that
if the person was not in England he was not liable to be brought before the
English court. Such provision was conspicuously absent from section 133.
It was more appropriate to compare the section 133 provisions with public
examination provisions relating to bankrupts, than with private examination
provisions.
The relevant provisions for public examination of a bankrupt were now
contained in section 290 of the 1986 Act. The power to order public
examination of the bankrupt was not confined to British subjects or other
persons present or resident in England (see definition of 'debtor', section
265).
The public examination provisions relating to bankrupts were similar in
three respects to the section 133 provisions.
First, the court might only order public examination of the bankrupt.
Similarly in the case of a winding up, under section 133 the court might
only order public examination of a person who had voluntarily participated
in a specified capacity in the affairs of the company.
Second, the court had no discretion to refuse to direct a public examination
in the case of a bankrupt or a winding-up, if the application was duly made
in accordance with the relevant sub-section (sections 290(3) and 133(3)).
Third, neither the provisions relating to public examination of a bankrupt
nor those relating to public examination in a winding-up contained any
provision similar to that in section 25(6) of the 1914 Act, now in sections
367(3) and 237(3) of the 1986 Act.
Section 133 on its true construction plainly implied that it applied to all
who fell within a class of persons specified in section 133(1), whether or
not they were British subjects, and whether or not they were within the
jurisdiction at the relevant time.
Parliament had legislated for public examination of persons who had acted in
one capacity or another in relation to the affairs of a company which was
either liable to be, or was being, wound up by the English court under
English law.
One would expect such persons to be 'within the legislative grasp, or
intendment' of section 133, whether or not they were in England and whether
or not they could be served with a summons in England.
The appeal was allowed. Mr Registrar Buckley's orders were restored.
For the Official Receiver: Nigel Davis (Treasury solicitor).
For Mr Slinn: Robin Hollington (Vance Harris, Crowborough).
</TEXT>
<PUB>The Financial Times
</PUB>
