<HEADLINE>
FT  10 MAY 91 / World Stock Markets: Calm returns after volatile months -
Taiwan led emerging market gains in April
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JACQUELINE MOORE
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
CALM returned to most of the world's emerging markets in April, after two
months of diverse and wide movements in the country indices. Only four of
the 17 developing markets covered by the International Finance Corporation,
part of the World Bank, showed double-digit percentage changes on the month
in dollar terms.
Of these four, Taiwan and Mexico moved sharply higher, while Turkey and
Greece were the worst performers.
Mr Peter Bristowe of Hoare Govett comments: 'Taiwan has had a good run, but
there have been ups and downs within that. The market could now be at the
peak of its rally, because calls on liquidity are growing.' He cites the
announcement this week of the flotation of part of the government's stake in
Chinese Petroleum, and a government bond issue to raise TDollars 45bn
(USDollars 1.65bn).
Last month's optimism was based on the government's plans to raise
infrastructure spending over the next few years, and the potential
establishment of direct trading links between Taiwan and mainland China,
says Mr Bristowe.
April's other winner, Mexico, has been rising steadily for most of this
year. Baring Securities provided a long list of reasons in its Latin
American summary in mid-April. 'Factors contributing to the market's strong
performance,' said Baring, 'include improved company financial results, the
fall in interest rates, the massive inflow of foreign investment, the
imminent bank privatisations and the sale of the remaining shares in Telmex,
combined with widespread optimism about the country's economic prospects.'
Optimism about the free trade agreement with the US and strong demand for
shares of oil company Telmex in the New York and Mexican markets also lifted
the index. Telmex has risen 91 per cent over the first four months of 1991.
The picture was less bright in Europe. Turkey continued to be the year's
most depressed emerging market.
Mr Kaya Didman of Turk Economi Bank in Istanbul says there are several
reasons for the decline. In the last 2 1/2 months, he says, short-term
interest rates have risen sharply, with overnight rates of 100 per cent,
against about 60 per cent in the previous 10 to 12 months. This is an
indication of the country's severe cash shortage, which has forced the banks
 -the main institutional investors in Turkey - to sell equities.
There has also been a fast depreciation of the Turkish lira against the
dollar and other major currencies, causing retail investors to turn to the
foreign exchange market. The sharp fluctuations in the exchange rate, in
turn, have produced volatile movements in the stock market.
Investors have also been beset by economic and political worries, says Mr
Didman, although he points out that the fundamentals look good, with
corporate earnings growth of 10 per cent expected this year.
The decline in Greece came as no surprise. The New York-based Kleiman
International Consultants in its latest Emerging Markets Briefing says:
'After the 'casino euphoria' of the past year, investors have come to
recognise that the country's deep-seated economic difficulties will not be
resolved so quickly or easily and setbacks are inevitable.'
THE Sao Paulo Bovespa index in Brazil jumped 5.3 per cent by midday
yesterday to 74,014, up 3,728. The rise followed the naming of a new economy
minister.
</TEXT>
