<HEADLINE>
FT  10 MAY 91 / Commodities and Agriculture: Brazilian tin factory closure
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By VICTORIA GRIFFITH
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   SAO PAOLO
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
ESTANBRAS, the Brazilian tin group, is closing its Minas Gerais factory
because the government has forbidden the company to export its product.
The factory, which went into operation last year, was capable of producing
100 tonnes of tin each month. Since domestic demand is very small, the
prohibition on exports soon left the group with few customers.
In an attempt to push Brazil's small-time miners out of the country's tin
reserves, the government last December prohibited the export of tin taken
from illegal mines. Estanbras purchases its tin from 'garimpeiros' who do
not possess mining rights.
'The prohibition of exports by companies without mining rights means big
groups like Paranapanema may soon hold a monopoly on the sector,' said Jose
Nivaldo Gomes Cordeiro, director of Estanbras.
The group has sent away its 80 employees. Thousands contracted are out of
work.
Mr Cordeiro said there is hope that Estanbras will re-open the plant, if it
succeeds in negotiations with the government to obtain mining rights for the
area.
