<PROFILE>_AN-BEJAXADIFT</PROFILE>
<DATE>910510
</DATE>
<HEADLINE>
FT  10 MAY 91 / International Capital Markets: Fox attempts to build on
property futures - The launch of a derivative in an area where others have
failed
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By VANESSA HOULDER
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
YESTERDAY'S launch of a UK property futures market by the London Futures and
Options Exchange (Fox) marks an attempt to create the world's first
successful such market - previous attempts in Chicago, France and Sidney
having failed.
The market allows developers and banks to reduce their exposure to market
movements; traders to speculate without buying and selling buildings; and
investors to switch their funds in and out of property more easily. Also,
houseowners and developers can hedge against fluctuations in mortgage rates.
Fox is introducing four separate but interrelated contracts, covering
commercial property, commercial rents, residential property and mortgage
interest rates.
They are based on a clutch of property indices: the IPD monthly capital
value and rent growth index (based on the valuation of 47 institutional
property funds), the Nationwide Anglia house price index, and the London Fox
mortgage interest rate index.
Someone hoping to make money from the new market has to take a view on the
accuracy of the consensus of where the indices are heading, which will be
reflected in the price of the futures. A trader will, for instance, profit
from buying futures, if prices rise by more than was expected when the
contract was taken out.
One of the main attractions (and risks) of using the futures market is that
contracts are highly geared, so only a small down-payment is needed to gain
exposure to the market. Another attraction is that transaction costs are far
lower than in the direct property market: Fox calculates average costs of
0.07 per cent for t for property.
Fox has appointed eight designated brokers, including Dean Witter, Goldman
Sachs, James Capel and Prudential-Bache. The contracts are traded
electronically, so the broker types the customer's order into the trading
screen. It is then automatically passed on to Fox's matching, allocation,
confirmation and clearing systems.
The contracts, which expire every three months during a three-year period,
are settled in cash. Their settlement is guaranteed by the International
Commodities Clearing House.
Fox's initiative has attracted intense interest and scepticism in roughly
equal measures. Marketing seminars about the futures launch have been well
attended, but many potential users say they would prefer to see the market
establish itself rather than commit funds straight away.
One difficulty for Fox is getting the message across. It is not easy to
market a new financial technique to an industry as large and diffuse as
property, which has not been eager to adopt financial innovations in the
past.
Fox has complained that institutions are as deaf to the virtues of a new
risk avoidance strategy as they are risk averse to new markets. Moreover,
surveyors, whose clients are potential users of property futures, appear to
be unfamiliar and uncomfortable with the futures market. 'A lot of them have
said they are going to wait and see,' says Mr Jon Payne, business
development director of Fox.
London Fox may also be handicapped by the mood of caution in the property
industry. Few developments are planned and investors appear to lack
enthusiasm to expand the range of their operations.
That said, it is possible that the uncertain climate in the property
industry will give the property futures market just the kickstart it needs.
The recent collapse in property values may have helped the cause of the
property futures by undermining the market's past claim of stability.
The usual consensus in the industry (which has led to worries that it would
be a one-way market) has been shattered - for the moment. For example, at a
seminar held by Fox, the number of investment surveyors who reckoned that
the market value would increase by the end of the year was nicely matched by
the number who thought it would fall.
The large divergence of views should help create a healthy distribution of
buyers and sellers. Fox may also be helped by the illiquidity in the market
at present. An institution that believes the property market has hit bottom
may wish to lock into existing prices with futures, rather than risk a rapid
price rise.
However, the main criticism about the contracts is that they measure the
average performance of the property market, which blurs the considerable
difference in behaviour between different sectors and regions. Some
institutions, such as Scottish Amicable, say that only when this problem is
resolved will it be interested in property futures.
The possibility of using more narrowly-focused indices was dismissed because
of the likely lack of liquidity. Instead, Fox hopes that financial
institutions will help by offering tailor-made policies for individual
portfolios, whose aggregate risk can be offset using the futures market.
As the market kicks off, Fox is anxious to see how much momentum can be
built in the market's early stages. None the less, a slow start will not be
disastrous, thanks to the relatively low costs of screen-based trading. 'The
start-up period will not take one day or one month,' says Mr Payne. 'We can
manage three years quite easily.'
</TEXT>
<PUB>The Financial Times
</PUB>
