<HEADLINE>
FT  10 MAY 91 / International Capital Markets: Prices indicate values to
bottom out in spring
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By VANESSA HOULDER, Property Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THE decline in commercial property values is expected to bottom out next
spring, according to the prices posted in the first day of the London
Futures and Options Exchange property futures market, writes Vanessa
Houlder, Property Correspondent.
Prices indicated that the Investment Property Databank capital value index
would fall 2.5 per cent between March 1991 and March 1992, but then rise
steadily.
Volume was three-quarters of that expected. There was little business in the
commercial rental values, house price and residential mortgage rate
contracts. By the end of the day contracts valued at Pounds 15m had changed
hands.
Mr Jon Payne, business development director, said he was 'pretty happy'. But
Mr Tim Bolton-Carter of James Capel, a designated broker for the market,
said that trading had been 'a little disappointing'. Business was
concentrated in the commercial value contracts, which accounted for 126 of
the 152 lots traded. Most of the activity was in the contracts relating to
the coming year.
Fox said trading was by a range of brokers, end users and traders dealing on
their own account. One broker said that the slow trading reflected the
conservative nature of the property profession.
The thinly-traded commercial rental value contracts implied a decline of
nearly 3.5 per cent in the next year.
Futures on the Nationwide Anglia house price index also showed a bearish
trend to September this year, although they predicted a rise in house prices
by December.
Mortgage futures prices indicated an average building society mortgage rate
of just less than 12 per cent in December this year.
</TEXT>
