<HEADLINE>
FT  10 MAY 91 / International Company News: Sara Lee snaps up Linter
Textiles
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By MARK WESTFIELD
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   SYDNEY
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
LINTER Textiles Corporation, Australia's largest clothing and textiles
group, once owned by entrepreneur Mr Abraham Goldberg, has been snapped up
by Sara Lee of the US after the collapse of the proposed sale to Merrill
Lynch Partners.
Mr Lindsay Maxsted, Linter receiver and manager of KPMG Peat Marwick, had
been trying to close the sale to Merrill Lynch since February. The deal had
all but collapsed last week with Merrill Lynch having trouble raising the
finance to complete when Sara Lee suddenly came in with a higher offer.
Merrill Lynch had managed to bring down the price of the 10 Linter
businesses from ADollars 230m (Dollars 179.60m) to ADollars 215m before its
bid ran into difficulty. The sale price to Sara Lee was undisclosed, but is
understood to be ADollars 220m.
Sara Lee, which produces hosiery, underwear and knitwear as well as food
products, made an unsuccessful attempt early this year to buy just the
Hilton Hosiery business out of Linter.
The US company already has a substantial presence in Australia with its
Kitchens of Sara Lee foods business and ownership of the drugs and household
products group Nicholas Kiwi. It can now include Linter's well-known brands,
which include Bradmill Textiles, Formfit, Hilton, King G, Kortex, Pelaco and
Stubbies.
Contracts for the sale were signed yesterday, and final settlement is
expected on May 31. The deal requires the approval of the Victorian Supreme
Court and the Foreign Investment Review Board.
When tenders were called for the businesses late last year, Linter was
estimated to earn about ADollars 55m before interest and tax for this
financial year. This forecast has been revised downwards as the Australian
economy goes into recession.
The group will also be adversely affected by the federal government's
decision in March to eliminate quota protection for the textiles and
clothing industry next year, two years earlier than foreshadowed in the
government's seven-year textiles, clothing and footwear plan.
In his statement yesterday, Mr Maxsted said Sara Lee had indicated it would
continue the Linter business as 'operating entities'.
'Towards this end, Sara Lee is prepared to make significant investment to
expand key businesses in the Linter group,' Mr Maxsted said.
Creditors are expecting a pay out of between 40 cents and 46 cents in the
dollar.
</TEXT>
