<HEADLINE>
FT  10 MAY 91 / International Company News: Saffa bids for box-board
supremacy - The plans of Italy's Bonomi family
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By HAIG SIMONIAN
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
AFTER an absence of some years, the name of Bonomi, one of northern Italy's
leading business families, has been edging back into the headlines after a
string of deals by Saffa, the quoted packaging group 52 per cent owned by Mr
Carlo Bonomi.
Does this signal the first signs of a comeback by what was once a household
name in Italian business circles? 'Definitely not,' says Mr Bonomi. But
while denying that Saffa is the vehicle for his return to the mainstream of
Italian business, he makes no secret of the fact that he would like the
group, already Europe's third biggest producer of box-board, to expand much
further.
It is the concentration on box-board, the material from which cigarette
packets and much of the packaging for food products is made, that lay behind
last February's complex deal between Milan-based Saffa and Torras Hostench,
the Spanish industrial holding group controlled by the Kuwait Investment
Office.
In one of the biggest asset swaps in Spanish industrial history, the two
companies exchanged a variety of paper-industry interests, giving Torras
Hostench control of the Spanish paper market as a result.
In return for the speciality papers business of Sarrio, the Spanish paper
maker of which Saffa had only just gained control, Mr Bonomi's company
received 4 per cent of Ebro, the sugar and foods division of Torras
Hostench, 9.9 per cent of Torras Papel, its paper division, 6 per cent of
Prima Immobiliaria, Spain's richest property group, a large box-board
production plant and Pta10bn (Dollars 94.33m) in cash.
The move surprised analysts, who had followed with approval Saffa's
step-by-step courtship of Sarrio, one of Spain's biggest paper groups, which
had led to majority control last December.
The decision to part company triggered particular surprise as Saffa had only
recently merged its own speciality paper interests - which form its second
main line of business after box-board - with those of the Spanish company,
which had assumed overall control of the sector.
Mr Bonomi says he understands the market's astonishment. But he rejects
speculation that the disposal of the special papers business, coming so soon
after Saffa gained control of Sarrio, was a purely opportunistic step in
response to an unusually generous offer from the Kuwaitis.
Rather, the decision reflected Saffa's policy of concentrating on box-board
following the collapse of much wider plans with Feldmuhle Nobel, the German
paper group which also had a stake in Sarrio, to set up two joint ventures
covering special papers and box-board.
Under the strategy worked out between Saffa and Feldmuhle, the Germans would
have taken management control of the two companies' pooled interests in
special papers, while Saffa would have been responsible for their joint
box-board activities. However, the plan was abandoned when Stora, the
Swedish paper group, acquired Feldmuhle.
Left on its own, Saffa lacked the resources for the heavy capital
investments necessary to keep ahead in both businesses, leading to the
decision to shed special papers business, Mr Bonomi explains.
By providing an additional plant, the Spanish deal has already allowed Saffa
to consolidate its position.
Although Saffa, including associated companies, only produces around 740,000
tonnes a year, Mr Bonomi highlights the fact that it is the second biggest
user in Europe, after Mayr-Melnhof of Austria, of an extremely high
proportion of recycled paper.
Some 99 per cent of Saffa's output is based on recycled products, he notes.
That has become increasingly important as a marketing tool, especially with
big consumer goods producers, which have grown increasingly sensitive to
environmental concerns in recent years.
Mr Bonomi does not expect Saffa to make any further big acquisitions on the
box-board side, following the Spanish realignment. However, further small
purchases in some southern European markets are not to be ruled out, he
hints.
Meanwhile, the company will push ahead with its strategy of expanding beyond
box-board into value-added services like converting, the business -
traditionally done by specialists - of cutting and printing raw box-board to
a customer's specifications.
Packaging machinery is another area for future growth, particularly as
medium-sized Italian engineering companies, many clustered around Bologna,
are among the world's leaders in the field.
Saffa has already made a number of acquisitions. However, equipment
manufacturing still accounts for only about L100bn of the group's sales of
L1,050bn (Dollars 818m) last year, with speciality papers making up L400bn
and box-board around L500bn.
The disposal of the specialist papers business means those figures will
change sharply this year, notes Mr Bonomi. The workforce has already shrunk
to about 2,700. In 1989, the group made L40.3bn after tax. Figures for 1990
will not be released until May.
Meanwhile, Saffa is also aiming to work its property interests harder thanks
to the opening provided by the Sarrio deal into the Spanish property market.
Mr Bonomi aims to combine the group's Italian and Spanish property
activities, which include one of the biggest vineyards in Sardinia, into a
new subsidiary, which will supervise growth in the property field.
That in itself would mark something of a return to first principles for the
Bonomi family, much of whose wealth has been based on Italian property
interests.
</TEXT>
