<HEADLINE>
FT  10 MAY 91 / International Company News: Italian insurer advances 1.2% to
L137.9bn
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By HAIG SIMONIAN
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   MILAN
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
RIUNIONE Adriatica di Sicurta (RAS), Italy's second biggest private-sector
insurer, which is controlled by Allianz of Germany, improved group net
profits by 1.2 per cent to L137.9bn (Dollars 108.32m) last year, writes Haig
Simonian in Milan.
Group premium income rose by 7.7 per cent to L5,849bn. Premiums at parent
company level went up by 12.7 per cent to L2,844.7bn.
As in 1989, RAS's results are deceptive in that they fail to reflect the
steadily deteriorating underwriting position at many of Italy's big
insurance companies owing to rising claims following a period of strong
growth in the number of policies written, notably on the motor side.
Mr Umberto Zanni, chairman, said underwriting losses rose to L180bn last
year from around L130bn-L140bn in 1989. By contrast, underwriting used to be
profitable as recently as the mid-1980s, but had deteriorated steadily
since, he noted. 'In 1990, the Italian market was the worst in the world'.
As in 1989, RAS had achieved its earnings through investment income, and
especially one-off capital gains on its extensive investment and property
portfolio.
Consequently, the company would once again be making a substantial transfer
of L53.2bn to extraordinary reserves, while keeping the dividend unchanged
at L300 and L360 for ordinary and savings shares respectively.
Mr Zanni said he hoped underwriting earnings would show improvement this
year.
San Paolo Finance, the investment banking arm of Istituto Bancario San Paolo
di Torino, raised net profits by 97 per cent to L20.9bn last year.
