<HEADLINE>
FT  10 MAY 91 / UK Company News: Kunick calls for Pounds 17.6m as profits
decline
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By DAVID CHURCHILL, Leisure Industries Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
KUNICK, the amusement machine and nursing homes group, is seeking Pounds
17.6m via a rights issue to help reduce gearing and to enable further
development of its core activities, although no acquisitions are planned.
The issue, underwritten by Samuel Montagu, is on a 2-for-9 basis at 33p per
share - a sharp discount on yesterday's closing price of 41 1/4 p, down 1
1/4 p on the day.
The details were announced along with the group's results for the half year
ended March 31 1991. These showed that pre-tax profits for the period had
fallen from Pounds 8m to Pounds 7.3m on turnover up from Pounds 50.69m to
Pounds 57.94m.
The main cause of the profits downturn was a sharp increase in interest
charges to Pounds 1.63m (Pounds 176,000).
Trading profits for the six months rose from Pounds 8.2m to Pounds 8.89m in
spite of what Mr Russell Smith, Kunick's chairman, yesterday described as
'extremely difficult trad-ing conditions in all divis-ions.'
The nursing homes operated by Kunick in the UK and France were now all fully
operational, but the sale of special serviced apartments in London for the
elderly and retirement housing in Harrogate continued to be held up by the
slump in the property market.
Mr Smith said that in spite of the depressed state of the pub trade, the
performance of the amusement machine business was strong.
In France, the amusement machine division was recovering after a difficult
first half.
The directors are adjusting the level of the interim and final dividends to
'reflect more accurately the pattern of annual profits.'
Therefore, they are raising the interim dividend from 0.6p to 0.8p and
intend to pay a final of at least 1.2p, keeping the total for the 12 months
at the same level as the previous year's 2p.
COMMENT
Kunick's figures were a shade disappointing to the company's strong City
following but not so bad for them to lose faith in the company's strategy of
turning amusement machine profits into the longer-term investment of nursing
homes for the elderly. Tight management control has kept the company on
course and the rights issue seems a sensible move, bringing gearing down to
about 36 per cent, and enabling management to develop some of its more
profitable activities. But the acquisition trail of the past looks likely to
be on hold for another year or so yet. Full year figures are being scaled
down to about Pounds 17m, putting the shares on a prospective p/e of under
10.
</TEXT>
