<HEADLINE>
FT  10 MAY 91 / UK Company News: Recession forces API into loss
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By DAVID OWEN
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
SEVERE recessionary conditions across a range of markets pushed API Group,
formerly Associated Paper Industries, into loss in the six months ended
March 30.
Including Pounds 570,000 (Pounds 90,000) of exceptional charges, relating
mostly to provisions for re-organisation and redundancy costs, the pre-tax
loss totalled Pounds 849,000 on turnover of Pounds 29.55m. On a
like-for-like basis, interim profits in 1990 amounted to Pounds 817,000 on
turnover of Pounds 31.81m.
Despite this, the company is maintaining its interim dividend at 2.75p. The
shares dipped 1p to 107p.
Mr Peter Armitage, chairman, said that 'the single greatest adverse
influence' on the results was Henry &amp; Leigh Slater, the coated and laminated
board unit, 'whose customers have been susceptible to the combined effects
of the recession and the Gulf war'.
'We are not despondent,' Mr Armitage said. The group, which recently lost
its managing director following a disagreement over strategy, now has three
divisions, encompassing image enhancement products, converted film and paper
products and heating and ventilating systems.
API is responding to the economic climate by lowering its cost base,
necessitating 50-60 lay-offs, and by accelerating its just-in-time
programme. It is also in the process of recruiting a new chief executive and
two new non-executive directors.
There was a Pounds 131,000 extraordinary item for the costs of improving
emission control at the group's Dry Print business in the US. Mr Armitage
said that the company was 'opening negotiations' with Dry Print's previous
owner for the recovery of some of this money.
Losses per share were 2.7p, against earnings of 2.5p.
</TEXT>
