<HEADLINE>
FT  10 MAY 91 / UK Company News: Exceptional but hardly extraordinary - The
reactions to the ASB's draft proposals for P&amp;L accounts
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By DAVID WALLER
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
IT IS NEARLY a month since the Accounting Standards Board published its
working draft on the restructuring of company profit and loss accounts.
First comments on the draft rules had to be submitted by Tuesday and the
Board is now considering what modifications will have to be made before the
proposals are reissued as a formal exposure draft.
The original document envisaged a radical reworking of the profit and loss
account.
If adopted lock, stock and barrel as a formal financial reporting standard,
as the ASB's rules are to be known, companies would have to provide far
greater details of the source of income and expenditure than at present.
They would also have to publish a prominent statement showing movements on
reserves.
Furthermore, they would not enjoy the same flexibility over non-recurring
items as they do now. The distinction between extraordinary or exceptional
would in effect be removed, and almost all unusual costs or revenues would
have to be taken 'above the line', affecting earnings per share.
Companies would also have to provide details of so-called discretionary
expenditure, such as advertising and research and development.
According to Prof David Tweedie, ASB chairman, the responses received by the
Tuesday deadline were broadly in favour of the Board's plans.
However there is much muttering in the accountancy world about the
complexity of the proposals, a feeling shared by the technical committee of
the 100 Group of top UK finance directors which met earlier this week to
formulate its response to the ASB's initiative.
Their worries focus on the appearance of the new P&amp;L account. There would be
no fewer than eight columns, showing income and expenditure coming from
businesses bought during the year, businesses sold, and businesses owned
throughout the year, plus a total figure, for each of this year and the
prior year.
There are also worries about the complicated language of the draft rules. It
is highly theoretical in tone and even technically literate accountants
admit to being baffled at such concepts as 'components of comprehensive
income'.
Despite these objections, a spirit of compromise is in the air. There is
none of the fierce confrontation between industry and standards-setters
which characterised the 1989 debate over the draft rules on accounting for
goodwill, issued by the Accounting Standards Committee, the ASB's
predecessor.
There is broad agreement among accountants, industrialists and institutional
investors that fundamental reforms are required.
'Most of what the ASB is proposing is directly relevant to their declared
objective of getting a better measure of a company's achieved performance,'
says Mr Nigel Stapleton, chairman of the 100 Group's technical committee and
finance director of Reed International.
'We support the principle of greater disclosure which underlies much of what
the ASB is doing. We do, however, have some reservations about the details
of the working draft.
'The 100 Group believes that the document provides a basis for discussion,
but there are some areas where it is not completely to clear to us that the
issues have been fully worked out. We hope that in a number of respects the
exposure draft looks quite different to this working document.'
Stapleton argues that there should be greater flexibility over the
presentation of the new P&amp;L account. In principle he has no objection to the
rule requiring a detailed analysis of income and expenditure. His doubts
centre on the usefulness of such information once it goes beyond a certain
level of detail.
He says that what details there are should be relegated to the notes to the
accounts, rather than clutter up the face of the P&amp;L account. He thinks that
this should retain a degree of simplicity for the sake of greater
usefulness.
In addition he has doubts about the thinking behind the requirement to
publish discretionary expenditure.
The proposals which have attracted most attention from brokers and other
analysts are those relating to extraordinaries and exceptionals.
Stapleton is in favour of a general tightening up of the rules. However he
adds: 'It is going a bit too far to forget about the distinction altogether
as it would denigrate the earnings per share figure as a reasonable proxy of
a company's basic performance.'
The reason for the interest is clear, the two items account for a
substantial part of UK companies total profits. If the costs of
restructuring a business after a takeover, or the proceeds of a disposal,
are all taken above the line reported profits will look very different.
Just how different is evident from a number of pieces of research published
in the last month. P-E International, a consultancy firm, has calculated
that overall balance of extraordinary charges in the UK's top 250 companies
amounts to a negative Pounds 2.9bn in the last financial year. Under the ASB
proposals this would all be set off against reported earnings.
At Goldman Sachs, the US investment house, Dr Sushil Wadwhani has calculated
that companies in the FT-500 Index record extraordinary items in three out
of five years on average, scotching the notion that extraordinary items are
really that unusual. He suggests that share prices may be depressed as a
result and argues that the new rules would reduce productivity growth.
The essence of his argument is that the stock market is fixated on reported
earnings per share. Companies would be reluctant to incur necessary
restructuring expenditure because the costs would have to be taken above the
line.
The authors of Company Reporting, a monthly review of financial reporting
practice, have looked at the latest accounts of 700 quoted UK companies. Of
these, 53 per cent have classified certain items as extraordinary, that is
taken below the line. More than half the items related to reorganisation and
business disposals.
'If the changes mooted by the ASB result in a new accounting standard, it
will have a resounding impact on financial reporting.'*
The scene is set for some behind-the-scenes horse-trading. The more the
formal exposure draft resembles last month's document, the more resounding
the impact on UK financial reporting.
If there are no changes at all, the finance directors are likely to be less
polite than they are being this week.
*Company Reporting May 1991, published by Company Reporting Ltd., 68 Dundas
St., Edinburgh EH3 6QZ. Tel: 031-558-1400.
</TEXT>
<PUB>The Financial Times
</PUB>
<PAGE>
London Page 19 Photograph David Tweedie, responses broadly in favour
(Omitted).
</PAGE>
</DOC>
